column15: Algeria has the ambitious goal to add 22GW of renewables generation capacity by 2030, with the aim of saving 300 billion m3 of its gas reserves as a result. The targets are broken down by sector and include a first goal of 4.5GW by 2020 that the country is unlikely to meet. The main issue around Algerias renewables target lays in the governments high upfront local content expectations which the nascent domestic sector is not yet ready to fulfil, and the uncertainties around the financial guarantees for developers. Algerias announcement of a first tender for 4GW of renewables, which would have allowed it to meet its 2020 objectives in one go, was stymied by the fact that it is not willing to back down on these local content expectations the domestic industry is not yet ready to fulfil.

The country aims to add 800MW of renewable energy capacity (500MW of biomass, 100MW of solar, 100MW of wind and 100MW of mini-hydro) by 2025, under the governments energy strategy "Viso Angola Energia. Most of Angolas electricity demand is met by large hydro. In 2017, the technology accounted for 54% of its 4.7GW of installed capacity and three-quarters of the 10.5TWh generated that year.  The $23-billion energy strategy for 2018-25 aims to reach 9.9GW of total capacity, and boost electricity access rates from around 35% in 2017 (rural areas: 16%) to 60%. By this time, natural gas is to meet a fifth of generation, hydro 64% and 8% from other renewables. Of the 9.9GW of new build, just under a third will be developed through public-private partnerships. Angola has no substantial incentives such as feed-in tariffs or auctions to promote renewable energy deployment.

While Benin has no clean-energy policies in place, February 2018 saw the creation of the UC/PDER, the so-called Entity in Charge of Renewable Energy Policy Development. This is attached to the presidency and will draft the countrys renewable energy law and structure the sector over the coming 18 months. In parallel, the U.S. Millennium Challenge Account II is on a four-year mission to help the Beninese government develop a new energy framework for the country. MCA II plans to increase local electricity generation by 46MW, reducing energy dependence. The program also aims to modernize distribution infrastructure by building new sub-stations, upgrading to higher voltage and building new lines. Finally, the program is driving off-grid electrification efforts.

Historically, Botswana has lacked the legal framework and incentives to develop its renewable energy industry  the National Energy Policy has remained in draft form since October 2009. The two open tenders for a 100MW solar plant and 20 small hybrid off-grid plants are quite ambitious, especially considering they would represent almost 10% of the total installed capacity of the country in a single project. These tenders are also a first for the sub-Saharan nation in terms of scale. The only operational renewable project is 1.3MW. Previous experiences raise questions about the reliability of the process: a tender in 2015 failed to move forward after attracting some 118 bids. The import and tax incentives have played little role in the development of the sector as they apply to a wide range of manufacturing goods and dont make any special provision for the renewables industry, besides, awareness of these exemptions is low.

Burkina Faso has a limited clean energy policy landscape. There is no auction program, feed-in tariff or net metering scheme in place. Some tenders have been announced for small-scale solar projects, but there is no program with a schedule of future tenders. Burkina Faso does have tax exemptions on solar equipment, which seems to attract investment around the capital in Ouagadougou, where dozens of small businesses sell and install solar panels for small-scale use. Burkina Faso aims to have an energy mix with 50% renewables by 2025, up from 24% in 2018. This would require roughly 150MW of renewables to be commissioned by the deadline compared with the pipeline at the time of writing of one 10MW PV plant that has secured financing.

Burundi has committed unconditionally to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 3% compared to a business-as-usual scenario for 2030, as part of its nationally determined contribution. The focus of Burundis Electricity Law, last updated in 2015, is on rehabilitation of existing hydropower plants and distribution grids as well as the development of new hydro sites. The countrys rural electrification program is planned mainly around grid extensions and providing information on alternative energy sources affordable for low-income households. The only effective support for renewables developers in Burundi is that equipment benefits from import tariff exemptions. There are no fiscal incentives or other policy instruments such as feed-in tariffs. Auctions were held in 2013 and 2014 but these are not regular and there are no further rounds planned. There are no specific legal tools to discourage fossil fuels.

Cameroon has committed to secure 25% electricity generation from renewable sources by 2035, as part of its nationally determined contribution (NDC). In 2017, the share was less than 4.5%. The government aims to formalize this target through a renewable energy law, which would introduce a mandatory auction or tendering process, set renewable electricity purchase tariffs, and clarify the rules around the purchase of renewable electricity. No draft has been announced as of yet. The only effective support for renewables developers in Cameroon is that equipment benefits from VAT exemptions. Other fiscal incentives, such as import duty waivers, are not consistently implemented. The utility, Eneo, has begun to procure tenders for solar.

The Central African Republic has little in the way of implemented or upcoming clean energy policy. Despite the majority of electricity generation coming from hydro plants, there exists no clean energy targets to supplement or maintain these penetration levels. Additionally there are no implemented auctions, feed-in tariffs or other incentives. The electricity cost rates are unrealistically low, driven by the high proportion of the population living below the poverty line, unable to afford electricity, even in the cities. Such low rates means that not only are investors deterred from entering the space due to the low returns, but even the state-owned utility, Enerca, is in a poor financial state.

Chad has been slow off the blocks in setting up renewable energy incentives. Although no such legislation is currently in force, tax incentives and a law facilitating the sale of privately generated output are being debated by the national assembly. The government has not set a national target regarding renewable energy deployment. But developers have praised the current administrations commitment to building out production from clean power sources, pointing to the recent reinforcement of the Agency for the Development of Renewable Energy (ADER), whose bolstered remit encompasses facilitating land allocation and the signature of contracts.

The Republic of the Congo has neither implemented any legislation intended to promote clean energy nor set a specific target for renewables deployment. Clean energy is relegated to the margins of the policy-making agenda, as the sector focuses on stamping out illegal connections, managing the emergence of a new state utility and maximizing the countrys large hydro potential.

The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has done little to develop a clean energy policy, largely due to the political instability of the country following widespread conflict and civilian unrest. President Joseph Kabilas refusal to leave office since his term ended in December 2016 has led to outbreaks of violence and intimidation against protestors and members of the opposition, so development of new policies is not of the highest priority. The DRCs low energy requirement and dependence on hydropower is not conducive to the development of clean energy policy to encourage other renewables build. Tax incentives for renewable energy projects are the sole area where policy directly benefits the industry.

Cote d'Ivoire is aiming for 42% renewables generation by 2030 (including hydro), up from 20% in 2017. Although the target is ambitious, the country has not yet introduced any significant clean energy policies and is still far from its 2020 interim target, with only some thermal and hydro capacity installed. The government initiated some tenders in 2016 for two biomass and one solar project of 20-25MW each, and could support the creation of further rounds, if the first one is a success. Solar players also benefit from modest tax exemptions. Yet their activity is limited to self-consumption projects, such as the distribution of individual solar kits, as the current framework does not allow for more.

Eritrea aims for renewables to account for 70% of electricity generation by 2030, as part of its NDC, but does not yet have any enabling framework to bring it toward this goal. It also plans to improve power sector infrastructure to reduce transmission and distribution losses by at least 50% by the same year. One small-scale minigrid was commissioned in 2018 to power two towns, with international aid from the UNDP. A hybrid solar-diesel system is also operational as of 2018, but provides captive generation for a mining operation. There are no incentives for renewables developers, and very little transparency on existing regulations.

Ethiopia, Africa's fastest growing economy, already meets all of its electricity needs from renewable sources, and its generating capacity mix is mostly hydro. Ethiopia has plans to add another nearly 10GW of hydro and 3GW of other renewables by 2020. However, this ambitious target has not been accompanied by effective policy mechanisms. Ethiopia has tendered both wind and solar projects, including through an ongoing Scaling Solar tender, but in a lengthy process that has still not resulted in capacity being commissioned. The private sector has until now been involved in ad hoc negotiations for PPAs with Ethiopia Electric Power (EEP), the state-owned power producer. Ethiopia is overhauling its public-private partnership regulations in order to attract IPPs, though this process is still in its early stages. Without more concrete incentives, the country will fall short of its 2020 aims.

The government has a clean energy target of 500MW. While this was originally to be commissioned by 2020, it is now unlikely that this will be built before 2030. This is because the government undertook a program in 2017 to review all PPAs signed following the energy crisis in 2016.  Because it considered that these were overpriced and did not offer value to Ghanaians, it cancelled some of the PPAs and delayed all those for renewable energy projects until 2025 or 2030.

Guinea offers no renewables incentives. This partly results from the countrys abundance of rivers and the government determination to tap into an estimated 6GW of hydropower potential. With no installed renewables capacity to date, Guineas target to increase clean generation capacity to 30% by 2030 appears far off. Promising developments include the creation of a rural electrification agency and an independent regulator in 2017, as well as forthcoming amendments to the 1993 Electricity Law, which are tailored to encourage private participation in generation. Reforms geared toward IPPs will have to wait until national utility EDG emerges from private management  the four-year contract signed with Veolia expires in mid-2019.

Kenya is in the process of transiting its renewable energy policy from a feed-in tariff scheme launched in 2012 to an auction-based one. Under the feed-in tariff, the fixed tariff of $0.12/kWh for solar projects of 10-40MW has led to an oversupply in proposed sites. This surplus reduced the incentive to rush large projects to commissioning, and as of August 2018, the rate is no longer available. A draft bill to introduce the auction scheme passed in parliament in August, but the government has not clarified further details yet. The government plans to price tariffs for below 10MW solar projects in local currency although it is uncertain when it will take effect or if it will affect operational power plants.

The Lesotho Energy Policy (2015-2025) provides a strategy for the energy sector but has not been enacted into law, creating uncertainty over the status and plans for the sector. A draft renewable energy framework policy has also been developed, which includes mechanisms for procuring both off- and on-grid renewables, but this has not yet been adopted  resulting in uncertainty for investors. There are no specific regulations for off-grid renewables deployment. The country has set electricity access targets of 40% of the population by 2020 (currently 30%), and renewable energy is one of the main tools proposed to achieve this.

Liberia lacks the policy mechanisms required to achieve the paltry energy targets introduced in 2009. The targets, initially intended for 2015 but later pushed out to 2030, call for 30% of electricity and 10% of overall energy consumption to come from renewable sources, along with a target electrification rate of 35% nationally and 70% in Monrovia. No proven instruments, such as feed-in tariffs or auctions, have been introduced since the target was established. Developers must instead reach a bilateral agreement with the state-owned utility if seeking to supply the main grid. The Rural and Renewable Energy Agency was established in 2015, following a 2010 executive order by then President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf. Microgrid operators have since become active across several communities formerly without access to power. A dedicated microgrid policy is currently under development.

The lack of active substantial policy support programs is likely to stymie renewables deployment in Nicaragua. The exception is the series of tax incentives to ease the clean energy project development process. Import tax and VAT exemptions for machines, equipment, materials and inputs for investment and construction, including the sub-transmission lines required to transport electricity to the national grid, the Sistema Interconectado Nacional (SIN). The incentives, introduced in 2005, were initially to be in force for a period of 10 years and expire in May 2015. In December 2017, the national assembly approved the law reform in which extends the fiscal benefits until 2023.

The government targets around 100MW of new renewables over the 2015-30 period. The most tangible signs of progress have been the commissioning of a 20MW PV project in 2Q 2018 owned by the state-owned utility, Jirama, and the tender for 25MW of solar with storage supported by the World Bank's Scaling Solar program. However, the countrys grid and generation fleet is in urgent need of investment and it would not be surprising if the 50MW gap left to meet the 2030 target once the current pipeline is delivered was exceeded rapidly and the goals revised upwards.

Malawi has limited clean energy policies. In 2017, state-owned utility Escom held its first renewable energy tender, contracting 70MW of PV power across four sites. To attract foreign investment in the power sector, the country has started opening up the electricity market with a standardized PPA to allow independent power producers to operate. The country does have a rural electrification fund incentive, tax incentives and a feed-in tariff policy for small-scale projects; however, progress is slow. Several IPPs are developing projects and more than 36 memoranda of understanding have been signed so far, the majority on renewable energy projects. However, as of now, only one IPP is in line to agree PPAs by the end of 2018. Clean energy project developers and manufacturers can qualify for general tax incentives that were set up to support foreign investment.

Mali has no grid-scale renewable capacity except for hydro, which accounts for 40% of the current capacity, down from 60% in 2010. The country's target for 2020 and 2030 is also 60% of the total capacity, hydro included, with an increasing share planned for PV. However, specific policies to incentivize the sector are lacking. In 2015, the government launched two tenders for 75MW of PV, but no further auctions have been announced. Mali has a vibrant off-grid sector, with numerous isolated grids operated by local private operators. The investment costs are subsidized at 75% on average by the rural electrification agency. In theory, such subsidies should incentivize the use of capital-intensive technologies such as solar. However, most operators are relying on diesel, although an increasing number of hybrid systems are being deployed.

The government has rolled out little in the way of incentives for the deployment of renewables. Nonetheless, Mauritania has comfortably overshot its goal of 20% of renewables capacity by 2020, set at the turn of the millennium. A public procurement system is in place, with the national utility, Somelec, issuing bids for renewable energy-related projects since 2013. Issues around the irregularity of the tender announcements persist, as well as the lack of a concession system to help developers take on geographically proximate projects. In a bid to spur greater private participation in generation, a law on public-private partnerships was issued in July 2017, but skeptics point to the absence of an implementing decree specifying a regulatory framework to enforce the law.

Morocco is heavily dependent on electricity imports from Spain and fossil-fuel imports for its energy needs, and has ambitious targets to change that. It aims to have renewables account for 42% of its generating capacity by 2020, and 52% by 2030. At the time these targets were announced Morocco had only 280MW of wind capacity and 20MW of solar. An aggressive $9 billion tender program was announced to achieve the target of both 2GW of wind and solar capacity by 2020. Some 350MW of commissioned solar thermal projects will bring Moroccos solar capacity up to 600MW by end-2018. Installed wind capacity is currently at 1,048MW with the first of five wind farms comprising the 850MW tender closing finance in 3Q 2018. Timely commissioning of this project and the remaining pipeline of tenders will see Morocco meet its 2020 target. The renewables sector has received strong state support as it is seen as key to securing energy independence and reducing expensive fuel imports. The winning consortium from the five shortlisted bids for the 600-800MW of hybrid solar thermal and PV Noor-Midelt projects is expected to be announced by the end of 2018.

The majority of electricity in Mozambique comes from large hydro, with the power fleet seeing little funding over recent years. The latest investment has been in developing the domestic natural gas sector, which has grown rapidly since 2015. In terms of clean technology, the last decade saw Mozambique receive $0.94 million in biofuels investments and $57.2 million in solar. Moreover, a partnership between German aid agency GIZ and Funae  the countrys electrification agency  has developed mini-grid and pico-solar pilot programs.

The introduction of feed-in tariffs (Refit program) in 2015 marked the end of Nampowers monopoly on electricity generation and the start of renewables investment. In 2015, the state-owned utility signed contracts with 14 IPPs as part of the Refit program, totaling 70MW of renewable projects. The regulator has suggested that Namibia would switch to tenders and unsolicited applications from IPPs, due to the high cost for government of the generous feed-in tariffs. The National Integrated Resource Plan includes a list of renewable energy projects totaling 530MW that it wants to build by 2035. It is unclear whether these projects will be tendered or awarded to unsolicited IPPs. Since 2016, two renewables projects totaling 41MW have been awarded through tenders, while five unsolicited IPPs totaling 74MW have signed a PPA with Nampower.

An import duty exemption for renewable energy components, passed in September 2017, stands alone as Nigers only piece of legislation explicitly designed to incentivize the rollout of clean power generation. Tenders for renewables projects have been issued since 2016, laying the groundwork for a first push toward meeting the official target of increasing the national share of renewable energy to 27% by 2020. It is worth noting, however, that this target includes large hydro. The government is also aiming to connect 15% of the population to off-grid renewables by 2020. The projects that are under way could make significant headway toward meeting these goals, but a lack of commissioned renewables plants and the short time remaining mean they are unlikely to be met on time.

Nigeria has a target of 30GW of overall power generation capacity by 2030, of which 30% is expected to come from renewables, as set out in the Nigeria Vision 30-30-30 energy target policy. By 2030, the country plans to have 5.3GW of minigrids and 2.8GW of solar home systems, up from 1MW and 30MW in 2015, respectively. Self-generation, typically diesel, currently meets more than three-quarters of demand. The government wants to reduce this from 13.8GW to 5GW between 2015 and 2030. The challenging conditions to access the government feed-in tariffs and uncertainties around the distribution companies ability to pay, means that decentralized power generation projects offer the most direct opportunity in Nigeria today. The dedicated minigrid regulation that applies to all minigrids between 100kW and 1MW, whilst assets under this threshold remain unregulated, guarantees investors that they will be paid a full year of revenue plus their assets residual value should a distribution company ever electrify the area in which they operate.

Growth in Rwandas energy sector has been driven by two major targets: 563MW of generating capacity by 2018 and 100% electrification by 2024. While the country failed to meet the first goal, and was forced to push the second goal back (it was originally 70% by June 2018), the progress the country has made is unprecedented for Sub-Saharan Africa. The country has quadrupled its electrification rate from 10% in 2010 to over 44% in 2018 and increased generating capacity from 85MW to 216MW over the same period. The off-grid sector is expected to make up 48% of Rwandas electrification rate by 2024, and a healthy congregation of solar home system providers are now successfully doing business in the country.

Senegal has nearly reached its 2025 goal for 15% of renewable energy in electricity supply, given that it is currently at 13% with the commissioning of several solar projects at the end of 2017. The country will easily surpass its target, especially when the 158MW Lekela wind farm comes online. The next Lettre Politique du Secteur de lElectricite will be published late in 2018 and may set a new renewable energy target. Senegal introduced a new investment code this year so that utility-scale renewable energy projects are exempt from paying VAT on power production and import duties on components. This will decrease cost and administration for projects in development. The Scaling Solar auction in April 2018 led to the lowest cost of solar power Senegal has seen, due to competition between established foreign companies to build projects in the African country. Senegal has yet to launch its own separate auction scheme, aside from the World Banks Scaling Solar program.

The Sierra Leone renewable energy targets are ambitious only in the implied increases in electrification, and not in the percentage of renewables added as the countrys power is already supplied by mostly biomass and hydroelectric generation. The targets call for 4,703ktoe/annum (79.7%) of renewable energy contribution to final energy consumption by 2020, rising to 8,950ktoe/annum (84%) in 2030. Ratified in 2017, the targets are yet to be supported by instruments to encourage renewable development. An Electricity Sector Reform Roadmap released by the government later that year in partnership with the Millennium Challenge Corp. proposed a comprehensive array of feed-in tariffs for small projects, auctions for large-scale assets, and net metering for behind-the-meter systems.

Somalia's power sector is completely decentralized, as a result of years of conflict and regional isolation. Power is delivered by independent 'electricity service providers' that usually own their own diesel generator and transmission and distribution lines, and sell power directly to consumers. The country is also divided into regions with no central administration overseeing the energy sector, while the self-declared independent Somaliland has its own energy ministry. Consolidation is naturally occurring among the many small IPPs, but lack of regulation raises concerns. Many international organizations, including the World Bank and USAID, are active in Somalia and are working to help establish a regulatory framework to incentivize IPPs.

Once the benchmark of success, South Africa's renewables auction program is recovering from nearly three years of policy stalemate. The pause came to an end in April 2018 when the new Energy Minister Jeff Radebe signed the power-purchase agreements for the 27 outstanding renewable energy projects from Rounds 3.5-4. So far 6.4GW of renewables capacity across 102 projects has won support through the scheme and the next round is scheduled for 4Q 2018, with 1.8GW on offer. Future plans will likely be driven by the updated Integrated Resource Plan, which outlines the countrys planned generating capacity and was sent back to the Cabinet in March 2018 for reprocessing. Contentious issues include more nuclear power capacity; and limits for renewables technologies. In fossil fuels, the government has plans to procure more coal and gas capacity through dedicated IPP programs.

The country has no specific clean energy policy. Indeed, it lacks a clear energy policy altogether, although it has tried to implement some plans in the past. In the 2011 'South Sudan Strategic Development Plan' a target of increasing electricity access from 22,000 to 48,000 customers was set out  a plan that was initially pencilled in to run from 2011-13. In 2013 it was extended to run until 2016, at which point a new five-year plan was to be deployed. However, the next five-year plan is yet to be announced by the government, largely due to the disruption caused by the ongoing civil war.

Despite a PPP law, a renewable energy act and import-duty exemptions for solar components that are all at various stages along the legislative pipeline, Sudan has no clean energy incentives. Nor has the country exhibited clarity concerning its ambitions in this area. In addition to the countrys plan for renewables to account for 20% of generation by 2030 as part of its nationally determined contribution, presentations given by officials have cited a goal of 500MW by 2020. These targets, however, have not been explicitly issued as national objectives by the government. Official or not, with no utility-scale renewables commissioned to date, their realization appears a distant prospect.

The government updated the Power System Master Plan in December 2016. This lays out several scenarios for the development of Tanzanias electricity industry and is currently the most prioritized long-term plan for the country. Its renewable energy target is very modest, at 5% in generation by 2040  and the country appears to prioritize large hydro and fossil fuel generation. For small-scale projects, Tanzania has one of the most robust regulatory and legal frameworks in the region and encourages their construction. Projects will earn a fixed tariff for the lifetime of the PPA and the selection method will vary by technology. In September 2018, the country announced its first auction to construct solar and wind projects.

Togo passed its first renewable energy development law in July 2018, setting out to reach 50% renewables in the national energy mix by 2030 from 15% today (including hydro). The government also published a roadmap to reach 100% electrification by the same year from a national average of 37% in 2017, which includes the addition of 108MW of solar and hydro capacity on the network, 315 mini-grids and the distribution of 550,000 solar kits all through public-private patnerships. While this is an ambitious target, Togos national political will to become energy independent and electrified should help to carry the sector. The country is in the process of setting up an open, transparent and easy-to-navigate regulatory framework. The renewables law comes a year after the launch of the AT2ER (Agence Togolaise dElectrification Rurale et des Energies Renouvelables), which will lead and guide the development of renewable energy projects.
Does it represent entrenched corruption or does it represent a repudiation of entrenched corruption?

Uganda failed to meet its ambitious clean energy targets for 2017, but generation capacity in the country has still grown by over 50% since 2010. There is also a pipeline of over 1GW of hydro projects in development. The biggest catalyst of growth in the countrys generation capacity has been the successful renewable energy feed-in tariff (REFiT), which offered attractive prices over 20-year contracts to hydro, biomass, wind and, most recently, solar developers. REFiT has since run out of funding, but tax incentives, while sometimes lacking in transparency, and a universal electricity access goal by 2035 are enough to put Uganda ahead of many of its neighbors as a clean energy investment hotspot.

Zambia's 2008 National Energy Policy, in line with the 2030 vision of universal electrification, aims to address the barriers associated with the wide deployment of renewable energy technology. The countrys electrification target is ambitious but appears achievable with the successful launch of the Request for Proposal (RfP) for the 100MW solar PV tender, which yielded a notably low tariff (below $80/MWh unlevelized). The announcement of the 100MW small hydro tender and 100MW addition from biomass as part of the GET FiT program, along with the planned dissemination of 500,000 solar home systems and installation of 350,000 solar water heaters, will contribute to increased access to modern energy services and meeting the ever growing energy demand of Zambia.  State-owned utility Zesco are currently facing financial strain and plan on implementing an approved cost-reflective tariff increase of 75% by the end of 2018. All policies have been stable and made fairly transparent.

Zimbabwe emphasizes clean energy as one of the pillars of its development plans. The National Renewable Energy Policy (drafted in 2017 but yet to be put in force) sets two goals: to achieve an installed renewable energy capacity of 1,100MW (excluding large hydro) or 16.5% of total electricity supply, whichever is higher, by 2025, and for renewables to reach 2,100MW, or 26.5% of total electricity supply, whichever is higher, by 2030. The Renewable Energy Feed-In Tariff policy and net metering regulations are also not fully implemented yet. The Rural Electrification Fund, in comparison, has been effective, and 427 microgrids have already been commissioned across the country; it is derived from a 6% surcharge on electricity consumption.

Afghanistan aims to develop 4.5-5GW of renewables capacity by 2032, as set out in the countrys Renewable Energy Policy. The targets are divided into two terms  the first (2015-20) envisages creating a favorable environment for the growth of renewables, and the second (2020-32) is when the capacity targets will be achieved. Going by current progress, the targets are very ambitious  the country is halfway through Term 1 and has made little headway in its goals for that period. There are no feed-in tariffs, subsidies, rules or regulations for the renewable energy sector  all of which were goals for this period.

Armenia aims to make renewables 21% of generation by 2020, and 26% by 2025; and it plans to cap emissions at 633 million metric tons of CO2 equivalent between 2015 and 2050. If hydroelectricity is counted within this renewables fraction, then Armenia has already reached its 2020 goal, as hydro currently makes up 31% of generation. The previous government put in place a generous feed-in tariff for rooftop solar, held an auction for 55MW of large-scale PV, and has issued licenses for commercial scale PV systems. The rules and structure of each of these programs are clear, and have been relatively successful. However, the sudden change in Armenias government has resulted in significant uncertainty around the future for these programs.

Azerbaijan set a target in 2011 for renewables to account for 20% of electricity generation by 2020. More recently, in December 2016, the countrys StrategicRoadmap for Public Utilities, which calls for the installation of 4.2GW of renewables, was endorsed by President Ilham Aliyev. This plan includes an estimated 3.5GW of wind, 500MW of PV and 200MW of biomass  however,there has been no significant movement toward these goals. Aconstant reshuffling of government agencies and the lack of a frameworkfor PPAs and interconnections have deterred investors. There has been some show of political will, especially by the State Agency of Alternativeand RenewableEnergy Sources, to encourage clean energy growth.

Bangladesh has an ambitious policy to consume 10% renewable energy by 2020 from 2% in 2018, including hydro. It will need 2GW of renewable projects to meet this target and is also preparing a net-metering policy to spur investments in the rooftop solar segment. The project developments on the ground, however, are very slow as IPPs struggle to secure land for projects and right-of-way to build transmission lines.  Some renewable projects have had quite generous feed-in tariffs set by regulators, but delays in getting project approvals mean most of these may be cancelled. Regulators want to conduct an auction to build projects in a solar park but these may not be awarded before 2019.

Cambodia has few clean energy policies in place today, and there are no incentives such as feed-in tariffs or net metering. With much of its infrastructure destroyed during the countrys civil war in the 1970s, the government and its utility (Electricite du Cambodge, or EDC) has instead set ambitious goals to electrify all villages by 2020, and 70% of all households by 2030. The Asian Development Bank has been working with EDC to help launch a pilot solar auction to procure 100MW; however, it is not a formal program and it is unclear if and when the auction will go forward.

With 635GW of renewable energy capacity, China is home to the worlds largest renewable energy market. Top-down targets and generous feed-in tariffs have driven strong growth, so that both solar and wind capacity will surpass the governments 2020 targets (110GW and 210GW, respectively). The result is a prolonged deficit in the governments funding support, now estimated at 150 billion yuan ($22 billion). In response, Chinas National Energy Administration (NEA) announced in May 2018 a major revamp of policies supporting wind and solar. Future new wind projects must compete in auctions and new solar subsidy quotas are on hold, possibly reduced in 2019. The policy changes came faster than the industry expected, particularly for solar. About 97GW of 151GW of commissioned solar plants have yet to qualify for subsidies. It is unclear if they ever will secure the quota. Regulators are planning to introduce renewable portfolio standards by the end of 2018. However, it remains unclear whether or not these non-subsidy measures will be enough to offset the subsidy deficit or help to maintain the momentum of Chinas renewable energy investment.

The Indian renewable auctions market is the largest in the world. Auctioned capacity has ramped up by 68% since 2017 as the country moves closer to meeting its goal to install 175GW of renewables by 2022. Indian energy ministers are optimistic about surpassing this target before 2022, with renewables now accounting for 20% of installed capacity. Over 8GW of projects were awarded through auctions in the first half of 2018 alone. Indias solar market almost doubled in size in 2017, making it a record year with annual PV installations touching 8GW. Through various government incentives laid out in the National Solar Mission, India aims to accelerate the growth of solar capacity to reach the target of 100GW by 2022.

Indonesia aims to generate 23% of primary energy consumption from renewables by 2025, up from around 5% in 2017. This target may be too bold, given the recent low levels of finance committed to renewables. The Electricity Supply Plan (RUPTL) 2018 sets goals to add 8.3GW of hydro, 4.6GW of geothermal and 2GW of other renewables over 2018-27. New solar and wind projects are to be awarded through a limited tender process. Bid prices are restricted to 85% of the regional generation cost, if it exceeds the national average. If the regional cost is less than the national average, tariffs can be negotiated between PLN and the developer. This policy, known as Regulation number 50, has provoked industry complaints that it incentivizes project development in remote areas with high regional generation tariffs but low electricity demand. Additionally, the process to participate in the tender is not clear and there is little clarity on the PPA template.

Kazakhstan has a massive potential for renewables and sufficient land for wind/solar installations. The country aims for its renewable energy capacity to reach 30% by 2030 and 50% by 2050, as specified in the presidential edict and the EXPO2017 hosted in the capital Astana. The principal incentive is the generous feed-in-tariff (denominated in local currency) introduced for each of the technologies such as hydro, wind, solar and biofuel. Tax exemptions are available. It has laid the foundation for private and foreign investors in the renewable energy sector for years, before Kazakhstan started operation of an auction mechanism in May 2018. This new mechanism, the largest one in Central Asia, may bid down the wholesale prices for renewables projects.

Kyrgyzstan generates less than 2% of its power generation from renewable energy sources other than large hydro, but the country aims to increase this figure to 10% by 2021. The main policy in place to reach this target is the countrys Forty Steps to a New Era program, which calls for the construction of 11 new small hydro power plants (with a capacity of about 160MW) over the coming three years. Small hydro plants are able to take advantage of a feed-in tariff offered by the Energy Regulator and are exempt from most VAT and customs duties. The country only has about 80MW of small hydro installed now, but its utilization of clean energy is significant. Large hydro accounts for the vast majority (nearly 80%) of Kyrgyzstans installed power capacity.

The government of Laos has billed the country as the battery of Asia, eager to capitalize on its abundant hydroelectric resources and small population to export energy to its larger, fast-growing neighbors. Accordingly, it has focused its attention on building large hydro facilities that, in many cases, send power directly across its borders to Thailand or Vietnam. The government has announced a target for non-hydro renewables to provide 30% of the power mix by 2025, but few actors in the country take this target seriously. There are no other significant policies to promote renewables, although international groups such as USAID have been working with the government to help design a pilot renewable energy auction, which may take place in 2019 at the earliest.

Malaysia introduced a feed-in tariff mechanism in 2011 and five years later announced the first competitive large-scale solar auction program. Both have been successful in promoting renewable energy generation. In contrast, the net-metering scheme has done very little to promote rooftop solar developments because of the very low retail electricity tariffs. The new government has yet to announce official renewables targets, and the delay has pushed back the announcement of a widely anticipated third large-scale solar auction. The Sustainable Energy Development Authority is preparing a new renewable energy transition road map for 2025, which is expected to push a more ambitious renewable energy target and streamline many of the existing policies, institutions and mechanisms.

The government aims to reach 20% renewable energy generation by 2023 and 30% by 2030  a significant leap from the 2017 share of 4.2%. The most important legal foundation was laid by the Law on Renewable Energy (2007), as well as the National Renewable Energy Program (2005-20), which provided official targets and incentives for global investors in the sector. The principal incentive is the relatively generous feed-in tariff: the price paid under the power-purchase agreement (PPA) is negotiated with the National Dispatching Center  such feed-in tariffs are denominated in U.S. dollars and paid in Mongolian tugrik based on current exchange rates, helping with elimination of currency risk. Tax exemptions are also made available for PV and wind turbines.

The 2015 Energy Master Plan is the latest national energy plan. It envisions raising Myanmars generating capacity almost threefold to 15GW by 2030. Almost a third of the additional capacity would be new and repowered hydro generation; the rest would be supplied by installing 3GW of combined-cycle natural gas turbines, raising coal-fired capacity by 2.88GW from its present level of 120MW, and building 300MW of grid-connected solar, wind and geothermal projects from the present level of none. A National Electrification Project (NEP), which aims to bring electricity to all households by 2030, has been rolled out by the World Bank since early 2016. By the end of 2017, the countrys electrification rate reached 39%, up from about 37% in 2016. In September 2018, the new government led by Aung San Suu Kyi was reported to be drafting a renewable energy law which will target 8% renewables in total electricity generation by 2021, and 12% by 2025.

The government of Nepal has a long-term target for hydro  10GW by 2020 and 25GW by 2030  and for electricity from renewables to account for 80% of generation by 2050. Its National Rural and Renewable Energy Program, initiated in 2012, targeted 25MW mini and micro hydro, 600,000 solar home systems, along with goals for biogas, water pumps, solar cookers, and also aimed to reduce dependency on fossil fuels by 50%, and cut CO2 emissions by 14 million metric tons by 2020. The targets are very ambitious as the country only has about 1GW of hydro. There is a feed-in tariff but this is rarely adjusted and is not cost reflective. Lots of plans have been put in place to achieve these targets, but progress has been slow.

Pakistan has seen a rapid expansion of renewable energy since 2015, with some projects built under the bilateral China-Pakistan-Economic-Corridor (CPEC) initiative which is driving Chinese funding to infrastructure projects in Pakistan. The new government led by Prime Minister Imran Khan seems to be committed to the CPEC, and to clean energy, but its preferences and priorities are yet to be spelled out. The previous government had already decided on moving to an auctions-based regime instead of relying on feed-in tariffs, and was mulling an increase in the clean energy target to 20% of total commercial energy by 2030, from 5%.

Two major laws, the Electric Power Industry Reform Act (EPIRA) and Renewable Energy Act (RE), have incentivized growth in the Philippines renewable sector. However, implementation of those laws has been slow, and as a result their energy targets were missed. There has been staggered renewables build, and the country plans to hit 15.3GW of renewables capacity by 2030 and total generating capacity of about 65GW by 2040. A feed-in tariff (FiT) has spurred 1.052GW of renewables growth, and behind-the-meter policies have achieved an impressive 50MW of distributed resources. The recent implementation of a renewables portfolio standard (RPS) is another positive sign, but the policies together havent been sufficient to reach the national targets.

The Singaporean government has set goals to reduce emissions intensity, improve energy efficiency and expand PV capacity within the city-state. A corner stone of its clean energy plans is the target for 350MW of installed PV capacity by 2020, of which around 150MW had been installed by end-2017. The government has announced its intention to increase the PV target to 1GW by an unspecified time after 2020. PV is the main focus for clean energy in Singapore as there is limited potential for other renewables technologies. Due to land constraints, rooftops and floating PV (on reservoirs and coastal waters) are key components of the governments plans, and several pilots have been launched to test solar technologies and financial support frameworks. Solar rooftop tenders have delivered over 166MW across 2,300 buildings. The government aims to install PV systems on 5,500 public housing blocks by 2020.

Sri Lanka has decided to move away from feed-in tariffs to auctions, except in select areas such as rooftop solar. It recently approved a long-term electricity generation plan (2018-37). This includes new coal plants, which is what the main utility, Ceylon Electricity Board, wanted, and it also envisages new gas and renewable energy plants, which is what the regulator Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka, or PUCSL, favored. This compromise ended the rather public difference of opinion between the CEB and the PUCSL. The next long-term plan for 2020-39 is to be submitted by April 2019. The debate on the future energy mix will continue, and the final energy choices are yet to emerge. Sri Lanka's grid is isolated, having no connections with any of its neighbors yet, and that fact also impacts future planning.

Taiwans feed-in tariffs have supported the growth of renewable energy to reach 7.8GW of capacity by end-2017. The new administration, which came to power in 2016, launched an aggressive energy transition plan to phase out nuclear by 2025 while adding 25GW of renewables. Lucrative offshore wind feed-in tariffs have attracted major European developers; but given the two previous PPA renegotiations between Taipower and independent power producers in the early 2010s, financiers are wary of possible offtaker risk. Though the government is expected to allocate targeted capacities, including through offshore wind and utility-scale solar auctions, difficulties in land acquisition for solar and an immature wind supply chain can be significant roadblocks to deliver projects on time to meet goals.

Tajikistan generates less than 2% of its power from renewable energy sources other than large hydro, but the country aims to increase this figure to 20% by 2030. To support this goal, the government has called for the construction of small hydro and solar power plants and granted VAT and excise duty exemptions to renewable energy investors. The countrys small hydro and solar markets have yet to take off, but its utilization of clean energy remains notable. Large hydro, for example, accounts for over 80% of Tajikistans installed power capacity.

Thailand is the regional leader in total installed renewable capacity in Southeast Asia. It was the first country in SEA to implement a feed-in premium intended to spur investment and development of renewable energy projects. The latest Alternative Energy Development Plan (AEDP) 2015-36 sets a target for renewables to account for 20% of generation by 2036. Specifically, Thailand aims to have 3GW of wind installations and 6GW of solar capacity by 2036. The generous feed-in premium and subsequent feed-in-tariff programs implemented by the government successfully supported the growth of the renewables industry. By end of 2017, cumulative installed solar capacity exceeded 3GW and wind capacity was around 800MW. With the long lead time to 2036, Thailand's current renewable energy target is well within reach.

Clean energy remains a low priority in Turkmenistan due to cheap and heavily subsidized natural gas, which accounts for nearly all of the country's electricity mix. Despite some overtures by the government to seriously consider renewables, such as working studies, a commitment to increase PV with neighboring countries and pilot programs, there has been no regulation or policy enacted to support these technologies.

Uzbekistan is the most populous country in Central Asia as well the biggest producer of electricity. However, the power sector is highly inefficient, plagued by decades of centralized Soviet-style management. Only recently has the country taken steps to bolster clean energy installations and investment. In 2017, the government published clean energy targets in a strategic plan to reach, saying it aimed to have 1.2GW of hydro, 450MW of PV and 300MW of wind by 2025. However, there has been no clarity on interconnections, tariff regulations or penalties, effectively making this target non-binding and hard to enforce. Nonetheless, the country has signed its first PPA for a 1GW PV project  an indication that large one-off bilateral deals will be the main mechanism for projects to be developed.

Vietnams revised Power Development Plan VII in 2016 increased the renewable energy target to 6.5% of electricity generation in 2020 from an earlier goal of 4.5%, and raised the 2030 target to 10.7% from 6%.  The 2020 target looks achievable as it only requires a cumulative capacity of 800MW of wind capacity, 850MW of solar and 750MW of biomass. The wind feed-in tariff has been revised for the first time since 2011, and has been raised to $0.085/kWh from $0.078 for onshore wind and to $0.098 for offshore wind. The solar feed-in tariff of $0.0935/kWh is one of the highest in the region. The interest from developers is reflected in the solar and wind projects approved by the Prime Minister and the Ministry of Industry and Trade.

Albania meets its electricity demand through a combination of domestic generation and imports. The level of imports depends on the annual hydrological cycle as Albania generates 100% of its electricity from large and small hydro power plants. Via a Renewable Energy Law that entered into force in 2017, it intends to incentivize new renewable capacity -- wind, solar and small hydro -- through granting feed-in tariffs for small projects and holding auctions for larger projects. It held its first auction in September 2018 for 50MW of solar  plus an obligation for the winner to build an additional 20-50MW unsubsidized. But there is no transparency on the timing, number or capacity of future auctions.

The Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) has implemented a number of renewable energy incentives. First and foremost among which is a target for the share of clean technologies in gross final energy consumption set through its National Renewable Energy Action Plan submitted to the European Commission. The country aims to reach 40% by 2020, a target which has already been surpassed by several percentage points due to large hydros classification as renewable. A feed-in tariff exists for several renewable technologies, including wind, solar geothermal, hydro and biomass, with an average tariff duration of 12 years. The government also encourages self-generation by offering power producers the right to a premium for the generation of electricity for their own use.

Renewable energy installations in Georgia are motivated by winter supply constraints and energy diversification concerns, rather than a need to significantly reduce the carbon emissions of their electricity supply, which is mostly hydro and natural gas. There are plans for 600MW of wind projects, but these are currently being held in the approval stages. The government introduced a residential net-metering program for small-scale solar, but uptake has been limited. It is planning to hold auctions, but has not yet released guidelines or a schedule. Most of the activity in the energy sector is focused on liberalization, to align with EU requirements. Regulations and frameworks for this are being set by GNERC, the independent energy regulator.

In April 2017, the Republic of Macedonia amended its National Renewable Energy Action Plan issued in 2012, lowering its target to source 28% of generation from renewable sources by 2020 to an achievable 24%. The original target has been pushed back to 2030. The country has little in the way of renewable energy policies besides a feed-in tariff, which entitles operators of PV installations to conclude 15-year PPAs. The agreements standard tenor is extended to 20 years for both hydro and wind power plants, and electricity suppliers are required to purchase the producers generation for the agreements duration.

Renewable energy (excluding large hydro) accounts for less than 1% of Russias power generation, but the country aims to bring this figure to 2.5% by 2024. The sole policy implemented to achieve this goal is an auction program that grants fixed 15-year capacity payments to government-approved renewable energy projects. Since 2013, the government has awarded over 5GW of wind, solar and small hydro capacity to developers across six annual auction rounds. As part of its nationally determined contribution, Russia intends to limit greenhouse-gas emissions to 70-75% of 1990 levels by 2030. Still, since its emissions have remained below 70% of 1990 levels since the collapse of the Soviet Union, the country is already on track to meet this target even if its greenhouse-gas output increases.

Since 2016, Serbia has offered a feed-in tariff to support wind, solar, biomass, biogas, hydro and geothermal. The feed-in tariff has been high enough to trigger capacity additions, but there are technology caps, to curb excessive build-out and ensure a manageable subsidy budget. Solar caps will be reached, albeit thanks to a low limit of 4MW for rooftop solar and 6MW for ground-mounted installations. Meanwhile, the larger wind cap, at 500MW is also expected to be met: 50% has already closed financing and the remaining 50% is expected to follow and be commissioned by 2020.

Turkey has ambitious capacity targets across renewables sectors, aiming to reach 20GW of wind energy, 5GW of solar and 1GW of geothermal by 2023, as well 34GW of hydro. A boom in unlicensed solar development saw Turkey approach 4.6GW by mid-2018 and the 1GW geothermal target was reached in 2017, thanks to a generous feed-in tariff. While wind growth has been steady, the 20GW would require the installation of more than 2GW a year of additional capacity, and policy support has been inconsistent. The site-specific 1GW YEKA auctions got off to a rocky start as the winners of the 2017 rounds have not reached financial close. The feed-in tariff is also due to expire after 2020, with no visibility on support for renewables after that point.

Ukraine has set itself a target for renewables to account for 11% of generation by 2020. In support of this it has a generous feed-in tariff, tax incentives for the import of renewables-related equipment and a break on corporate tax for sales of electricity from renewable sources. Some regions such as Odessa even offer land under favorable conditions for renewables development. Still, the country is not on track to meet its 2020 target, with less than 2% of electricity generation coming from renewables in 2017. Ukraines new Electricity Law, which comes into full effect in July 2019, establishes a much clearer framework for the growth of renewables. The power markets are being reformed under this law, the role of the offtaker is clarified, and a framework for standard PPAs is established. All of this should boost investor confidence, which has been undermined by political instability over the past decade and following the annexation of Crimea and fighting in the east of the country.

Argentina has set an 8% target for renewable electricity consumption by 2018 and 20% by 2025 under Law 27.191. The law represents a landmark for clean energy in the country, as it created the Trust Fund for the Development of Renewable Energies (FODER) and provided tax incentives to boost investments in renewables  a VAT tax rebate and accelerated depreciation. Under Resolution 281-2017, Argentina also establishes that large consumers (>300kW) need to comply with the 8% target individually and allows companies to make bilateral corporate PPAs. Projects subscribed to the scheme receive priority of dispatch. The country has implemented a series of renewable power auctions, RenovAr, to spur the development of clean energy projects. As of November 2018, RenovAr tenders have contracted a total of 3.8GW of clean capacity. However, despite this growth, Argentina is unlikely to meet its target.

Bolivia has adopted clean energy policies and renewables represent a significant portion of the countrys 2.6GW generation base. The countrys National Development Plan 2017-2020, which commits to a total effective installed capacity of 4.9GW by 2020, targets a significant expansion in hydro capacity (1.4GW) and wind, biomass, geothermal, and solar (411MW), as well as combined cycle and gas plants (1.1GW). Bolivia also has a goal of increasing the share of 'alternative' energy (wind, biomass, geothermal and solar) and other sources of energy (combined cycle) to 9% in 2030, up from 7% in 2017. In 2014, the country published Decree 2048 to encourage clean energy development.

Since 2009, Brazil has implemented reverse auctions to contract new clean energy generation capacity to supply the regulated utility market. The country has pioneered competitive auctions, which led to over 24.8GW of renewable energy contracted, despite a two-year tender hiatus between May 2016 and December 2017. Auctions started to pick up again in late 2017 and four rounds were held between December 2017 and August 2018. Significant competition among project developers caused by a lack of contracts over the period resulted in the lowest average wind auction price ever recorded in Brazil of $20.3/MWh in April 2018. In terms of other renewables incentives, retail electricity customers may install self-generation facilities, connect to the grid, deliver surplus generation and obtain compensation in the form of a subsequent billing credit.

Chiles exceptional natural resources, stable government and healthy economy make it attractive to clean energy investment. The government has set ambitious long-term goals for adding clean energy capacity and begun implementing policies to foster an environment in which renewable projects are more competitive. Targets include a clean energy mandate of 20% of generation for utilities by 2025 and an overall clean energy target of 60% of generation by 2035. By 2050, the country aims to have 70% renewables generation from its electricity mix.
Chile plans to auction a total of 12.2TWh/year by 2022. Auctions are technology-blind, with wind, solar, gas and other technologies competing head-to-head. In 2014, the government implemented a new system that created a more competitive environment for clean technologies. Since then, Chile has held four tenders and contracted 31TWh/year. In two of the last three tenders, renewables accounted for 100% of all generation contracted. 
In January 2018, coal asset owners signed an agreement committing to not invest in new coal plants. Coordinated by the government, the four generators with coal assets and other players are working on a decarbonization plan that aims to retire or convert all coal plants by 2040.

Colombias historically weak policy support for non-hydroelectric sources of renewable energy, a product of its abundant large hydro resources, has resulted in limited wind and solar development to date. New momentum behind established policies may stand to change this. Colombia will hold its first long-term power auction in 2019. In June 2010, the country set a modest target of 6.5% of generation from non-large hydro renewables for end users with access to the grid by 2020. For those lacking access, the goal was set at 30%. Colombia's total generation from non-large hydro renewables that year was 4%. In 2011, it reached 6.2% before dropping in subsequent years. The 6.5% target was met in 2017 with 8% generated from non-large hydro renewables.

In 2007, Costa Rica committed to becoming the worlds first carbon-neutral economy by 2021 and also set a goal to reach a 100% renewable energy matrix. In 2017, the country generated 99.7% of its power from clean energy sources (including large hydro) and ran 300 days on clean energy alone. Hydro power is still the predominant energy source, representing 77% of generation, however, wind accounts for 11.5% of the total.

The Dominican Republic has set an ambitious target to get 25% of its electricity supply from clean energy by 2020. As of December 2017, 18% of the nations total 15.3TWh came from clean energy generation. The country also has a net metering program, which allows retail electricity consumers who have renewable self-generation facilities to interconnect with the distribution company, deliver surplus generation to the grid, and obtain a billing credit.

Ecuador does not have a clear target for renewables, despite claiming an interest to raise clean generation by 2025. The country had a 90% hydro target to be met by 2017, which it did not achieve, even after the addition of 2GW of hydro capacity in 2016. Ecuador, like many countries in the region, is heavily dependent on hydropower and exposed to variations of rainfall. The government gives priority of dispatch for biomass, geothermal, small hydro, solar, tidal and wind projects. Renewable energy developers may also apply for import tax exemption on clean energy equipment and a five-year waiver on income tax. Despite that, deployment of wind and solar assets have been minimal. Ecuador was one of the few countries in Latam to have a feed-in-tariff incentive for renewables, which is currently not in force.

El Salvadors government is strongly focused on diversifying its power matrix and reducing its oil dependency by adding renewable energy capacity. Since 2013 the country has held three auctions, contracting 285MW of renewable capacity. The country also offers income and import tax exemptions to clean energy projects and guarantees priority dispatch to electricity generated from renewable sources.

In 2017, Guatemala generated 11.4TWh of electricity, 35% of which came from fossil fuel plants and another 35% from large hydro. Renewables combined (small hydro, wind, solar, biomass and geothermal) accounted for 30% of generation.

Improving access to energy has a central place in President Jovenel Moises program following his election in February 2017. The country aims to increase renewables share of power generation from zero in 2017 to 47% by 2030. The target is broken down as follows: 24.5% of generation is to come from hydro, 9.4% from wind, 7.5% from solar and 5.6% from biomass. A few months into office, the government abolished import duties on wind and solar generation products, as well as solar appliances. The 2017-18 Finance Act has abolished all import duties levied on PV generation equipment, wind generation equipment, and solar powered off-grid home appliances such as fridges, lights, chargers.

Hondurass National Energy Policy has an ambitious goal of 70% of generation from clean energy by 2020. Generation from solar energy has doubled from 2015 levels, reaching 924GW in 2017, or 11% of generation. Decree 70-2007, published in June 2007, guarantees priority dispatch to electricity generated from renewable sources. Renewable energy is also eligible for exemption from three types of taxes: income tax, import duty, and sales tax.

Jamaica seeks to decrease its oil dependency and improve its energy security by diversifying its electricity mix. It was the Caribbeans first country to hold clean energy-only auctions. The countrys National Energy Plan 2009-2030 calls for 20% of its electricity generation to come from renewable sources by 2030. Private utility Jamaica Public Service (JPS) has responsibility for generation, transmission, and distribution on the island (the government owns 20% of the company). Other players may enter the market as independent power producers (IPPs) and sell electricity to JPS.

Energy reforms in Mexico that have transformed the power sector have also included strong support for renewable energy. Mexico in 2012 established a mandate to generate 35% of power from clean sources by 2024. It set up a Clean Energy Certificates (CELs) market in 2014, the main incentive for clean energy. The clean energy target begins at 5% in 2018 and will increase gradually to 13.9% in 2022. Implementation of key policies remains a work in progress. The CELs market is scheduled to enter into force in 2018. Certificate market demand, essentially a proxy for the total GWh of renewable power that will need to be delivered for Mexico to meet its clean energy goals, is expected to total approximately 13.7 million CELs in 2018, rising to 16.5 million in 2019 and 21.4 million in 2020 according to projections from the Secretariat of Energy (SENER). Mexico held three successful long term renewables auctions over 2016-17, making headlines with record low prices and contracting a total of 19.8TWh of clean power, 1.8GW of firm capacity, and 20.6 million CELs. A fourth long-term auction is scheduled for December 2018.

Nicaraguas Ministry of Energy and Mines updated in January 2017 the Plan for Electric Generation Expansion 2016-2030 with a non-binding 73% renewables generation target (including large hydro) by 2030. The plan also establishes interim renewables goals of 55% by 2018 and 64% by 2023. In 2017, the country had reached a 56% share. Renewable energy developers enjoy a full range of tax breaks, including import duty, VAT and income tax exemptions.

Panama continues to promote advances in the energy sector. In 2H 2017, the governments of Panama and Colombia signed an agreement to resume construction of a 500km transmission line to interconnect the two countries. The project had been halted in 2012. The interconnection will have capacity to transport up to 400MW of energy between the two countries and is now expected to be commissioned by year-end 2020.

With nearly all of its electricity demand met by three large hydro plants totaling 8.8GW, Paraguay has had little incentive to develop a policy framework for other energy sources. In fact, the country is a net exporter of electricity. The only clean energy policy incentive in Paraguay is a biofuel blending mandate for gasoline and diesel.

Technology-specific auctions have been essential for renewables deployment in Peru. In 2008, under decree No. 1002, the government established auctions to contract on-grid renewable capacity every two years. Since then, four auctions have been carried out, resulting in 71 project developments, totaling 1.34 GW of biomass, small hydro, solar and wind capacities. To promote renewables, Peru also offers priority dispatch to clean energy plants and 20% accelerated depreciation for renewables projects. Peru also held an auction for off-grid solar in November 2014 to contract up to 500,000 off-grid PV systems. Ergon, the only one winner, announced that will develop 150,000-200,000 systems. Peru was one of the first countries in the world to hold off-grid energy auctions.

Uruguay experienced a boom in renewable markets thanks to a series of technology-specific auctions combined with tax incentives. From 2013 onward, the country saw clean generation jump from 2% to an impressive 39% of the total. Wind and solar alone account for 28% of generation, by far the biggest penetration of intermittent technologies in emerging markets. The government of Uruguay established a 15% clean energy installed capacity target by 2015, which was met comfortably. From 2009 to 2013, AdministracinNacionaldeUsinasyTrasmisionesElctricas (UTE) held several tenders. Since then, Uruguay added around 2GW of clean assets, summing to 4.5GW of total power capacity. Tenders held in Uruguay offered a premium payment for projects that use local content equivalent to more than 40% of the value of the total project.

Egypt aims to reach 20% renewable electricity generation by 2022 (albeit two years later than originally planned). Yet the country has only seen modest renewables build to date. This has not been due to a lack of support programs: despite a less-than-successful first round, the feed-in tariff, which has now closed, secured some 1.5GW of PV capacity. The tenders for engineering, procurement & construction contracts have been responsible for most renewables deployment to date because they have principally been attached to cheap financing from international development banks. In contrast, the tender scheme for build-own-operate (BOO) contracts has faced delays and changing specifications, while the bilateral and net metering systems have seen little-to-no uptake, principally because of the low electricity tariffs. The most recent auction program replaces the feed-in tariff and the first round began in 1H 2018 for a BOO contract to build 600MW of PV capacity. Consortia comprising one global renewables player plus a local player dominated the bidders.

Iraq aims to generate 10% of its electricity generation from renewable sources by 2020 under the Integrated National Energy Strategy (INES). The Ministry of Energy is unlikely to achieve this target having already fallen behind on its plan: it has identified 13 potential locations for developing PV projects in Baghdad, Anbar and four other provinces as part of its investment strategy. The ministry offered a 15-year fixed feed-in tariff of $35/MWh and has outlined 2.7GW of potential PV projects. However, unclear investment and operation laws in the electricity sector and a lack of support from international financial institutions are deterring investment in renewables.

Jordans National Energy Strategy plan aims for the country to generate 10% of its energy needs by 2020 from renewable sources. Since launching, the plan has already seen 730MW of renewable projects come into operation, with 1036MW under construction and a further 150MW under financial close. To date, two rounds of direct proposals have been completed and a third is under way. Despite delays due to grid capacity constraints and the introduction of a 35% local content requirement in round three, stable policies and transparent incentives have allowed Jordan to become a regional leader in renewable energy.

Kuwait's 2030 Energy Strategy sets out to secure 15% of electricity generation from renewable sources by 2030. This target is to be achieved through a combination of solar (both PV and solar thermal) and onshore wind. Kuwait has only recently started to develop and deploy renewable technologies, and the energy mix remains largely hydrocarbon-based, but there are many projects in the pipeline to increase the share of renewables in generation and lessen the countrys dependence on fossil fuels. An illustrative example is the 1.5GW Al-Dibdibah solar project, with a tender submission deadline set for December 16, 2018. Most renewables capacity is under development at the Shagaya Renewable Energy Park, which will have the capacity to house 2GW of renewables by 2030. This would displace nearly 12.5 million barrels of oil for electricity generation per year.

Lebanon aims to generate 12% of electricity from renewable sources by 2020 under the National Renewable Energy Action Plan. It has made headway toward this target, with 380MW of solar and wind projects signing PPAs to date. However, it will need a timely commission of its second phase of wind and solar projects to meet its 2020 target. The 300MW solar and 200-400MW wind projects in this phase are receiving requests for proposals as of 3Q 2018. Government support for renewables is stable  the elections in 2018 maintained the political status quo. The downside to this is that there is little chance the severe underinvestment and frequent blackouts that plague the power sector will be addressed soon.

The Sultanate has legally bound the state utility to ensure that at least 10% of electricity generation be derived from renewable resources by 2025. Oman has not implemented any other renewable energy incentives. A lack of legislation promoting clean energy notwithstanding, progress is being made toward reaching the 2,500MW to 3,000MW of capacity required to meet this goal. The Oman Power and Water Procurement Co. (OPWP) is overseeing the construction of a 50MW wind farm and the last bidding round for a 500MW solar project. The OPWP has, thus far, procured renewables projects through a tendering mechanism.

The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia has ambitious plans to develop clean energy and implement its plan articulated as the National Renewable Energy Program (NREP). This strategic initiative falls under Vision 2030 and the National Transformation Program (NTP) and is aimed to substantially increase the share of renewable energy capacity to 9.5GW by 2023. The program sets out a systematic and targeted road map to rapidly diversify the domestic power supply, catalyze economic development and support long-term prosperity in line with the goals of Vision 2030, which include creating a new renewable industry and supporting the build-up of this promising sector. Saudi Arabia opened bids for its first utility-scale 400MW wind farm in July 2018 with project award planned for December 2018.

The U.A.E. has set itself the goal of reaching a 50% share of renewable energy in the generation mix by 2050. Given the federal structure of the country, individual emirates have each determined their own objectives. Abu Dhabi and Dubai are shooting for 7% by 2020; both have also put renewables projects up for bidding. Dubai, for instance, issues tenders for renewables projects as part of its Clean Energy Strategy 2050, which aims to source 75% of power generation from clean energy by this centurys halfway point. Despite the U.A.E.s reputation as a regional trailblazer for clean energy, the country has not put in place any renewables incentives  progress to date has largely been driven by state-backed projects.

The government of the Palestinian Territories has prioritized renewable energy as a means of meeting growing demand and as a way to circumvent limitations on land use and access. Its 2020 goal of 130MW of renewables capacity is probably too ambitious, as just 18MW had been installed as of 2017. However, a generous feed-in tariff and net metering scheme are designed to incentivize rooftop solar. Palestine does not have any currently operational large-scale power plants, and thus relies on electricity imports mainly from Israel. The emphasis on renewables is considered a means of achieving greater energy independence.

Renewable energy projects to date have been small at around 15-20MW, with the biggest being Sonelgaz's Sahara portfolio of 14 plants totalling 268MW. The country attracted $557 million of clean energy investment over 2006-17 but saw no big deals in the last three years. Despite its abundant solar potential, obstacles to investment include the level of bureaucracy, evolving regulatory framework and a weak financial sector. Stringent local content rules, if left unchanged, are likely to impact the cost of projects for developers by raising the cost of equipment and of finance, at least in the short term. In the short term, the government is also faced with the issue of having spent several billions of dollars in adding new gas capacity to the grid and upgrading existing power plants. This has resulted in a cooling of renewables ambitions as demand has been growing at a lower-than-anticipated rate.

With an energy sector dominated by large hydro plants, Angola has not received significant investment in utility-scale clean energy plants in recent years. However, its 2025 energy strategy will require substantial investment in renewables, much of which is likely to come in the form of concessional financing.

While Benin has attracted no clean energy investment from commercial sources to date, international and national concessional finance have been committed to the Millennium Challenge Account II program. The U.S., the main benefactor of the MCA II, has donated $375 million. The Benin government has contributed another $28 million on top of that. This funding will go toward the development of four solar PV projects: two 15MW plants in Bohicon and Parakou, 10MW in Djougou, and another 5MW plant in Natitingou are planned. On top of new solar developments, the program hopes to restore the Yripao Dam and install a second turbine to increase production to 1MW.

There is only one commissioned grid-scale renewable energy project in Botswana to date, the 1.3MW solar PV project near Phakalane. It was financed through a $12.5 million grant from the Japanese Government. This is the only utility-scale renewable project to get financed in the last five years. Therefore the current foreign investment share stands at 100%. However, according to the World Bank, many entities are not able to prepare project proposals that meet the criteria for international finance. For the 100MW   solar tender, developers suspect that local commercial banks won't be able to compete with international concessional organizations as their terms would be unfavourable to the local developers that are looking for long tenors. International commercial banks have yet to have the chance to participate as no utility-scale projects have been permitted.

The biggest new clean energy investment deals were for the 33MW Zagtouli PV plant, which commissioned in 2017, and the 15MW Essakane PV plant, which came online in 2018. Together, these deals totaled $115 million. The Zagtouli project, which signed a PPA with Sonabel, Burkina Fasos utility, was financed by international donors. The Essakane plant has a PPA with gold miner Iamgold and is partly financed by Banque Internationale pour le Commerce, lIndustrie et lArtisanat du Burkina (BICIAB), a BNP Paribas Group subsidiary, suggesting that commercial sponsors are also willing to invest in PV in Burkina Faso.

There has been significant under-investment in the energy sector over the last 20 years. As a result, the country has a relatively weak electrification rate of 8% nationally and 2% in rural areas, so there is significant scope for investment. The country has also opened its energy sector to privatization. Uptake of this opportunity has been limited, but one notable investment in 2017 included a 7.5MW solar plant. This was accompanied by a 25-year PPA, signed between the developer Gigawatt Global and the national utility, Regideso. Other foreign investment in the energy sector in Burundi has primarily been made by the World Bank, the African Development Bank, UNDP and European Investment Bank. Investment in rural electrification is being undertaken by the Burundian Agency for Rural Electrification, established by decree in 2011. The objective of this entity is to develop and implement rural electrification projects, including small-scale hydropower, solar and wind energy.
