Hydro projects have been the largest recipient of clean energy investment in Cameroon, with 5GW either announced or secured financing as of September 2018. Some small-scale solar projects have also closed financing in recent years, particularly for rural electrification, but investment in MW-scale projects has yet to gain traction. Cameroon is open to private finance. The biggest investors have been international organizations such as the World Bank, which financed $784.5 million in 2018 for the Nachtigal hydropower project. Investors from China, including firms such as Eximbank, are active in Cameroons hydro and solar sectors.

Clean energy investment has neither been a top priority for the state, nor has it been readily available or utilized. The majority, if not all, clean energy financing has come from international development banks. These projects have focused on updating the existing infrastructure and generation assets, rather than expanding the fleet of clean energy production. This is caused by a combination of ongoing conflict within CAR, poor performance from the state-owned utility Enerca, and a lack of policy to implement and support any incoming projects, and financial support.

A number of renewable energy projects have either been announced or are under way, starting from the low base of no substantial deployment to date. Investment is exclusively international and disbursed at concessional rates. August 2018 saw the announcement of the biggest such undertaking thus far in the 60MW Djermaya Solar project, backed by a 6.35 million-euro ($7.3 million) grant pledged by the EU. Chadian developer ZIZ and Schneider Electric are planning to construct a series of 1MW hybrid plants financed by the AFD. But funding is scarce  difficulties in securing financing were partly behind the repeated delays that afflicted Vergnets 1.1MW wind farm at Amdjarass, which finally came online for initial testing in late 2017.

There has been no real investment in renewable energy to date. Finance for prospective renewables initiatives would likely come from international donors, with organizations such as the French Development Agency, the African Development Bank and the World Bank currently underwriting transmission and capacity-building projects through grants and loans dispensed at concessional rates. Any concrete developments in this area are limited to small hydro feasibility studies carried out by the UN Development Program and a handful of small-scale solar systems.

Investment in clean energy projects in the DRC has been limited for a number of reasons. Political instability and currency volatility do not create an environment conducive to foreign investment. The countrys domestic banking sector is also not well set up to provide commercial finance. Hydropower remains the dominant form of energy generation, given the countrys significant river resources - notably the Congo River. The few announced solar projects are small-scale and linked to commercial mining activities or the telecoms industry.

There has been no recent investment in clean energy, except in the 275MW Soubre dam, financed 15% by the Ivorian state and 85% through a commercial loan with Chinas Exim Bank. Several other state-led hydro projects have been announced and are expected to follow similar financial structures, with a planned 10-15% participation from the state. Although a couple of independent power producers have announced biomass and solar projects, none has secured financing yet.

Eritrea has so far attracted some international aid for clean energy projects, but investment is very limited. There is no framework for public-private partnerships, and no incentives to attract international interest. Rapprochement with Ethiopia, agreed in summer 2018, could lead to a gradual opening of the economy to international involvement, but so far interest has been limited to the mining sector. This does offer opportunities for clean energy, as PV panels installed alongside diesel generators offer cost savings. However, this solution has only been implemented in one case so far.

New investment in clean energy in Ethiopia has been episodic, with jumps in investment corresponding to specific large-scale projects. After a geothermal financing in 2015, no new investment was seen until May 2018, when the Assela wind farm reached financial close through concessional funding from Denmark. Generating capacity is increasing rapidly, but much of the development is still driven by the government and by EEP. Large-scale investment, especially in hydro, has also come from China. Geothermal has also attracted considerable investment, in both resource exploration and project development.

Clean energy investment has stalled over the last couple of years as the government embarked on the PPA review, which delayed most renewables projects. The majority of investment in renewable energy in Ghana has come from foreign sources, with the largest solar project (20MW) being financed by Chinese investors. The African Development Bank is currently assessing opportunities to invest in renewables in Ghana and, while a number of domestic funds are looking to back renewables, they have yet to sign on the dotted line.

What little renewables funding exists comes from foreign actors such as the French development agency (AFD) and EU, mostly in the way of grants targeting rural electrification or small hydro feasibility studies. By and large, foreign investment in the energy sector has been funneled into large hydro, although concerns regarding variations in flow rates have led a number of developers to countenance hybrid dams kitted out with solar panels. Attracting funds has been complicated by the governments lack of financial headroom, ruling out sovereign guarantees for the foreseeable future. But the current administration is eager to lock down further concessional funding, with talks under way regarding launching projects through the International Finance Corp.s Scaling Solar initiative.

Geothermal accounts for 50% of Kenyas clean energy investments, which overall amounted to $3.4 billion between 2010 and 2Q 2018. Wind is in second place with 39% of investments. The feed-in tariff and significant past experience in geothermal development means uncertainty about exploration and development of new projects or capacity additions is relatively low, and loans are available from development finance institutions. The majority of the investment in the wind sector was asset financing for the 310MW Lake Turkana wind project. In October 2017, Kenya recorded the largest financing deal for solar in Sub-Saharan Africa, with the $80 million debt financing for M-KOPA, a pay-as-you-go solar firm. It was led by Kenya-based Stanbic Banks $55 million debt denominated in local currency.

Clean energy investment in the country to date has been limited but there is at least one IPP with approved financing and private sector support. The government put forward a well-structured investment plan to the World Banks Scaling Up Renewable Energy Program in November 2017. A $1.5-million preparation grant was subsequently approved for a utility-scale solar plant, through the African Development Bank, and for distributed renewable energy solutions, through World Bank. Uncertainty in energy policy and slow implementation of a renewable energy framework have hindered investment.

The lack of a transparent and uniform policy framework has hindered Liberian clean energy investment. Commercial lenders are yet to enter the market, leaving only concessional agencies to support the limited roll-out of rural electrification projects. Independent renewable power producers are not active, despite policy allowing project operators to sell power to the state-owned utility. However, the country has attracted some foreign private-sector involvement; most notably Manitoba Hydro International, which led the refurbishment of the Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant under tender from the Liberia Electricity Corp. (LEC).

Libyas power sector remains closed to private investors, so the country does not yet have a policy of providing financial guarantees to private investors nor has it established a green fund for renewable energy projects. Clean energy investment is in its infancy, and mostly concentrated on solar and wind power. Libya has signed contracts with foreign companies to build power plants and turbines, but this is entirely on government initiative. Due to the ongoing conflict in the region, clean power projects have been subject to numerous delays or have been abandoned altogether, which has impeded growth in renewables investment.

Clean energy asset finance for utility-scale projects to date has been limited to the self-funded 20MW project owned by Jirama for a value estimated at around $12 million. The other project in the pipeline is contracted through the Scaling Solar program and should be able to secure financing as a result of the guarantees and incentives provided to the winning developers.

Most financing to date has come from internal investment, through Malawi's Ministry of Natural Resources, Energy and Mining (MNREM); however, some has come from IPPs based in other countries. The planned 300MW Kammwamba coal-fired power plant has met all the 14 conditions that were set by the financiers AXIM Bank of China for Malawi to access the loan for the project.

The only grid-scale clean power plants commissioned since the 1980s are two hydro plants developed by Sogem, the only IPP in Mali. A few other projects have reached financial close, including a 50MW PV plant, financed through a mix of private foreign investment and international commercial loans, with one local bank also participating. The other projects are hydro plants and will be financed through a mix of grants, state funding and loans from institutions such as the World Bank. For off-grid projects, up to 80% of capital investment is subsidized, but the rest often comes directly from the operator's own funds rather than from bank loans. The mini-grid market has grown from almost nothing to more than 50 operators since 2003.

The government has overseen a steady increase in clean energy capacity since 2013, relying heavily on concessional funding, often from Persian Gulf donors. Highlights include the completion of several large PV projects, such as a 50MW plant commissioned in November 2017  the Arab Fund for Economic and Social Development footed the lions share of the projects $53 million costs. Two wind farms have been commissioned, the biggest weighing in at 15MW. Moreover, investing in structural reforms alongside renewables projects, the UN Development Program, the French development agency and the EU have spent considerable sums on rural electrification. While still at the planning stage, the Zourate 21MW PV plant looks to involve financing from several domestic banks, a first for Mauritania.

Moroccan solar tenders to date have stipulated storage requirements, to displace expensive generation from fuel oil currently used to meet high evening peak demand. Concessional finance from the World Banks Clean Technology Fund (CTF) has been key to kickstarting the Moroccan solar thermal industry. CTF and CTF MDB (co-financing) have totaled $1.3 billion across the Noor I-III and Noor-Midelt projects. This financing has in turn attracted a further $3.3 billion from multilateral and regional development banks. Developer finance and assumed equity make up the remaining $874 million of the Noor solar thermal projects as of 2018. In contrast, Moroccan wind projects have been successful in attracting significant amounts of commercial finance. Lured by the countrys world-class wind resource, commercial finance has provided some $894 million of the disclosed $1.76 billion invested in the wind sector since 2011. Total financing in the Moroccan wind sector is expected to reach $3.7 billion by 2020.

The majority of electricity in Mozambique comes from large hydro, with the power fleet seeing little funding over recent years. The latest investment has been in developing the domestic natural gas sector, which has grown rapidly since 2015. In terms of clean technology, the last decade saw Mozambique receive $0.94 million in biofuels investments and $57.2 million in solar. Moreover, a partnership between German aid agency GIZ and Funae  the countrys electrification agency  has developed mini-grid and pico-solar pilot programs.

The PV industry has so far attracted the largest share of clean energy investment (120MW over 5years), while the rest of the share went to two wind projects. Debt has been provided by local Namibian banks, as the PPA tariff is paid in Namibian dollars. On the equity side, projects have attracted a fair share of foreign investors, mainly from South Africa. However, the government introduced ownership rules in 2014 that limit the share held by foreign investors; for example, under the Refit program, at least 30% of the ownership of an IPP project must be allocated to previously disadvantaged Namibians. Meanwhile, high electricity prices are driving investments in off-grid solar battery systems, even in areas where the grid is available. Windhoek alone has an estimated 20MW of off-grid capacity.

As domestic banks do not fund renewables projects, finance has largely come from foreign donors. The EU and AFD have joined forces on two such undertakings, spending a combined 28.5 million euros ($33 million) on a 20MW solar plant at Gorou Banda and 32 million euros on a 19MW solar-diesel plant in Agadez. The World Bank launched the National Solar Electricity Access Project (NESAP) in March 2018, funding it over six years to the tune of $50 million. Other noteworthy funders include the African Development Bank and the Islamic Development Bank, both of which have long underwritten domestic energy projects. Further renewables deployment is to come, with 50MW of projects announced by Nigelec, the national utility.

In 2016, some 14 solar utility-scale projects totaling 1.4GW signed PPAs with NBET (Nigerian Bulk Electricity Trading). NBET, the bulk trader, act as the middle man between generators and distributors, they buy power from generators via U.S. dollar-denominated power purchase agreements and sell that power to the distributors. In order to reach financial close, lenders require developers to obtain a so-called put-call option agreement (PCOA), a Ministry of Finance document guaranteeing that if a project defaults (due to the developer or NBET) the government will pay lenders the outstanding principal in full. In March 2018, the former Minister of Finance, Kemi Adeosun, said the PPA tariff agreed with NBET of 11.5 U.S. cents/kWh was too high and developers should accept 7.5 U.S. cents, so no PCOAs have been signed or approved yet. Some developers have told BNEF that since PV capex has fallen drastically, they may accept the lower tariff. One developer has said it will reach financial close as early as December 2018, so construction could start in early 2019.

Investment in Rwandas clean energy space has been volatile, despite consistent year-on-year growth in electrification. Most historical on-grid investment has been in hydro, natural gas and solar, but national utility Rwanda Energy Group (REG) has halted all permitting for future on-grid generation due to a current oversupply. Most future investment in Rwandas energy market is expected to go toward expansion of the grid to meet this oversupply and to off-grid companies working with communities that wont have grid access in the near future. The financing matrix has been dominated by donor groups, most notably through a EUR 200m loan from the European Union and the World Banks Scaling Up Renewable Energy Program (SREP).

Energy project development in Senegal is becoming increasingly vibrant with new stakeholders seeking opportunity to invest. Four solar projects totaling 100 megawatts have come online in the last couple of years and in 2018, Senegals first utility-scale wind farm reached financial close.  Lekela is providing equity for the project and debt is being provided by U.S. and Danish development banks. Lekela is a joint venture between Dublin-based developer Mainstream Renewables, and Actis, a London-based private equity firm. Lekelas financial close shows the improved maturity of the energy market, particularly after the successful completion of several solar projects in the last year. Projects in Senegal continue to rely upon development bank finance, but the presence of foreign investors Meridiam and Lekela in the country highlight the growing maturity of the sector.

As stability returns following decades of political and social turmoil, the lack of stable policy mechanisms has hindered Sierra Leone clean energy investment from also recovering. Most rural electrification projects are sponsored by concessional agencies with little private sector involvement. However, a pico solar industry is maturing and independent renewable power producers are starting to see commercial lenders willing to finance projects that sell to the state-owned utility through a PPA . These financiers typically have experience in other, more mature, West African markets such as Ghana.

Somalia owes significant debt to a number of international financial institutions, which means that it is ineligible for international development aid and concessional financing from many other sources. As international efforts are ongoing to develop a plan toward debt relief, investment in Somalia comes through short- and medium-term grants. A number of international organizations are undertaking large-scale projects focused on the power sector and energy security. Somalia also receives significant remissions from its sizable diaspora living abroad, and IPPs are in some cases able to fund projects directly through this kind of investment.

Clean energy investment in South Africa has risen and fallen with the rounds of its auction program, with particularly high totals in years when winning projects had to reach financial close. In total, it attracted $16.7 billion over 2004-17 but that last four years have averaged just $1.4 billion each, as the auction scheme was on standby. Two-thirds of the 2004-17 total was spent on solar projects, with the solar thermal projects commanding a per-megawatt capex more than its PV cousin. South Africa has the most diverse mix of investor types in the region where typically renewables projects rely on concessional financing. Of the $15 billion of asset finance since 2004, 45% has come from (in particular, local) commercial banks and another 8% from private equity.

There is a lack of access to grid infrastructure which has impeded any growth in clean energy investment. Of the money that has been invested, most of it has come from international aid organizations and foreign governments. The African Development Bank loaned South Sudan $26 million in 2013 to increase access to clean energy  a project that is ongoing  and in 2017 a further $14.7million was loaned to the country. More recently, a Chinese-funded electricity pole plant was commissioned that is expected to help boost grid infrastructure and provide greater access to clean energy in the capital, Juba. The construction of a transmission grid is likely to open up further opportunities to investors in clean energy.

Difficulties in securing finance are first and foremost among the challenges facing developers. No domestic banks offer loans to developers investing in clean power, and years of international isolation coupled with crippling debts (the World Bank puts Sudans arrears at $50 billion) have left international financial institutions reluctant to bankroll renewable energy projects. Difficulties in attracting donors have translated into a lack of utility-scale renewables build-out. Although several projects have been announced, including a 100MW wind farm with a predicted cost of $217 million, all have struggled to secure funding. Investments have been limited to rural electrification schemes, with the United Nations Development Program and the government implementing separate initiatives to expand energy access through distributed renewables.

Clean energy investments in Tanzania have been sporadic, with a total amount of $248 million between 2010 and 2Q 2018. Nearly half of this is VC/PE finance for the off-grid solar companies such as Off-Grid Electric. Inconsistency in multiple long-term plans, lack of supporting mechanisms, and the high offtaker risk might have hindered investments into utility-scale renewable energy projects. The current trend is expected to continue as long as these challenges remain, and the administration maintains its priority on large-hydro and fossil fuel generation over renewables.

While Togo has no utility-scale clean energy projects as yet, existing rural electrification programs have attracted both international concessional finance and domestic commercial finance. The Cizo electrification program has received the support of local bank Union Togolaise de Banque (UTB). Furthermore, the World Bank is involved with reinforcing grid capacity in Lom and has contributed to the electrification roadmap. Togo hopes to see investment grow in the coming years to accompany the renewables law and contribute to reaching the ambitious target. The country expects in particular to attract foreign private investment.

Tunisia has received little investment in utility-scale clean energy so far, but that is poised to change as over 1GW of auction-winning projects are expected to be commissioned by end-2022. International development banks have been the main debt providers for Tunisia's clean energy plants. The countrys Fond de Transicion Energetique (FTE) will invest 2.13 billion Tunisian dinars ($730 million) in energy transition projects over the next decade. The budget has grown significantly, from 1.3 billion Tunisian dinars between 2006 and 2015.

Steady growth in both the on-grid and off-grid markets in Uganda has led to consistent clean energy investment. A myriad of development banks, foundations, private equity funds, local banks and impact funds, both domestic and international, have boots on the ground. Most of this investment has gone into hydro projects, with over 700MW commissioned to date and an additional 1GW of projects in the pipeline. Investment in the off-grid solar market has increased dramatically as well: through 2017, 270,000 solar home systems have been distributed in Uganda. Engies acquisition of Ugandas largest off-grid solar player, Fenix International, at the end of 2017 emphasizes strong investor appetite in the country from big name foreign players.

The 2015/16 drought had a devastating effect on the Zambian economy bringing annual GDP growth downwards from a mean 7%, between 2002 and 2014, to 2.92% in 2015, the lowest since 1998. With the resulting rise in electricity demand, Zambias investment into clean energy has shown positive and stable growth in recent years. The country remains highly dependent on hydro generation, which accounts for approximately 99% of renewables and 85% of overall generation. Despite solar having a minimal impact in the past, high solar irradiation values and declining technology costs promise strong potential for the development of PV-based generation, demonstrated by the IFCs Scaling Solar program and SIDAs Beyond the Grid Fund.  Wind energy potential in Zambia is relatively limited and is not particularly suitable for electricity generation.  Despite poor support from local debt providers, the country has received both international concessional and commercial support with the largest from the Export-Import Bank of China ($130 million).

Growth in clean energy investment has been slow. The single IPP offtaker, ZETDC, and the general economic situation of the country have not instilled confidence in investors. Although some projects have been awarded licenses, few of them have been constructed or commissioned in the last five years. If the country moves toward an auction approach, as the Zimbabwe Energy Regulatory Authority (ZERA) has indicated that it plans to from 2019, it will help create a transparent process and attract more interest from clean energy providers and IPPs. The immaturity of the market means there has been limited international financing available to projects. The controversial government-funded Gwanda Solar project has been riddled in corruption scandals from the start. Already three years behind schedule, the future of the project is unknown after recent parliamentary hearings.

All the renewable energy projects in the country have been fully supported by international donors, with the World Bank being the biggest contributor. The government by itself is not able to secure financing for these projects yet. Most investments have been made in the hydropower sector, followed by solar. There hasnt been much private sector involvement yet. However, the first segment of the Renewable Energy Policy had set goals to provide incentives such as interest subsidies, soft loans and tax exemptions to increase the private sector participation.

Clean energy investment in Armenia (aside from hydropower) has so far been small, with no large-scale projects currently built. Fotowatio, the winners of the first large-scale PV auction, plan to spend $50 million on the Masrik-1 project, backed by Armenias SREP program and the World Bank. Armenias energy ministry also provides a Renewable Resources and Energy Efficiency Fund to provide concessional financing. Loans for merchant projects have come from the European Development Bank and other international funds. Most investment has focused on solar power, as the countrys wind resources are far from its transmission lines. Additionally, the country has a power deficit in the summer, which matches the supply profile of solar much better than wind.

There has been very limited investment in clean energy so far, with only 123MW of installed capacity. This will obviously need to ramp up very quickly if the country is to meet its 2020 target of 4.2GW of renewables. There is no domestic financing option, with only international development banks active in the sector.

Clean energy investments in grid connected projects are rare in Bangladesh  all new money is flowing into a few rooftop solar projects being developed by export companies. Apparel manufacturers are responding to pressure from purchasers in the U.S. and Europe that aim to decarbonize their supply chains. No wind projects have been installed in Bangladesh in many years. This might change as USAID is conducting a wind-resource assessment that could be the basis for wind power policy and investments. Almost all renewable financing is provided by domestic lenders that in turn have access to credit lines from multilateral and development banks. Infrastructure Development Company Limited is the biggest recipient and disburser of renewable financing.

Like its neighbor Laos, Cambodia has directed power-sector investment toward large hydro and coal-fired power plants, as well as transmission and distribution, to support its electrification target. One 10MW solar plant has been built to date, by a Singaporean company with concessional finance support from the Asian Development Bank and the Canadian Climate Fund. There are few Cambodian banks or other financial institutions with the ability to support renewable energy projects at present, although some small banks, with assistance from Japanese parent companies, are hoping to increase the availability of domestic financing with capacity building.

After a dip in 2016 due to the wind and solar installation freeze in several curtailment-prone northern provinces, clean energy investment increased by 23% in 2017, to $132 billion. Since 2013, solar has surpassed wind to attract most funds. The gap between them was most pronounced in 2017, when the 53GW of new solar capacity attracted $86.5 billion, while wind only received $36 billion. Investment so far has come predominantly from Chinese sources, with the China Development Bank at 24% of total asset finance. Multilateral banks such as the World Bank have supported early development, and can provide international concessional finance. A large number of domestic banks, such as Industrial & Commercial Bank of China, provide commercial financing.

India was the worlds fifth largest clean energy investment market in 2017, jumping up from being the sixth largest in 2016. Clean energy investment totalled $7.4 billion in the first half of 2018, with solar power projects accounting for the majority. Indian companies issued $3.8 billion of green bonds in 2017 and issuances are expected to increase further as lenders and IPPs look to raise cheaper funds to meet their capital requirements. More recently, IPPs are starting to tap into public markets and private equity funding to raise capital. BNEF expects overall clean energy asset financing to surpass $12 billion in 2018.

Indonesia has seen very limited investment in solar and wind power, with geothermal accounting for around 90% of the $800 million raised in 2017. Its first large-scale PV plant in 2018 secured financing from the Asian Development Bank, which will invest $40 million in the 42MW of PV plants under development by Vena Energy across four locations. There is interest from commercial banks to participate in the renewables market but their involvement has been limited due to lack of investment-grade projects.

While Kazakhstan introduced the feed-in tariff in 2009, clean energy investment only really kicked off four years later. In total, it attracted $960 million between 2013 and 1H 2018. The country is looking forward to several major new projects in both solar and wind in order to meet its 20-50% target, potentially indicating that investment may rise in coming years. However, the Kazakh market faces a lack of liquidity in the aftermath of the financial crisis, and energy financing typically comes from international concessional or commercial sources. Local interest rates are above 12%.

Kyrgyzstan has not seen substantial investment in clean energy. Though the government has called for the construction of a fleet of new small hydro plants, the countrys installed small hydro capacity has remained flat in recent years and the deployment of other renewables, such as wind and solar, has been negligible to date. Still, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank are active in Kyrgyzstan, and these groups have provided grants to support various governmental clean energy and energy efficiency initiatives.

Laoss power market is currently oversupplied with carbon-free hydroelectricity, creating little incentive for the government or local companies to invest in non-hydro clean energy technologies. The bulk of recent investment  in large hydroelectric facilities and a single coal-fired plant  has been financed by Thailand and Vietnam for their own consumption. Only one large-scale solar project has been built to date in Laos, by a local company (EDL-GEN) but with significant support from international partners. China, Thailand, Japan and Vietnam are dominant players in the market. There is little to no domestic concessional financing available, and few Lao banks have the capacity to finance power projects.

Tax and financing incentives, like the Green Technology Financing Scheme, have contributed to the growth of clean energy investments. As of last year, 3.5 billion ringgit ($840 million) was approved to support 319 projects under the financing scheme. An additional 5 billion ringgit ($1.2 billion), approved in May 2018, is now available for investments over the next five years. In June 2017, the country also issued the worlds first green sukuk (Islamic) bond, which was used to finance large-scale solar projects awarded under the first auction for that technology. Solar projects continue to garner the most interest, and biogas and small hydro have good potential, whilst biomass consists of mostly legacy assets. Foreign involvement in the second solar auction increased, but limited foreign capital makes its way in as ownership limitations have deterred foreign participants from investing heavily.

Mongolia could supply 8,000TWh of wind power and 5,000TWh of solar power per year. However, renewable energy investment began relatively slowly, amounting to just $200 million over 2010-16. Then 2017 set a new annual record, at nearly $100 million, with the trend extending to 2018. Due to the nascent state of the renewables sector, the vast majority of investment has come from international development banks and foreign governments. The single largest investor is the European Bank for Reconstruction & Development, responsible for over a cumulative $120 million; and the largest local developer is Newcom Group. If the country is to meet its renewables target, it will need to attract significant investment.

Solar is the main source of clean energy for Myanmar given the countrys geographic location, falling prices of solar panels and easy installation both on and off grid. Investment interest in solar projects surged under the previous government with developers proposing dozens of projects, but only one utility-scale solar project has made progress  Green Earth Power Thailands 220MW project that kicked off with the first phase of 40MW in 2017. The governments perception of high cost and concerns of solars impact on grid stability have led to a halt in approving utility-scale solar projects. Heavily subsidized electricity tariffs make solar rooftops unattractive for many commercial and industrial users. Solar-plus-battery has been explored for off-grid applications, largely funded by the IFC-led Lighting Myanmar program. Recently, private capital has been flowing into the off-grid market lately propelled by the search for impactful investment returns.

Various funds have been set up by the government for the development of renewables, such as the Central Renewable Energy Fund and the Small Hydro Power Fund. However, the government is also aware that it will be unable to make sufficient investments on its own. Focus is on increasing foreign investments and drawing private players into the market. International donors such as World Bank, Asian Development Bank and UNDB have financed projects in the past, and policies and subsidies have been introduced to promote foreign direct investments as well. The country has the potential to attract more than 28 trillion Nepalese rupees ($268 billion) in foreign capital into energy sector by 2045 if it recognizes foreign direct investment as a top priority and implements policies and incentives to promote FDI, as quoted in Nepals 2017 Investment Summit.

The total installed capacity of solar, wind and biomass is set to cross 2,000MW by the end of 2018. Rooftop PV installations have picked up pace, as they are a means to avoid frequent power shutdowns, and also save on electricity costs. There are new high wind zones waiting to be developed. Overseas investors active in Pakistan's clean energy sector include Three Gorges from China and Zorlu Enerji from Turkey.  The multilateral development banks are also active in pushing energy access, as well as in promoting initiatives like smart metering. Most projects rely on some form of concessional financing.

The Philippines has seen scattered renewables investment. Geothermal and hydro initially made up most of the build, but spiking demand caused the government to lean toward conventional power. The EPIRA officially opened up generation to the private industry in 2001. Since then the generation sector has been dominated by thee major players. The country has had difficulty financing renewables due to challenging policy and infrastructure conditions. The government allows no more than 40% foreign ownership in projects. For developers, challenges such as becoming a Qualified Third Party (QTP) or Independent Power Producer (IPP) and bottlenecks in permitting make it difficult to secure financing for projects. The FiT, which is paid on the basis of actual production, ultimately was a losing proposition for many investors. Developers raced to commission projects, but to date about 360MW of commissioned solar intended to receive the FiT missed the cut to claim its benefits.

Clean energy investment in the country to date has been driven by the government-backed pilot schemes for floating and rooftop PV. The first SolarNova tender for 76MW was awarded in 2015 to Sunseap, with the second smaller tender for 40MW awarded to Million Lighting Co. in 2017. The most recent tender for 50MW was awarded in June 2018 to Sembcorp and Kurihara Kogyo. The terms of the SolarNova development contracts have not been disclosed but it has been reported that the winning bid for phase three was close to zero. Under the SolarNova Programme, developers must sign a service agreement to provide power to the HDB residences, but generation in excess of the terms of the service agreement can be sold into the wholesale market or contracted to other commercial and industrial customers. The zero bid reflects the expectation that costs can be recovered through the sale of excess generation. An example of this model is the recent announcement by Sembcorp that it has signed a 20-year agreement with Facebook to provide the company with renewable energy to power its offices and a new data center in the country.

Unlike any other country in South Asia, Sri Lanka boasts 100% electrification. New power plants are required to meet growing demand, and also to balance retirements. The island nation of about 20 million people has a large base of small hydro plants, is expanding wind and solar, and piloting newer technologies such as geothermal and wave energy. Multilateral lenders like the Asian Development Bank and IFC are active in the market, lending funds and providing technical assistance. Some of the recent smaller-sized solar projects auctioned are aimed at giving the local entrepreneurs an opportunity in this sector.

Solar has so far attracted most of the clean energy investment in Taiwan though investment in wind is poised to grow fast, largely because the government auctioned off 5.5GW of offshore capacity in 2018. Taiwan local banks have lent to solar projects, but are still becoming comfortable with the nascent offshore wind sector. As a result, early offshore wind deals have been led by foreign banks. International commercial financing may continue to play an important role through project finance and local green bond issuance.

Tajikistan has not seen any serious investment in clean energy. Though the government has called for the construction of small hydro and solar power plants, the countrys installed capacity for small hydro remains less than 300MW and no new solar plants have come online. Still, international development banks and public-private partnerships are making some progress. The Asian Development Bank approved a $10 million grant in 2013 to support green energy solutions in households and Pamir Energy, a public-private partnership, is investing in small hydro projects in rural parts of the country.

Stimulated by the attractive feed-in premium, also known as the 'adder', introduced in 2007, renewable energy capacity has grown significantly. Between 2010 to 1H 2018, asset financing for renewable projects totaled $9.7 billion. Within two years from the release of the 2015 Power Development Plan (PDP), Thailand has achieved almost half of its 2036 renewable energy capacity target. Among all technologies, solar accounts for majority of the growth. In its infancy, there were concessional financing programs from Clean Technology Fund, Asian Development Bank and International Finance Corp. Over the years, Thailand's conglomerates actively participated in the development of renewables projects. Local commercial banks have supported the energy transition in Thailand, and as they familiarized themselves with the renewable technologies, actively financed projects in the country.

There is no significant installed renewables capacity in Turkmenistan and no clear strategy by the Ministry of Energy to grow the sector. Barring any clear direction set by the President's office, the forecasted growth of renewables is very limited. And, since the country has a closed off economy, private international finance is difficult to obtain.

Clean energy investment has seen a large increase in the past year as the country marked its first major project, a 1GW PV plant developed by SkyPower Global at an approximate cost of $1.3 billion. This is a significant step toward the estimated $6 billion required to achieve the countrys clean energy targets. To date, financing for this project is not complete; however, funds will be raised almost entirely from international private financiers. The government has allocated only $80 million to clean energy investment and expects the remainder to come from foreign sources.

Clean energy investment is expected to pick up as approved wind and solar projects obtain financing. The clean energy investments in the first half of 2018 is close $1 billion, which is higher than the past annual clean energy investments. Small hydro makes up the majority of current renewables investments in the country but solar and wind will dominate in new investments. The Vietnam Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development is one of the biggest investors in renewable energy. Some of the other major investors include Asian Development Bank, Sumitomo and local financiers like State Bank of Vietnam and Vietnam Development. There is limited participation from foreign banks and funds owing to concerns about the bankability of PPAs.

Most investment in clean energy over the last five-years has gone into small hydro projects. It is difficult to estimate the exact share of foreign investment, but the majority of projects are built by local developers. The exception is the 73MW Banje power station, which is owned and funded by Statkraft, the Norwegian utility. The market for clean energy is open to foreign investment and it is likely that any future large-scale wind or solar projects will attract foreign investors. To date, international concessional financing has been key for clean energy projects, specifically small hydro. Concessional finance has also helped projects raise debt finance from domestic and international commercial banks, such as Italy's Intesa and Austrias Raiffeisen.

The countrys maiden wind farm  the 50.6MW Mesihovina project  began producing electricity in March 2018. The facility was built at a cost of $101.4 million. While Siemens provided the turbines, the project was primarily financed through a loan provided by KfW, a German state-owned development bank. Meanwhile, the BiH government has launched a tender for the construction of a 65MW solar project. Most renewables investment has come from international concessional lenders, including the International Finance Corporation, European Investment Bank and European Bank for Reconstruction and Development. In addition to domestic funds and government grants, organizations such as the United Nations Development Program, GIZ and USAID provide co-financing as well as technical assistance.

Financing is well established and widely available for hydro projects, where the country has domestic expertise. Wind and solar projects use both domestic and international concessional financing from the Georgian Energy Development Fund (GEDF) and USAID. Most of the foreign investment interest has come from the Czech Republic, Germany and Asia. The potential for new wind and solar development is bringing in European players. The government believes that local banks would finance projects commercially, if there was an economic case, but without a feed-in tariff, this looks unlikely in the near future. The single wind and solar plants operating today were majority financed by the GEDF as demonstration projects.

Macedonia was the first country in the Western Balkans to erect a sizeable wind farm  a 36.8MW project at Bogdanci. The government is offering concessions for investors looking into funding small hydropower plants. Finance for wind and small hydro projects has mainly come from such international concessional donors as the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, with local developers or the state utility providing smaller equity stakes. However, the current administrations focus appears set on channeling investment into non-renewables sources, whether in bolstering coal and gas-derived capacity or attempting to attract investors to construct three new large hydro facilities.

Russia has only built a handful of wind and solar projects, but about 5GW of wind, solar and small hydro capacity is in the pipeline. While many developers have missed commissioning targets for projects awarded in early renewables auctions, the arrival of foreign players such as Fortum, Enel, Lagerway and Vestas in the last two rounds suggests Russia may actually start to bring awarded clean energy capacity online. Regardless, the country will continue to produce a significant share of power from low-carbon sources. Nuclear and large hydro, for example, account for about 19% and 17% of Russias power generation mix, respectively.

Over the last five years, when excluding small hydro, renewables capacity has grown at a CAGR of 44%. The majority of this is thanks to the financing of large-scale wind farms, sourced from domestic banks, foreign banks and money from impact funds. One of the biggest investors in Serbia's clean energy sector is MK Fintel  a joint venture between Serbia's MK Group and Italy's Fintel Energia  and it is expected to build around 60% of the country's 500MW wind capacity target. Beyond traditional energy players, the country's wind sector has also attracted financing from Masdar, a subsidiary of Abu Dhabi's Mubadal Investment Co., where it bought a 60% stake in the 158MW under-construction Cibuk 1 wind farm.

Investment in clean energy grew steadily in Turkey over 2012-17, with wind dominating the totals and accounting for more than $1 billion each year over that period. Solar saw a surge in investment in 2017 as unlicensed projects rushed to commissioning before transmission costs increased. However, investment in clean energy has stagnated in 2018, amid policy uncertainty and ongoing political uncertainty and currency fluctuations. Turkey holds auctions for pre-licenses, which are required for renewables projects to reach commissioning, and after two auctions held in 2017 no more have been announced for either wind or solar, leaving developers with no route to bring projects online.

Clean energy investments in Ukraine have been rising in the past few years, spurred by regulatory and legislative reforms that are increasing transparency. The biggest investments so far have been made by local developers, including Ukraines largest non-state utility DTEK, which is building the 200MW Primorskaya wind plant in the Zaporizhia Region. DTEK is also behind what will be Europes largest solar plant, the 246MW Nikopol plant in Dnipropetrovsk. Chinas Trina Solar said in October 2018 it had delivered 123MW of panels for the plant. Foreign investors have also started testing the market. Acciona Energia began construction of the 55 million-euro, 57MW Dymerka solar project in 3Q 2018. Engie, which has reportedly been in discussions over a solar plant to be built in the Chernobyl nuclear plant exclusion zone, in 2017 became the first foreign company to gain a gas import license for Ukraine and appears to be concentrating its efforts in the gas sector. Finance is available from some local banks, such as Ukragazbank, but the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development and other international institutions are the main source of funding, while U.S.-based OPIC has been offering insurance against political risk for some energy investments.

A scarcity of capital, price-distorting subsidies, and political risk combined to make Argentina a relatively unappealing destination for clean energy investment in the first half of this decade. That began to change in December 2015 with the arrival of President Mauricio Macri. Since then, Macris government has sought to cut subsidies and liberalize energy markets to spur conventional and renewable project build underwritten with foreign capital. FODER, created under his administration, was backed by the World Bank, which provided guarantees of payments for the renewable tenders. The guarantees boosted confidence among foreign debt providers. Only then, Argentina started to see financing in the sector, accounting for $3.1 billion in the past two years. Despite recent progress, Argentinas current macroeconomic crisis may push investors away and create difficulties for auction-winning projects that have yet to secure financing.

Development of clean energy projects in Bolivia is dominated by state-owned Empresa Nacional de Electricidad (ENDE), with investment coming from international development banks and the Central Bank of Bolivia. Non-hydro activity remains modest. The countrys first solar plant was commissioned in 2015, a 5MW project located in Pando department, which was followed by two more plants totaling 65MW brought online in Tarija and Potosi in 2018, all developed by ENDE. Bolivias first wind farm, Qollpana phase I (3MW) was commissioned in 2014 with a second phase (24MW) brought online in 2016. Wind projects lead the near-term pipeline, with four projects totaling 132MW having secured financing over 2017-18, also developed by ENDE and mostly located in Santa Cruz. A 50MW PV plant with financing from European development agencies is expected online in Oruro in 2019.

Brazil attracted almost $57 billion in new asset finance for clean energy plants in 2010-17, by far the largest amount in Latin America over the period. Wind alone accounts for 56% of the total, while solar attracted just 6%. However this is due to increase as solar developers have secured almost 2GW in contracts in the 2017-18 auctions.  Brazilian national development bank BNDES has played a major role in the development of the countrys renewable energy market. The bank is the top global lender to clean energy, having disbursed $27 billion for renewable energy (excluding large hydro) projects between 2008 and 2017.  In addition, BNDES applies a strict local content requirement in granting wind and PV project loans, spurring equipment manufacturers to build factories in the country.

Chile recorded $10 billion of clean energy investment between 2013 and year-end 2017. The country has many types of financial organizations investing in renewables, including development and commercial banks. The U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) has been the main lead arranger in the country, injecting $557 million into PV assets over the period. For distributed generation, however, it is a different scenario. Although distributed PV generation has expanded strongly in 2018 (from 12MW in January to 20MW in September), the lack of cheap financing, as well as bureaucracy, remain obstacles for the sector.

Colombias first long term power auction, scheduled to take place January 2, 2019, is expected to drive increased investment in renewables. The auction, which will be technology neutral, will offer a local currency, 10-year year power purchase agreement (PPA). Colombias Ministry of Mines and Energy has announced plans to contract 3,443GWh per year to be supplied from December 2022 onwards, which the government estimates would translate into approximately 1GW of capacity. Most investment directed to non-hydro renewable energy in Colombia to date has come from international development banks, including the IFC's loan to Celsia's solar PV portfolio, which includes Colombia's lone commissioned solar plant as of October 2018. However, growth in renewables will likely change this in the near term. Enel's 86 MW El Paso PV Plant, currently under construction, is likely financed from that company's balance sheet, though no information has been disclosed about the financing structure.

Costa Rica attracted $1.9 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-2017. Over a third of the total was directed to small hydro plants ($0.7 billion), followed by geothermal with $0.6 billion and wind with $0.5 billion. Investment peaked in 2014 with almost $0.6 billion provided to the three technologies, but it dropped by half in 2016 and 2017.

The Dominican Republics clean energy sector attracted $1 billion of investment over 2010-17. Wind energy accounted for the bulk of it, with $559 million, followed by solar with $256 million. Almost half ($260 million) of the wind investment was recorded in 2017 to finance two plants with a combined capacity of 97MW. Most renewable energy projects are financed by project developers and multilateral investment banks. Commercial banks have limited participation in the market.

Investments in clean energy in Ecuador are very small. Since 2011, the total invested amounted to only $500 million, mainly in small hydro assets. Development banks Inter-American Investment Corporation and Corporacin Andina de Fomento (CAF) are the biggest lead arrangers in the country, mainly investing in small hydro.

El Salvador's clean energy sector attracted $926 million of investment over 2010-2017. Over half of the investment was directed to PV plants, which received $532 million, followed by $250 million for biomass and waste. Largely due to its successful clean energy auctions, over 65% of the total was recorded in 2016-17.

Guatemala attracted $1.3 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-2017. Over a half of the total was directed to biomass and waste ($728 million), followed by small hydro with $271 million, and solar with $176 million. Investment peaked in 2014 with $657 million provided, but dropped continuously over the following three years to $92 million in 2015, $29 million in 2016, and $9.5 million in 2017.

Haiti has not seen any investment for clean energy in recent years. This is similar to the trend seen with fossil fuels, with the total installed capacity only increasing marginally over the last five years. The only investors available for financing are international development banks  domestic financial institutions do not invest in renewable energy projects. Electricit dHati (EDH), the national electricity company, has received grants from the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank and other international organizations to help the company improve its infrastructure.

Hondurass clean energy sector attracted $2.3 billion over 2010-2016, driven by high investment in solar energy of $1.2 billion between 2014 and 2016. These investments were boosted by a feed-in premium that came into force in August 2013. A renewable energy feed-in premium is applicable to electricity generation from renewable resources independent of project capacity or power. Additionally, PV projects installed by July 31, 2015 (or up to 300MW of installed capacity) received a base price for their energy equal to the short-term marginal cost plus $0.03/kWh plus 10%.

Jamaica attracted $0.4 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-17. Wind energy was responsible for the highest investment in this period ($187 million), followed by solar with $134 million. Wind investment peaked in 2015 after renewable energy auctions, which commissioned 60MW of wind plants and one 20MW PV plant.

A substantial increase in opportunities brought about by energy reform has transformed Mexico into a leading destination for new clean energy investment. The second largest power market in Latin America, Mexicos installed renewables capacity represents 9% of its 76GW total. This share is expected to increase as a result of new investment in the countrys excellent solar and wind resources, as well as auction mechanisms put in place by energy reform. Clean power investments jumped more than sixfold from 2016 to 2017, to $6.2 billion. Mexicos financing landscape is diverse, with project developers, commercial banks and development banks all playing important roles. Wind projects, in particular, have been historically successful in attracting investment. Rapid cost declines for both wind and solar have been seen in recent years, a trend that is expected to continue and which will pressure the countrys growing natural gas sector.

Nicaragua attracted $942 million in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-16, but none was disbursed in 2017. Wind has accounted for the highest share claiming a third of the total, followed by small hydro with $218 million and geothermal with $215 million.

Panama's clean energy sector attracted $1.5 billion of investment over 2010-2017. From 2013 to 2017 the country received larger investments in solar and wind energy, which led to a jump in installed capacity from zero in 2014 to almost 400MW in 2017.

As nearly the entirety of electricity in Paraguay comes from large hydro, the country has not received significant clean energy investment in recent years. In 2011 Paraguay received $28 million for biofuels investments.

Peru attracted $2.3 billion in clean energy investment from 2011 to 2017. Most of the investments were into small hydro and onshore wind projects, equivalent to 39% and 32% of the total. Peru saw a peak in investment throughout 2012-2014, mostly led by financing of auction projects. In recent years, funds injected in the country have faded away, as only $300 million was invested in 2017. The country has received capital from international and national commercial financial institutions, as well as development banks. The biggest lead arrangers are U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) and European Investment Bank, registering $235 and $213 million on PV and onshore wind.

Investments in Uruguay peaked in 2015, registering $1 billion in that year, mostly destined to wind assets. Driven by auction activities, investments in clean energy summed to $4.4 billion since 2011. More than 80% of that was invested in wind, followed by solar. Foreign investments are by far the biggest contributions. The biggest lead arrangers are Inter-American Development Bank and Inter-American Investment Corporation, proving debt to wind and PV projects. In 2017, investments reduced significantly, registering only $200 million, all in wind assets.

Clean energy investment levels in Egypt fluctuate year on year, depending on individual deals. 2017 was no exception when the second round of the feed-in tariff program helped the country secure a record $2.6 billion  up from around $430 million in 2016. As is common for renewables deals in Egypt, most of the financing for the feed-in tariff projects came from concessional investors (in this case, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and World Bank's International Finance Corporation). Indeed, the majority  or 88% over 2004-17  of total clean energy investment came from foreign sources. Japan and Germany account for the largest shares, at 21% and 14% respectively, largely because they are home to development banks, JICA and KfW. The feed-in tariff scheme required that a certain share of investment came from domestic sources.

Hydro and solar have been the focus of renewables investment in Iraq to date. Despite 2.5GW of installed hydro capacity, just over half is available to generate due to damages and aging infrastructure. In 2016, the Ministry of Energy awarded Al Dana International Co. of Kuwait and Sama Baghdad Power Co. of Jordan tenders to build 695MW of PV. Since then, further tenders have come to a standstill and the ministrys PV investment plan has fallen behind schedule. Financing renewables projects in Iraq is difficult with private investors forced to rely on local banks that lack experience in financing larger projects. With just 50% of electricity lost before billing and only 50% of bills collected, there is a high perception of risk surrounding the sector.

Wind and solar have been the focus of renewable investment to date with 533MW of solar and 197MW of wind currently operational. The government is launching a 30MW battery storage project and has requested proposals for its development by the end of 2018. It has targeted a further 70MW of battery storage capacity pending the outcome of the project. Traditionally international development banks have provided financing for renewable projects, however, an increasing number of domestic banks and private equity funds are active in the market. As such, financing for renewable projects in Jordan is both well established, and the process of securing finance is less onerous than elsewhere in the region.

The deployment of renewables started very recently in Kuwait, translating into high growth rates from a very small base. The bulk of renewable generation is solar (both PV and solar thermal), with onshore wind accounting for the rest. No other renewable energy technologies are set to be developed, but some hybrid projects are in planning. The country does not have financial institutions solely dedicated to green investments, but domestic banks have been active in financing energy projects, namely the first phase of the Az Zour North Natural Gas Power and Water Plant. Still, the concept of project finance is quite new and the vast majority of renewable projects under development have secured funding from foreign companies.

The current pipeline of renewables projects will ensure strong growth in the sector in Lebanon. Following the signature of PPAs for 180MW of solar in 2017, the PPAs for the first 200MW of wind  developed in the country were signed in February 2018 at a price of $113/MWh. The next solar auction will add a further 300MW and will include battery storage. The Lebanese Centre for Energy Conservation received 75 expressions of interest for this project, including both local and major international developers such as ACWA Power, First Solar and Tesla, amongst others. The next phase of 200-400MW of wind projects received 42 EOIs by the deadline in April 2018. Investment in the first round of auctions has come mostly from domestic sources.  The National Renewable Energy Action Plan targets $ 1.7 billion of investment to develop the renewables sector.

Work started on the aforementioned 50MW wind farm in August 2017. Early 2018 saw 28 companies bidding in an initial tendering round for the 500MW PV plant  the final stage will be held by the years end. In October 2018, the OPWP announced a 500MW-1GW solar project by issuing a consultancy tender for the so-called Solar 2022 IPP. Encouraging participation from domestic IPPs, the regulatory authority launched the Sahim initiative, which aims to install rooftop PV on 10-30% of Omans residential buildings. Successive annual solar tenders are to be issued from here on out, with capacities starting at 500MW. The OPWP also intends to attract bids for 150-200MW wind projects.

The growth rate of clean energy has been dismal to date, with significantly more talk than actual project development. Renewables represent less than 1% of installed capacity in the country. Structural obstacles such as subsidized energy prices and the concentration of power generation assets among just a few institutions stymie development. These institutions await direction from higher government authorities regarding development responsibilities. A chicken and egg situation also exists in that there are substantial localization mandates, but renewable technology vendors are reluctant to establish local manufacturing in case policy shifts and markets do not materialize.

Investment in renewables has been considerable  $400 million went towards funding solar plants in 2017 alone. Spending is set to skyrocket: the U.A.E. has pledged $163 billion in spending on renewables by 2050. Home-grown players such as Masdar have led a number of consortiums heading the countrys main projects, such as the Shams Power solar thermal plant, commissioned in 2013 and owned by the Abu Dhabi-based developer (80%) and Total (20%). The project was underwritten to the tune of $600 million by a group of 10 foreign and domestic banks, underlining the extent to which sources of finance are diversified. International developers, investors and banks have invested considerable sums in the countrys renewable energy initiatives.

Investment in clean energy comes from international development organizations and other countries, especially in the Persian Gulf, reaching a total of $76 million in 1H 2018. The Palestine Investment Fund and the Arab Bank are financing a $20 million solar portfolio to be developed in the West Bank. The PIF's subsidiary Massader invests in large-scale infrastructure projects, including the $80 million Noor Palestine solar program.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Clean energy projects developed so far have benefited from feed-in tariffs, Algerias primary renewables support mechanism to date. The feed-in tariff is awarded for 20 years for wind and solar, and 15 years for cogeneration. The rate will change after the first five years of operation and will only be paid for a limited number of hours a year, after which electricity will be sold at conventional prices. Conventional prices are predominantly set by the cost of producing domestic gas and are relatively low as a result, especially considering the relative competiveness of renewables is hurt by stringent local content requirements.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Angolas residential and commercial electricity prices have not changed since 2013 at $33.5/MWh and are among the lowest prices across emerging markets. As such, there is little incentive for consumers to install small-scale PV. The country does not have an industrial tariff or a wholesale power market.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Benins electricity prices are comparable to those in neighboring Togo. Overall, prices have decreased over the past couple of years, due to currency fluctuations rather than a change in tariffs (they havent changed since 2010). There is talk of raising the tariffs in 2019 as new local electricity production is more expensive than existing imports.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: For decades, electricity in Botswana has been heavily subsidized, however, this is slowly changing as tariffs have increased in recent years.  The private consumer only pays 0.28t pula/kWh (10.32 Pula = 1 USD), while Botswana Power Corps (BPC) production costs are 0.50 pula/kWh, dispatching power at a loss. In an effort to create more cost reflective tariffs, BPC has gradually increased the tariffs and steadily reduced the subsidy from 2.4 billion pula to 1.4 billion pula with the intention to reduce it further to 800 million pula in 2018. Electricity tariffs have risen consistently over the last decade at an average of 10% annually. Up until three years ago   residential consumers paid the highest electricity tariffs. BPC now charges their biggest customers, industrial users, the highest tariffs. This may need to be reviewed after the largest state mine in the country, BCL Mine Ltd., was forced into liquidation and closed in 2016.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The regulator ARSE sets a national fixed electricity tariff, with no distinction between the prices for commercial, industrial and residential users. The tariff has been stable over the last five years, but it is not cost reflective. Burkina Faso has one of the highest costs of electricity in the region, as it needs to import expensive diesel to run its thermal power plants. As electricity tariffs do not recover costs, Sonabel relies on government subsidies and has been incurring losses since 2011.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity tariffs are set by the monopoly electricity supplier, Regideso. Power prices are extremely high, considering the high proportion of hydro, with average tariffs being among the world's most expensive. The growing gap between power supply and demand that is driving these high prices is largely due to grid inefficiencies and a lack of investment into new infrastructure. There is also a heavy reliance on expensive fossil fuel imports to run the thermal power plant in the capital, as no indigenous sources are available. This drives prices up due to import taxes and limited access to foreign currency reserves  and black market exchange rates are prohibitively high. This also affects companies and consumers when they run diesel generators during blackouts. A number of Burundis businesses are currently self-generating their energy using expensive firewood or peat, and have great interest in sourcing renewables to reduce costs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The Electric Sector Regulation Agency (ARSEL) sets the electricity tariffs, which are relatively high for the region, particularly for a hydro-dominated market, owing to high transmission costs (including grid distribution losses of about 30%). The government subsidizes the tariffs by transferring funds to the monopoly utility, Eneo, paying some $20.6 million over 2012-18. Hydro remains Cameroons cheapest source of electricity, but recent growth in small-scale and off-grid solar suggest these are becoming increasingly competitive in rural areas away from the three separate power grids. Grid operators must buy excess production from renewables installations, but no price is specified and they may not buy electricity at above-market rates, limiting the policys effectiveness.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The government artificially keeps power prices stable over time   not through the use of subsidies, but driven by the populations low electricity usage. This contributes to the poor financial performance of the state-owned utility, and could act as an inhibitor for foreign investment. Compared the Democratic Republic of Congo, industrial and residential electricity prices are similar to those in CAR. But commercial prices are much lower. With regards to technology costs in the country, it is difficult to determine due to the very low pipeline of any capacity additions. The very few projects that have been announced lack detail and are currently on hold due to the ongoing political disturbances which prevent progress from being made.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Although retail tariffs are heavily subsidized, amounting to around half the average production cost of around 251 CFA/kWh ($0.43 based on the average 2017 exchange rate), consumers face higher bills than neighboring states such as Cameroon. Tariffs have remained stable, having last been tweaked in the 2012, when they were slightly reduced. Seeing the government is squarely committed to increasing the wider populations access to cheap electricity, there is little chance of rates being increased in the short term.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail power prices are lower than in neighboring Gabon, Cameroon and the Central African Republic, and are cheap when compared to the region as a whole. They are kept far below production costs by substantial subsidies: only tariffs in the Democratic Republic of Congo are lower. Another hurdle stymying investment is illegal connections, which are thought to siphon off 50% of the state utilitys output. Prices are unlikely to be increased in the near future, the focus being on getting the recently formed state utility on its feet while putting the screws on bill-dodging consumers. Only one IPP sells electricity, with the state utility purchasing electricity from Enis thermal plant at a rate of 45,000 CFA/MWh ($76.20 based on the average 2017 exchange rate).

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The DRC has a regulated electricity tariff that has only marginally changed over the last few years. Residential customers are charged one of the lowest tariffs in the world, which dooes not even cover the utilitys (SNEL) operational costs. However, there have been recent increases to residential tariffs due to a devaluation in the Congolese franc, according to reports. There has been little change to the levelized costs of electricity in the DRC due to a lack of new projects being built. Most electricity is purchased by consumers at a fixed lump sum as meters are very scarce, leaving much at the discretion of officials. Furthermore, it is also common for public institutions (schools, health centers and public enterprises) to have large amounts overdue on their electricity bills.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Cote d'Ivoire are among the lowest of the region thanks to the use of gas and hydro resources. Production costs have not followed any specific trend and depend mostly on the fuel cost, as well as the share of thermal generation in the total mix. Despite those low costs, the sector has been running on a deficit and there is regular pressure from international organizations to increase retail prices. In 2016, an attempt at increasing prices led to riots in several cities in the country, forcing the government to abandon the measure.  A year later, it announced that tariffs would be frozen up to 2018, although there is ongoing pressure from the World Bank. Despite this, offtaker risk remains low as the utility is a financially sound company, owned by Eranove, itself linked to the private equity firm Emerging Capital Partners.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices are regulated in Eritrea, but nearly all the on-grid capacity is diesel generation. Diesel costs in Eritrea are among the most expensive in Africa, but the full brunt of the costs are not passed along to the consumer. Wind and solar resources are good, but financing costs are likely high.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Ethiopia are subsidized below a cost-reflective level. Due to its fully renewable power mix however, generation costs are fairly low  considerably lower than its neighbors  as they are not exposed to fuel prices. The government has plans to introduce cost-reflective electricity tariffs in order to improve the financial health of the EEP. These plans were adopted the Council of Ministers in August 2018, and will be the first tariff adjustment in 13 years.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Ghana has some of the highest power prices in the region, due to an inefficient transmission system, with high losses, and a failure to effectively collect revenue. As a result, the power-price spike in 2016/17 became one of the main focuses of the 2016 election. As part of his campaign, President Nana Akufo-Addo promised to lower electricity tariffs to help industry. In March 2018, acting on the Presidents promise, the government unveiled new electricity tariffs that were up to 30% lower than the previous rates. The reductions were also extended beyond just the industrial sector to residential and commercial customers as well. The new tariffs are not reflective of the cost of generation and transmission, and so are heavily subsidized.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Domestic power prices, which have been unchanged over the last decade, are among the regions lowest. The government is eyeing future tariff increases as a necessary measure to buttress reforms, yet an outbreak of riots following a fuel price hike in February 2018 may stay the governments hand in the short term. Alterations to current rates are to be based on an ongoing African Development Bank tariff study, which is likely to conclude that retail bills should be raised by 30% over three years in order to facilitate the state electricity companys recapitalization. Insofar as power purchasing by the utility is concerned, EDG agreed to pay China Water and Electric around $85/MWh for energy produced by the 240MW Kalta dam, which was completed in 2015.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Kenyas electricity tariffs are set by the Electricity Act of 2006. On August 1, 2018, the Electricity Regulation Commission scrapped the monthly fixed charge of 150 Kenyan shillings for all the consumer categories. This has led to the reduction in the overall unit power price from 23.49 Kenyan shillings/kWh to 20.18 Kenyan shillings/kWh, a 14% drop. The power prices in Kenya are higher compared to the neighboring large economies such as Ethiopia and Tanzania, where cheap large-hydro power is available and the government regulates the tariffs lower than the costs respectively. Power prices could decline in Kenya after new renewable energy capacity is added and cheaper hydro electricity is imported from Ethiopia.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The utility Lesotho Electricity Co. says it must import approximately 282GWh a year (2016/17) of electricity from South Africa (Eskom) and Mozambique (EDM). The imports are priced between 0.77 to 1.50 maloti/kWh ($0.05-0.10), substantially higher than the price of power from its only power station, Muela Hydro (0.13 maloti per kWh). In 2015, electricity imports accounted for two-thirds of the utility's supply cost. The country has significant untapped renewable energy resources and has plans to procure further large hydro. The maloti is pegged to the South African rand.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Liberias retail electricity prices have declined significantly in recent years as a result of the refurbishment of Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant, which brought a low-cost supply to the heavily constrained power system. Regulated tariffs, which are equal across all customer types, dropped by more than 40% over 2015-17, to USD 0.35/kWh today, and further reductions are expected in the next 12 months. Beyond this, a pressing need for substantial investment in the LEC grid may place upward pressure on rates, while the development of renewable energy generators to capture share from diesel generators selling back to LEC may further contain costs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Energy prices in Libya are highly-subsidized and are among the lowest in the region, leading to inefficiency in the allocation of resources. Residential prices are broken down into three tiers as follows: 20 dirham/kWh for consumption of 1-1,000kWh; 30 dirham/kWh for 1,001-1,400kWh and 50 dirham/kWh for more than 1,400kWh.
