Electricity prices in other sectors are charged a fixed tariff of 68 dirham/kWh for commercial users, and 31 dirham/kWh for light industry or 42 dirham/kWh for heavy industry. Libya needs to implement significant subsidy reform in its energy sector but so far the country has not set plans to tackle this issue.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The government purchases the fuel for diesel generation in bulk and finances a budget gap at the main utility which is required to retail electricity below its extremely high costs. However, current power procurement costs are well above those of renewables technologies. The government is aware that renewables offer a good solution for reducing the cost of producing electricity in Madagascar and should continue to create opportunities for project developers as a result.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Average commercial and industrial electricity prices fell in 2017 after a large rise in the preceding year, with residential tariffs increasing 6%. With coal being cheaper than diesel, electricity prices are expected to fall as the three new coal-fired plants currently in the planning phase come online by 2021. Malawi is not connected to power systems with neighboring countries and cannot therefore benefit from membership of the Southern African and the East African Power Pools.  A plan to interconnect with Mozambique and Zambia for the purchase of at least 150MW is being developed.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Mali is a landlocked country that relies heavily on fossil fuel imports. Production costs are high, and the utility is running at a deficit despite subsidies from the state. The average cost for delivering electricity to the end-users was estimated at $0.25/kWh in 2016, more than the double the worldwide average. The electricity tariff was $0.16/kWh on average, so was not cost reflective. Retail tariffs have been relatively stable since 2004, with only slight increases in 2009 and 2014.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity is currently imported from Mali within the framework established by the Senegal River Basin Development Authority (OMVS) at a rate of around $50/MWh. Generous subsidies have kept retail tariffs stable and low compared with other countries in the region. But while the overwhelming majority of citizens pay discounted social rates bankrolled by the state, rural consumers are faced with steeper bills levied by microgrid operators. This disparity has long been contentious; the UNDP is carrying out a series of studies designed to amend the tariff system.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Morocco are subsidized  the state utility, the Office Nationale de lElectricit et de lEau potable (ONEE) does not pass on the full cost of generation to consumers and operates at a loss. Government support of the energy sector is a strain on public finances but has been rationalized within a developmental context. Servicing the 5% growth rate in electricity demand and the acute evening peak remains a primary concern in securing new generating capacity, with much of this slack having been met with expensive diesel generators. The difficulty and expense in meeting evening peak demand has resulted in storage requirements being added to Moroccan solar tenders and electricity tariffs that are 40% higher during the evening for commercial and industrial clients. The high cost of meeting the evening peak justified a PPA for the Noor I solar thermal project of $189/kWh in 2013, which includes five hours of storage. However, Moroccan and global PPAs for solar thermal have fallen since then, and the presence of existing solar thermal expertise and supply chains in the country, combined with PV hybridization, are fueling expectations of a competitive PPA for the Noor-Midelt projects to be announced by the end of 2018. In 2016, the PPA for 850MW of wind projects awarded to the Enel-Siemens-Nareva consortium set a world record price of $30/MWh on average. PPAs for PV auctions to date are unknown; however, most projects have been commissioned in the context of rural electrification and deferment of grid upgrades.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Despite a five-year freeze in the 2010-15 period, retail power prices have risen considerably over the last decade as the national utility,  Commercial tariffs climbing more than eightfold and residential bills more than doubling as state utility Electricidade de Moambique (EDM) attempts to make up for longstanding revenue shortfalls. In 2017 alone, the regulator increased the tariffs for both the commercial and residential bands by approximately 34%. Industrial prices saw a marginal decrease over the same period, falling from $41.97 to $41.53/MWh. Social tariffs, which apply to low-income users, have remained stable. Like most countries in Sub-Saharan Africa, Mozambique does not have a wholesale power market, but it does belong to the Southern Africa Power Pool, which is gradually increasing liquidity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The Electricity Control Board (ECB) sets the electricity tariffs that are cost-reflective, as  unusually for Sub-Saharan Africa  power prices are not subsidized. Hence Nampower is not running on a deficit, unlike most other national utilities in the region. For consumers, however, electricity prices are among the highest in the region and have been increasing by an average of 8% a year over the last five years. This has accelerated the uptake of rooftop PV among households in Namibias major cities. As Namibia relies heavily on imports from the Southern African Power Pool, electricity prices ramp up during peak demand. In order to bring them down, investment is needed in flexible capacity that can be used during peak times.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Niger relies heavily on imports from Nigeria to meet its energy needs, paying roughly 20,000 CFA/MWh ($33.88/MWh, based on the average 2017 exchange rate). The cost of electricity imports is set to rise dramatically in the near future due to the progressive privatization of Nigerian large hydro generation assets across the border. The Nigerien Ministry of Mines and Energy is bracing itself for what could amount to a threefold price increase. The output of Sonichar, a 69% state-owned company which operates the two 18MW coal plants that power the norths extractive industry, is procured at around 65,000 CFA/MWh ($110.11/MWh). Retail rates are subsidized, with a social tariff introduced in 2012. Prices increased slightly in January 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Nigerias retail electricity prices are lower than most West-African countries, such as Ghana and Senegal, but higher than other parts of Africa, like South Africa and Zambia. The electricity prices are set by the Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission in the so-called multi-year tariff order (MYTO) model. The tariffs are cost-reflective and are derived using an LCOE-approach. The MYTO is reviewed every five years and sets out the retail power prices for five years ahead. Given the recent activity with the on-grid solar projects, the tariff of 7.5-11.5 cents/kWh falls within the range of our global solar LCOEs. Currently there is no wholesale power market in Nigeria, instead NBET works as the middle-man/broker between generators and distributors.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Rwanda are among the highest in East Africa, and commercial and residential tariffs have increased since 2010. The biggest driver of this is the take-or-pay contracts administered by REG. These contracts compensate developers for the contractual offtake from their project even at times when power cannot be evacuated. As a result of these high prices and low income levels in the country, retail electricity is highly subsidized by REG and the Government of Rwanda. Small hydro remains the most popular source of generation, due to the strong network of rivers in Rwanda, but the country has also taken advantage of methane from gaseous lakes in the southwest to generate electricity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Senegal have stayed relatively stable in recent years, with higher prices for commercial and industrial users compared to residential. Tariffs are higher in rural areas than they are in areas governed by Senelec, so the government is currently undertaking a process of harmonization of tariffs to make the situation fairer. Prices for diesel and kerosene have fallen in line with oil price trends in recent years. Power prices in Senegal are significantly higher than in Cote dIvoire where tariffs are subsidized more. This reflects Senegals lack of natural resources in comparison to the Ivory Coast, and the smaller scale of its power sector.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Significant cross-subsidization between customer classes means a low-use domestic consumer can pay as little as 560 SLL/kWh (6.7/kWh), while an industrial facility or hotel incurs 1,412 SLL/kWh (17/kWh). The Electricity Distribution and Supply Authority has proposed significant increases to the most heavily subsidized rates and modest increases across other classes. For bulk supply, most of the utilitys procurement costs are unknown. A deal signed with the Turkish Karadeniz Powership in 2017 at 19.596/kWh was later renegotiated down to 16.4/kWh for 30MW of baseload supply over five years  a blended rate reflecting both capacity and fuel payments. A pressing need for substantial investment in the Sierra Leone grid may place upward pressure on rates in the future, while the development of solar and hydroelectric generators may further contain costs and subsidy levels.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail power prices in Somalia are among the highest in Africa. Electricity service providers still rely mostly on older, inefficient diesel generators that have high fuel costs. Transmission infrastructure is fragmented and unreliable, and losses are very high  around 40% compared to the sub-Saharan Africa average of 11%. Power producers are often not connected to other generators, which also increases costs and inefficiencies. Finally, technical know-how is lacking and metering consumers to measure consumption does not happen in most cases. As a result, many electricity providers charge based on the number of appliances or light bulbs used, which gives consumers little incentive to use more energy-efficient products or curb consumption.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The winning tariffs have dropped significantly in each renewables auction: wind and PV fell 24% and 29% between Rounds 3 and 4, after adjusting the tariffs for factors such as inflation and merchant tail. Overall, the LCOE for onshore wind in South Africa  at $64-95/MWh  falls in the middle of our benchmark estimates in 1H 2018, as its relatively low capex is counteracted by higher financing costs. It's a similar story for PV (without tracking), with an LCOE of $63-69/MWh. As is common in the region, South Africa has no wholesale electricity market and the energy regulator (Nersa) decides the retail prices. Eskom has repeatedly argued for substantial tariff increases to claw back its billions of expenses. Overall, tariffs climbed an average of 13.7% a year over 2004-17.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The government has only just re-started an electricity market following the collapse of an earlier attempt. The average tariff will be set at $0.42/kWh by the government, cheaper than both Uganda and Kenya. As the new electricity system is in its first year it is not clear how tariffs could change in the future.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Sudanese consumers benefit from generous electricity subsidies which result in some of the world's lowest retail prices. A reduced social tariff benefits those whose consumption amounts to less than 200kWh/month, a higher threshold than is found elsewhere in the region. Prices have increased in recent years, but only for higher consumption bands. While the peculiarities of the procurement arrangement should be taken into account (see below for details), Sudans sole IPP has its generation purchased by the state-owned offtaker at $50/MWh.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Fundamentally, retail electricity rates are set too low and are not cost reflective. The average tariff was 215 Tanzanian shillings ($0.10)/kWh in 2017, lower than the other East African nations such as Kenya and Rwanda. The current president is eager to keep the electricity price low for Tanzanias industrialization. Tanzania Electric Supply Co. (Tanesco), the state-owned utility, submitted a request to the Energy and Water Utilities Regulatory Authority (Ewura) in October 2016 to increase its average electricity tariff by 18%. Ewura approved an increase of just 8%. However, this had not been implemented as of June 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Togos retail electricity prices are similar to those in neighboring country Benin, between $150-180/MWh. On average the prices in dollars have gone down since 2010, mainly due to currency fluctuation. The only tariff change observed since 2010 was an increase for the residential sector in 2011. The country hopes that building its local energy generation capacity will reduce cost of electricity further.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Due to the high level of subsidies, Tunisias average residential electricity prices were among the 10 lowest in Africa at $52.5/MWh in 2017. Industrial and commercial prices  at $76/MWh and $87/MWh, respectively  are significantly higher than the residential tariff but still over 50% below the regional average.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Uganda has high retail electricity prices relative to its East Africa neighbors, due to a slew of renewable projects locked into take-or-pay contracts at prices that were once considered cost-competitive. The de-facto utility in the country, Umeme, guarantees its shareholders a 20% return on investment, which has had a further ripple effect on prices, even with heavy subsidies. Commercial and residential retail prices have increased 75% since 2010 to roughly $170/MWh, while industrial prices have more than doubled to $100/MWh over the same period. Strong hydro and solar resources in the region will make both technologies the focus of Ugandas energy sector moving forward, which should help to bring electricity prices down.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Up until recently, electricity prices have remained fairly stable due to being heavily subsidized by government. In 2017, however, average commercial electricity prices increased significantly as Zesco began implementing steps toward more cost-reflective tariffs. The expected 75% tariff increase, under the Energy Regulatory Board's proposal, is mainly due to a sharp shortage of up to 600MW of electricity from poor rainfall in 2015/16. This has put pressure on government to raise cash that will be used to increase investment into other energy sources and boost power supply.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in the country are set by ZERA and are higher than in other countries in the region. This is partly because the country imports expensive power from Mozambique and South Africa to meet demand. Despite the higher prices, the utility is still operating at a loss. The power fleet requires modernization and investment, with most power stations operating at low capacity factors. Renewable energy, in the form of solar and hydro, have potential to meet the supply deficit at competitive LCOEs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Afghanistan are highly volatile as the country relies heavily on imports to meet its needs. Over the last few years the national utility has hiked prices as the U.S. dollar has appreciated against the afghani. Afghanistan spends more than $200 million each year to import electricity from neighboring countries. The national utility, however, believes that once the country is able to harness its own resources, prices will come down again. When this will be achieved is unclear.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Armenias retail electricity prices are higher than those of its neighbors, but not drastically so. The country is reliant on imported gas for roughly a third of its generation. More so than climate change, energy security is a major driver of the shift to renewable energy. Power prices are not subsidized, but are low enough to be acceptable to most of the population. The cost of renewable energy in Armenia is falling, and becoming more favorable compared to gas. The recent PV auction price of $41.90/MWh was lower than many in the government expected, and will be used as a baseline tariff for other, smaller projects.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The power sector in Azerbaijan is centrally controlled by the state-owned utility, AzerEnerji. It controls all aspects of the supply chain from generation to distribution.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Average power prices in Bangladesh are lower than in neighboring India even though the smaller country generates most of its electricity from more expensive natural gas compared to cheap domestic coal in India. To keep the retail tariffs low, the government provides subsidies at two levels  by selling fuel to power generation companies below the market rate and providing subsidies to the power distribution companies. Electricity prices have been rising almost every year but they are still not high enough to meet all the operational and new investment expenses of the power distribution companies.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Cambodias consumers pay some of the highest retail electricity rates in the region, at $0.15/kWh for most residential consumers. These tariffs have declined by roughly one-third since 2010, as the government has sought to make power more affordable at the same time that it connects more villages to the grid. Tariffs are not cost-reflective but are subsidized by the government, which covers losses faced by electricity distributors. Because of their focus on rapid electrification and lowering costs, EDC and the government have favored large power plants with low per-megawatt costs, such as hydro and coal. Solar costs are coming down, however: Sunseaps 10MW project reportedly cost $0.09/kWh, while a recent contract for a 60MW PV plant came in around $0.07-0.08/kWh, rendering it competitive, or nearly so, with coal-fired units.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: China has some of the cheapest residential electricity in the world because it is subsidized by commercial and industrial (C&I) rates. It began in 2016 to address this cross-subsidization by lowering retail C&I power costs. In March 2018, regulators announced a goal to reduce retail C&I tariffs by 10%. By June, 25 out of the 33 provincial or sub-provincial markets had cut rates by about 6%, mainly due to reductions in government surcharges and taxes. Levelized costs of PV power has dropped significantly on the back of efficiency improvements and oversupply  especially in 2018 after the change in the solar market. Now subsidy-free solar is getting traction. Wind LCOE has been steadily decreasing too.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail electricity tariffs in India have been rising, with residential tariffs, which are subsidized by commercial and industrial consumers, hit the hardest. In 2017, Gujarat was the only state where electricity prices declined, and that was because of the strong financial health of distribution utilities. Through auctions, India has discovered some of the lowest tariffs in the world. Expectations of a drop in PV module prices due to demand-side shocks from China drove the lowest tariffs to 2,440 Indian rupees/MWh in July 2018 auctions. Furthermore, wind power prices dropped below the cheapest solar prices, to a record low of 2,430 rupees/MWh in December 2017. LCOEs have been pushed lower with increased competition amongst IPPs in auctions and high capacity utilization factors.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Indonesia are one of the lowest in the region: at $0.08-0.09/kWh for commercial and industrial users in 2017, and $0.08/kWh for households. Government subsidizes retail electricity tariffs, which are 20-30% lower than the cost of supply including generation, transmission and distribution. Subsidy is given directly to PLN, the national utility of Indonesia, to cover its electricity supply cost. In 2018, the government said that it would not change the prices until 2019. The levelized cost of solar and wind power are higher than retail tariffs, and have not declined at the same rate as other Southeast Asian countries such as Thailand due to poor capacity development.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail electricity tariffs in Mongolia range from 12-15 tengi a kWh for various types of user. The years of reducing tariffs means it is now cheaper than its neighbors such as Mongolia and China. This level has been kept relatively low, because the operating cost for general thermal generators (typically built in the Soviet Union times and using old technologies) can be lower than 10 tengi a kWh. By comparison, the feed-in tariff stands at 22.86 tengi for wind, 34.61 tengi for solar, 16.71 tengi for hydro and 32.23 tengi for biofuel. Even in the auctioning market in 2018, the resulting tariffs are still significantly higher than the retail power prices, creating challenges for the competitiveness of renewables.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Kyrgyzstan, like many of its neighbors in the former Soviet Union, has low power prices due to government subsidies. While electricity rates have increased slightly in recent years, prices for residential customers remain some of the lowest in the world (at just $0.01/kWh) and far below the level needed for full cost recovery. Still, electricity rates will have to increase further still if the government is to tackle the main issues facing the power sector: out-of-date infrastructure and weak reliability of supply.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Laos are relatively low, due to its abundance of low-cost hydroelectricity. The government sets electricity tariffs and subsidizes industry, residential consumers, agriculture and small and medium enterprises with rates below the cost of service. Banks and hotels, on the other hand, see significantly higher tariffs, which can make onsite solar competitive for a small segment despite the absence of net metering or other incentives. Although rates have remained fairly steady over the past five years, rising roughly 2-3% annually, the government is planning to publish new, higher rates in 2019.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Malaysian residential electricity prices are among the cheapest in the region at $50/MWh, while commercial and industrial tariffs are slightly higher, ranging between $88 and $101 per MWh. Power prices were last increased in 2014. Ongoing initiatives to deregulate the power sector and reduce gas price subsidies will have a knock-on impact on electricity tariffs. Residential prices, however, are unlikely to increase substantially given the political ramifications, especially with a government in its infancy. Malaysia's levelized cost of electricity (LCOE) across different technologies has been going down or at least remained flat, with the exception of gas. The country's lowest renewables LCOE is for small hydro, followed by geothermal and solar.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail electricity tariffs in Mongolia range from 110.67 tugrik a kWh ($0.04/kWh) for households to 158.23 tugrik a kWh for commercial and industrial users. This level, having climbed by 60% since 2011, puts them higher than neighboring countries such as Kazakhstan, and just slightly cheaper than in China. Wholesale prices for general thermal generators are at 80.86 tugrik/kWh, while the feed-in tariff ranges for on-grid renewables are: wind $80-95/MWh, small hydro $45-60/MWh, and solar $150-180/MWh. This level is generally more attractive than neighboring countries such as Kazakhstan and China. In general, energy costs are higher than in other countries due to transportation and limited know-how in the local market.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Myanmar has some of the lowest electricity tariffs in the world, with $0.03/kWh for residential customers and $0.06-0.08/kWh for commercial and industrial users. In contrast, the recent negotiations with developers of LNG-to-power and solar projects indicate that cost of power generation on a levelized basis is no less than $0.095/kWh. The artificially low tariffs make market-rate power uncompetitive in Myanmar, and the cost of the subsidies makes it impossible for the government to fund new generation, transmission and distribution projects. The last tariff hike in Myanmar took place during the term of former President U Thein Sein. While the current government has mulled a further rise in tariffs since it took office, it has yet to implement an actual hike. The political sensitivity of a price increase has been cited as the main reason for the delay.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Nepal's electricity tariffs are relatively low compared to the neighboring countries. One of the reasons for heavy losses incurred by the Nepal Electricity Authority is the absence of a tariff adjustment system. Tariffs were last adjusted in 2016 after a period of 12 years. The Electricity Tariff Fixation Commission increased prices by 19% and replaced the provision of minimum charges with a fixed service charge. ADB conducted a policy dialogue with the NEA which highlighted the need for tariff revisions on a regular basis.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices have been artificially kept low, increasing the problem of circular debt. With the country seeking a bailout package from the International Monetary Fund, there will be increasing pressure to align retail tariffs with costs. Thermal power plants dominate electricity generation in Pakistan (oil -7GW, gas  9GW), while solar and wind plants total almost 2GW. There are some new coal and gas plants under construction under the CPEC. The list of 21 energy projects under the corridor include less efficient sub-critical coal-fired power stations as well as lignite plants. One of the first statements made by the newly appointed advisor on climate change  Malik Amin Aslam  was that the new government would ensure the "strictest possible environment controls" on these projects for which contracts are already sealed and signed.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity in the Philippines is among the most expensive in Southeast Asia. While costs are decreasing, they are doing so at a slower rate than their neighbors. A lot of this is due to geography. The country is far from the sources of its imported fuels, and power prices reflect that. Economies of scale are hindered because the Philippine is made up of more than 7,000 islands.  Adding to this are ratepayer subsidies and spending on off-grid and grid-extension projects, which bumps up unsubsidized rates.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Singapore power prices are heavily linked to the price of oil. The country is 95% dependent on imported natural gas for power generation, the majority of which is purchased at oil-linked prices. Wholesale prices, known as the Uniform Singapore Electricity Price (UESP), are around S$100/MWh (US$70/MWh) and reflect the short-run marginal cost of generation in the contestable market (see below). It should be noted that the wholesale power price in Singapore is depressed by the significant level of generation overcapacity. The system reserve margin, a measure of operational capacity compared with peak demand, currently stands at 80%, meaning that almost half of the countrys power plants lie outside of the money. Non-contestable tariffs paid by small businesses and residential consumers (that make up around a quarter of total consumption) are high compared with international peers. The regulated tariff is currently around S$200/MWh (US$140/MWh) and is made up of energy costs (~70%), grid charges (~28%) and service and administration fees (~2%). The energy cost component of the regulated tariff is revised every quarter, whilst the grid charges and services fees are revised annually.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Sri Lanka has among the highest tariffs in the world for residential users (45 rupees or 28 U.S. cents), that partly explain the rapid uptake of rooftop solar in households. The tariffs in the industrial and commercial segments are lower. Tariffs have not been revised since 2014. The CEB has not done adequate work to improve transparency [of its transactions] that would compel the Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka to revise tariffs, according to Kanchana Siriwardena, PUCSLs director of tariffs and economic affairs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Taiwan has some of the worlds cheapest retail power prices, a deliberate government policy to benefit semiconductor and other economy-driving manufacturing industries. In 2017, the residential tariff was the third lowest and the industrial tariff the sixth lowest, according to Taipower and the International Energy Agency. The utility raised the average retail tariff by 3% in April 2018 for the first time in four years; industry and large commercial companies will feel the brunt of the increase, while 80% of residents and small businesses are not affected. Adding new and more expensive renewables and gas generation will further stress Taipower's balance sheet as the cost cannot be fully passed on to end-consumers.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Tajikistan, like most former Soviet Union countries, has low power prices due to government subsidies. Still, its electricity rates are higher than those in Kyrgyzstan and have been increasing for the past several years. The government has raised rates in an effort to improve the financial health of its main energy company, Barqi Tojik, but not all tariffs have increased. The Tajik Aluminum Co., for example, still has access to a special, subsidized electricity rate, even though it accounts for almost 20% of the countrys power consumption.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Thailand's retail tariffs consist of a base tariff that is reviewed every three to five years and an adjustment tariff component that is reviewed every four months. The adjustment tariff reflects changes in fuel costs, electricity purchase cost and the impact of government policies. The costs from various renewable energy schemes are passed through to retail consumers and have contributed to an increase in retail tariffs over the years. Compared to neighboring countries such as Malaysia and Vietnam, retail tariffs in Thailand are higher. A drop in equipment costs globally, the establishment of domestic equipment production bases and a reduction in development and balance-of-plant costs as developers gained experience, all contributed to a constant decline in the levelized cost of electricity for solar and wind in Thailand over time.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Despite the price of electricity recently being doubled from $0.04/kWh, rates in Turkmenistan are among the lowest in the region. Heavily subsidized electricity has been a key strategic policy of the government and only recently has the Ministry of Energy attempted to bring the price closer to cost. Tariffs should continue to increase in the future but are still far away from wholesale rates.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: While electricity prices are low compared to estimated generation costs, those for commercial and industrial sectors are comparable to prices in neighboring countries (around $40/MWh), while residential prices are significantly lower, at $20/MWh. As with most countries in the region, tariffs are indirectly subsidized through low natural gas pricing.Electricity tariffs have increased steadily at 10-15% annually in recent years, which is roughly the rate of inflation. There are no plans to increase tariffs to better reflect generation costs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail tariffs in Vietnam are considered to be among the lowest in the region. The tariffs remained almost flat from 2005 to 2010 and then began increasing till 2015, when they reached about $0.07/kWh. They were again flat in 2016 and 2017. Electricity prices for industrial customers are regulated based on voltage level and time-of-day usage. The residential tariffs are heavily subsidized. Despite concerns over solar PPAs, there is strong interest from private developers due to the high solar feed-in tariff rate and recent increase for wind.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Residents and small- to medium-sized commercial enterprises are eligible to receive a regulated electricity tariff. Since receiving a World Bank loan in 2014 to reform the power sector, the distribution system operator, OSHEE, has eradicated the two-tier pricing system for households in 2015 so households play a flat fee per kilowatt-hour. Then it simplified the commercial rates, so users pay a flat rate, depending on whether it is using 35, 20, or 10kV electricity. The tariffs are re-stated annually, while OSHEE is under pressure from the World Bank's loan covenants to reduce its debt burden, potentially by increasing prices. There is no power exchange in Albania (although there are plans for a joint exchange with Kosovo by the end of 2018), which means large consumers of electricity negotiate prices bilaterally with suppliers.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Comparable to those found in Macedonia, power prices are lower than in Albania and Croatia, but higher than in Serbia. Residential tariffs are too low to encourage the private sector to invest in building many new power plants. This state of affairs has contributed to the country being four times as energy intensive as the EU average. The highly subsidized residential sector amounts to more than half of final energy consumption. Tariffs have, however, been increasing incrementally in recent years.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Georgias electricity prices are fairly low due to legacy hydro assets that can supply power as cheaply as $0.01/kWh. The average retail rate is just under $0.10/kWh, but this tariff is stepped according to consumption. Customers with very low demand are given a special rate, supposedly as a subsidy for vulnerable consumers, and although there is no means-testing associated with the rate, it is applied automatically. Electricity prices have been rising, as the winter supply constraints worsen. Commercial and industrial prices are being increased to allow residential retail rates to be reduced. Georgias northern disputed territory of Abkhazia contains the countrys largest and cheapest hydropower plant, Khudoni.  There have been difficulties with collecting payments in the region. While the cost of wind and solar is falling, it is currently not competitive with existing hydropower plants.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Macedonia has some of the lowest electricity prices in Europe, with residential bills amounting to less than half that of the European average. Tariffs are gradually increasing due to the progressing electrification of household heating. The domestically sourced lignite currently providing well over half of the countrys power is running out, leading to renewed interest in bolstering natural gas share of the energy mix. Even if two mooted lignite mines are opened, the country will likely have to import over half of its coal production by 2030. Higher logistical expenses and steeper production costs anticipated for new mines are expected to push up operating outlays, putting further pressure on power prices.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Russia has low power prices relative to its European neighbors, due to an abundance of natural gas and government subsidies. Still, the Ministry of Energy reports that electricity rates have been inching up in recent years, and BNEF estimates that commercial and residential retail prices have risen to around $53-57/MWh as of 2017. Low electricity prices are a common feature of power markets throughout countries of the former Soviet Union, but rates are likely to continue increasing as Russia works to modernize its ageing power fleet.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Commercial, retail, and industrial power price reforms were introduced in 2015. Previously, tariffs were set below the cost-recovery point for the state utility, EPS. The reforms also helped Serbia align with the EU's accession requirements. For end-users, it meant a 30% increase in tariffs in 2016, and a further 2% in 2017. Serbia's feed-in tariffs are over twice the average wholesale price in 2017, and between one-to-two times the commercial and industrial rates in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Turkey have risen over the last five years, but are still kept low through intervention in the market. Wholesale power prices do not allow power producers to recoup their costs, which are rising along with fuel prices and currency fluctuation. Gas plants especially struggle as gas supply has been strained, and resources are diverted to heat and away from power. BNEFs levelized cost estimate for coal power in Turkey is still the lowest across technologies, due to its high capacity factor, but it does not have the same downward trajectory that wind and PV LCOEs have followed in Turkey over the last five years. Financing costs remain high, however, across all technologies, keeping LCOEs from falling as rapidly as in other regions.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Power prices in Ukraine are regulated, and have been rising in preparation for the establishment of a wholesale market in 2019. More than half the countrys electricity generation in 2017 came from Ukraines mostly aged state-owned nuclear fleet, which effectively sells power at a subsidized rate. Both thermal and nuclear plants are in need of investment for renewal and life extension. It is unclear how this will be funded and how pricing will play out when the power market structure foreseen in the new Electricity Law comes into effect, which is expected for 2019. Power prices in the region are largely subsidized and are dependent on state-owned assets, or somewhat antiquated coal-fired power stations. Ukraines situation is further complicated by the shortfall in coal supplies from the east of the country that resulted from the 2014 war and the annexation of Crimea. Coal imports have partially compensated for this. Ukraine is currently debating a proposal to introduce auctions for renewables in 2019, which would bring market forces to bear on power pricing. The proposal faces opposition from developers currently operating in the market under the generous feed-in tariff system.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Since Macri took power, electricity prices have spiked, as customer subsidies have been cut. In 2016, industrial prices grew by 260%, while residential increased by 219% compared to the previous year. In 2017, commercial, industrial and residential prices rose by 71%, 183% and 173%, respectively. CAMMESA, the governmental market regulator, regulates tariffs and is also the offtaker for the RenovAR auctions. Auction bids have consistently dropped each round, averaging $59.6/MWh in the first, $54/MWh in the second, and $42.4/MWh in the last round.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Consumer electricity prices in Bolivia are heavily subsidized. As a natural gas producer, Bolivia is reliant on this fuel for power generation, a trend which has steadily increased since 2010. In 2017, 72% of the 9.7TWh generated came from gas plants, followed by hydro, accounting for 23% of the total that year. Electricity prices have risen gradually since 2010, although rates remain low compared to most countries in Latin America, particularly residential and retail rates. In 2017, the average retail electricity price was $0.11/kWh, virtually unchanged since 2013.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Retail electricity prices (in local currency terms) jumped on average 61% between 2010 and 2017, mainly due to inflation and decreases in hydropower generation. In 2017, residential tariffs were among the five highest in Latin America, at $200/MWh. Average commercial and industrial prices were $199/MWh and $170/MWh.  Commercial and industrial (C&I) customers with power demand greater than 500kW are eligible to purchase electricity from Brazils deregulated wholesale market. Consumers with demand between 500kW and 3MW choosing this option must purchase wholesale power generated from incentivized renewable sources, including wind, small hydro, biomass and solar.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: In Chile, spot prices are determined by the node of delivery, which takes into account the marginal operating costs of nodal plants, as well as nodal demand. Wholesale prices have shown high volatility in recent years, especially in the north of SIC sub-system. In 2017, SIC prices slipped to zero at times during midday, while shooting back to $60/MWh at night. The tariff is based on peak load pricing, where consumers pay a price according to the demand. Average national commercial, industrial and residential tariffs were $214/MWh, $149/MWh and $199/MWh, respectively, in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Colombias electricity prices have risen steadily since 2010, standing on average over 60% higher across commercial, industrial and residential segments. Colombia is highly dependent on hydroelectric sources, with 70% of generation supplied from this source on average annually since 2010. Prices are vulnerable to upward pressure from extreme weather, as seen in 2015-16 when a pronounced El Nino effect was observed. Higher temperature and a lack of rain diminished Colombias main water sources causing problems at key dams, isolated power outages, and increased reliance on more expensive natural gas, oil and diesel generation to meet demand. An accompanying a spike in wholesale rates resulted, which came down in 2017. Given Colombias reliance on large hydro and modest progress in development of alternative renewable sources, wholesale price volatility and reliance on imported natural gas (via LNG) is expected.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Costa Ricas electricity prices jumped 30% between 2010 and 2017. Between 2016 and 2017, prices spiked 15% as it was necessary use expensive diesel-fired power to satisfy a 6.6% increase in electricity demand. The increase in demand was driven by power price reductions applied in the previous months, as well as greater economic activity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The Dominican Republics residential power prices remained relatively flat between 2014-2017, averaging $149/MWh. Commercial prices fell 22% over this period from $247/MWh in 2014 to $193/MWh in 2017. Average industrial prices decreased from $186/MWh in 2014 to $161/MWh in 2017, and wholesale prices also decreased over same period, from $156/MWh in 2014 to $94/MWh in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Since 2011, commercial, industrial and residential power prices have risen 33%, 58% and 8%. In 2017, average commercial, industrial and residential tariffs were $104.1/MWh, $94.6/MWh and $101.70/MWh, respectively. Ecuador has one of the lowest tariffs in Latin America, being in the bottom five.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: From 2015 to 2016, electricity prices in El Salvador decreased on average by 20% (commercial, residential, industrial and wholesale). However, dry conditions in 2016 that reduced reservoir levels resulted in increased generation from bunker and other fossil fuels, causing electricity prices to rise in 2017. Commercial prices increased 11% from $199/MWh in 2016 to $220/MWh in 2017. Both residential and wholesale prices increased by 12% over the same period, while industrial prices rose by 6%.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Guatemalas average residential electricity price decreased 20% between 2014 and 2017, from $285.92/MWh to $231.15/MWh, however, prices remain among the three highest in Latin America. Commercial prices, on the other hand, increased 4% from $145.38/MWh in 2016 to $151.40/MWh in 2017 and industrial prices grew from $140.98/MWh in 2016 to $148.42/MWh in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Considerable ambiguity exists regarding EDHs tariffs, as no regulated authority exists to provide information regarding how prices are set. But bills charged to users have remained largely unchanged in recent years. Broadly speaking, industrial tariffs are set at $204.82/MWh, commercial at $201.01/MWh and residential at $115.74/MWh. It has been reported that actual prices charged to customers have been lower, potentially due to the recent depreciation of the Haitian gourde. No tariffs have been fixed for procuring the offtake of private generators  IPPs are free to negotiate with the state utility.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Honduras have declined since 2012, with the biggest decrease occurring between 2014 and 2015.  Commercial prices decreased 20%, from $227/MWh in 2014 to $182/MWh in 2015, while industrial prices decreased 19%, from $193/MWh to $157/MWh. The fall in prices was largely the result of increases in electricity generation of 9% in 2015, which rose from 7.8TWh in 2014 to 8.5TWh.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: In 2017, Jamaicas residential and commercial electricity prices were the highest in the region. Its industrial average price is the second highest in Latin America. The residential price increased 18%, from $243.17 in 2016 to $286.91 in 2017, while the commercial price increased 20% over the period. The industrial price increased 25%, from $167.12 in 2016 to $208.57 in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The Mexican market is characterized by relatively high wholesale prices overall, with both day-ahead and real-time prices rising steadily. Day-ahead prices averaged 1.67 pesos/KWh ($0.088/KWh) in 2018 through August, approximately 33% higher than the 2017 average over the same period and nearly double those in 2016. A second phase of the short-term energy market featuring an hour-ahead market remains to be introduced. Off-takers with a load center of at least 1MW are classified as qualified users and are allowed to purchase electricity directly from qualified suppliers. There are now six such qualified suppliers active in the wholesale market, including CFE Calificados, the subsidiary of state power utility, Comisin Federal de Electricidad (CFE). CFE continues to be the supplier of basic retail services to residential customers and small and medium-sized commercial customers under regulated tariffs. Regulator CRE sets the final retail and last-resort supply tariffs based on the cost of energy and ancillary services required.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Nicaragua have increased by less than 4% (in local currency terms)  over the past five years. Commercial electricity prices are the second highest in Latin America at $256/MWh, only after Jamaica. Residential and commercial tariffs are significantly lower at $194/MWh and $192/MWh, respectively, but still appear among the top seven most expensive tariffs in the region. Nicaraguas high retail prices are largely due to its dependency on imported fossil fuels for generation. However, tariffs are not cost reflective. Renewables development is key to improving energy security and reducing generation costs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: In Panama power prices increased in all sectors from 2016-2017. Commercial prices grew from $174.16/MWh to $182.20/MWh, industrial prices increased from $168.27/MWh to $175.90/MWh and residential prices moved from $152.83/MWh to $157.70/MWh. On the other hand, the wholesale price decreased slightly from $59.19/MWh in 2016 to $58.51/MWh in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: In 2017, Paraguays average residential electricity prices increased 9%, moving from $64.40/MWh in 2016 to $70.20/MWh in 2017. Industrial prices jumped 26% over the period and commercial prices rose 7.5%. Despite the increases, Paraguays electricity prices are the lowest in Latin America due to the excess of electricity supply.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Since 2012, average commercial and industrial power prices have risen 35%, while residential registered a 25% increment. By the end of 2017, industrial, commercial and residential prices were at $84.1/MWh, $112.1/MWh and $144/MWh, respectively. Even after recent increases, Perus electricity prices rank among the cheapest in Latin America. The latest renewable energy auction winners were announced in February 2016. The contracts awarded for wind and solar projects represented the lowest prices recorded on an unsubsidized basis in the Western Hemisphere at the time, at an average of $38/MWh and $48/MWh, respectively.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Uruguay is among the top 10 most attractive countries, in terms of tariffs, for renewable investors comparing other emerging nations. Stable and high prices make the country a good market for power project developers. In 2017, commercial, industrial and residential electricity prices averaged $246/MWh, $169/MWh and $245/MWh, respectively.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity tariffs in Egypt may still be low on global standards but they have risen significantly in recent years, as the government has sought to cut subsidy costs. Industrial prices have increased the most  by the compound annual growth rate of 48% over 2013-17  while residential and commercial tariffs have climbed 22-24% over the same period. The efforts to reduce fuel and electricity subsidies are a condition of the country's three-year, $12-billion loan program from the International Monetary Fund. The government has said that electricity subsidies will be phased out by the end of June 2022 (three years later than planned). However, it has a tough task to balance these tough economic reforms with the need to ensure social stability, with over a quarter of the population living below the poverty line.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The government subsidizes electricity and fuel prices, giving Iraqis some of the cheapest prices in the world. The supply of electricity is unreliable and available for less than 15 hours a day. This has forced consumers to turn to private, predominantly diesel, generators for supply. Cheap electricity has led to very high consumption, with each household consuming twice as much on average than in neighboring Jordan. As a result, electricity subsidies cost the Iraqi government 3.4% of GDP each year while fuel subsidies cost it 3.6%. The government has introduced a progressive tariff increase to reduce the subsidy and encourage efficient consumption of electricity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Prices for consumers in Jordan are subsidized. Commercial consumers have traditionally paid the highest electricity prices, subsidizing residential consumers. This led to a rise in wheeling projects and the loss of high-paying commercial customers. Wheeling projects have thus been discouraged and prices for commercial consumers lowered slightly, while prices for households were increased. This has not stemmed financial losses at state-owned National Electric Power Co. (Nepco), which is already heavily indebted, and as a result electricity prices across sectors continue to rise.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity prices in Kuwait are amongst the lowest in the Middle East and North Africa, due to heavily subsidized fossil-fuel generation. These subsidies distort the allocation of resources by encouraging excessive consumption, accelerating the depletion of natural resources and undermining the growth potential of renewables. In order to curb this, the government increased electricity prices for expatriates living in Kuwait. Effective September 2017, the flat rate of 2 fils/kWh (0.7 U.S. cents/kWh) changed to a three-block tariff of 5 fils/kWh, 10 fils/kWh and 15 fils/kWh for consumption ranges of 0-1,000kWh, 1,001-2,000kWh and above 2,001kWh, respectively. However, Kuwaiti citizens were exempt from the increase. Electricity prices in the commercial sector increased to 25 fils/kWh, while industrial prices remained flat at 1 fils/kWh. There are no further plans to increase prices.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The government subsidizes electricity prices in the form of cheap diesel and heavy fuel oil for the state utility, Electricit du Liban (EDL), which sells electricity to the grid significantly below its cost of generation. The World Bank estimates that this massive strain on public finances is responsible for 40% of all government debt since 1992, two years before retail tariffs were frozen. However, any movement toward more cost-reflective power prices remains politically untenable. EDLs inability to meet electrical demand has spawned a large fleet of private diesel generators. These supply the grid during the daily blackouts, which may last three hours in Beirut and up to 12 hours in rural areas. Despite their illegality, these generators contribute an estimated 23% of all electricity. The PPA for the first round of wind auctions was at $113/MWh. The LCOE of solar PV in Lebanon will likely be competitive in the context of the countrys diesel-dominated power sector. By 2016, small-scale PV solutions already totaled 20MW, with at least a further 10MW in development.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The OPWPs bulk supply tariff, which sets the price at which electricity is sold to licensed suppliers, averaged out at about 18.25 riyals/MWh ($47.40 based on the average 2017 exchange rate) for the countrys main grid network in 2017. Retail prices have not changed since 1992. The introduction of a cost-reflective tariff (CRT) in January 2017 is a notable exception, removing subsidies for customers whose yearly use exceeds 150MWh. The CRTs incorporation of peak pricing is intended to even out demand. Despite such reforms and the fact that rates remain higher than the GCC average, the government continues to sell gas to power generators at prices kept well below international market rates.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: The country's energy prices have long been subsidized well below regional and international levels. Energy prices, however, are on the rise  the most recent increase for electricity and petrol was at the beginning of 2018. The target is for energy prices to reach international levels by 2020.  As in the first round of NREP auctions, the winning bid for a 300MW solar tender that was won by local player Acwa Power came in at $2.36/MWh. Acwa was selected over an EDF bid of $1.78/MWh. Official Saudi policy is to eliminate many subsidies, but actually doing so may be harder than anticipated.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: U.A.E. solar tenders have attracted headlines for record low tariffs: June 2016 saw the Dubai Electricity and Water Authority (DEWA), one of four national utilities, announce the $29/MWh price agreed on with the Masdar-led grouping chosen to complete the 800MW third phase of the Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park. This project will bring 5,000MW online by 2030 at a cost of $13.6 billion. The projects fourth stage, adding 700MW of solar thermal capacity, was awarded to a consortium of Chinese and Saudi investors with a 35-year PPA price of $0.073/kWh  by far the lowest for the technology. Retail electricity tariffs are the Gulfs highest and are independently set by the four utilities.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column15: Electricity in the Palestinian Territories is expensive compared to its neighbors. Most power is imported from Israel, and Palestinian consumers pay the same retail prices as set by the Israel Electric Company, despite the higher standard of living in Israel compared to Palestine. Power prices are set by the regulator, and although they are high, Palestinian distribution companies (that are also the retailers) are unable to fully recoup their costs. Consumers are able to install rooftop solar panels and high power prices incentivize their uptake.

column15: Algeria opened up the electricity sector to competition in the generation segment in 2002. To date, however, the sector remains dominated by Sonelgaz whose competitive position allowed by its access to cheap domestic gas resources is hard to challenge. The countrys delayed renewables auctions will most likely change this landscape rapidly. The Sonelgaz group is also the sole authorized retailer of electricity on the countrys three grids. However, consumers are free to procure their own electricity through self-generation or direct PPAs. The recent drop in the cost of solar, the costs and difficult operating conditions for diesel generators, as well as issues around the quality and availability of grid electricity supply have created a growing market for small-scale renewables.

Much of Angola's infrastructure was destroyed during the 27-year war, which ended in 2002, and had to be built and refurbished. A significant investment program increased generation capacity from 700MW in 2002 to around 4.7GW in 2017. The country saw capacity jump 80% in 2017 as a result of 1.4GW of two large hydro plants and a 750MW gas plant. Half of the new large hydro capacity came from the first phases of the flagship $4.3 billion Lauca, due to become the largest hydropower plant in Southern Africa, alongside Mozambiques CahoraBassa. As part of an electricity sector reform beginning in 2014, the power market was unbundled into: Prodel on the generation side, together with RNT and ENDE as the transmission and distribution system operators. Gamek saw its mandate extended beyond just hydropower to oversee the development and construction of most major power projects. Once completed, these are then transferred to Prodel for operation. The power network is still fragmented across three regional grids (Norte, Centro and Sul) and some isolated systems.

Benin relies on thermal generation, with a heavy dependence on its neighbors. While the country has virtually no renewable energy projects to date, the planned PV plants will help Benin reduce energy dependence. Policies and regulation linked to renewables have not been elaborated yet, so uncertainty on their status and market priority remains. Benins power sector is partially unbundled. Generation is separated from transmission and retail, though very few players have entered the space due to the lack of financing available to date.

The power sector in Botswana is dominated by coal, which accounts for 79% of the current installed capacity. By contrast, renewables, which is essentially solar, represents just 0.1%. This is due to change with the development of 100MW solar project that is currently in the proposal stage. Botswana has gradually weaned off from the Southern Africa Power Pool (SAPP) importing only 23% of the distributed power nationally. There is only one operational 1.3MW solar plant in the country and renewables do not benefit from purchase obligation as BPC buys all the power available regardless of sector. Currently, Botswana Power Corp. (BPC) is the sole provider of generation, transmission, distribution and retail services. However, BPC is looking to transform itself into a transmission and distribution utility, and move away from being a fully integrated utility. Independent power producers (IPP) have been allowed to enter the market since 2007 but have only began to expand into the generation market in the last two years. Two PPAs for the Morupule B Coal plant and a 1MW solar plant were signed in 2017.

Generation is dominated by thermal plants that are fueled by expensive imported oil. In recent years Sonabel has tried to keep up with rising demand by ramping up generation of existing fossil fuel plants, and by importing electricity from Ghana, Togo and Cote dIvoire. Imports rose from 145GWh in 2009 to 434GWh in 2017. The power sector is partly liberalized. The country is divided in two segments: The first covers the urban areas where Sonabel has a monopoly over transmission and distribution. Although generation is open to private actors, no IPPs are active. The second segment covers rural areas, where local cooperatives (COOPELs) are responsible for distribution. In this segment the private sector may operate generation and off-grid distribution projects. The offtaker can be commercial, as in the case of the Essakane PV plant.

The renewable energy mix is dominated by hydro (49%), followed by solar (19%). In September 2017, the government leased an emergency 30MW natural gas power station for the supply of the capital Bujumbura. The city accounts for 95% of electricity consumed. Aside from its national generation capacity, Regideso also buys electricity from an old cross-border hydropower complex located in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) with 70MW shared among Rwanda, DRC and Burundi. The national average electricity consumption per capita is only 25kWh per year, which is one of the lowest rates in the world. Power generation continues to be dominated by Regideso, which has a legal monopoly (renewed in 2015 for 25 years) for electricity transmission, distribution and supply. The generation capacity is owned and operated by Regideso and subject to severe under-investment, as is the case for the transmission and distribution assets, much of which date from before the country's independence in 1962.

Hydro dominates the capacity mix, followed by fossil fuels. Cameroon was one of the first in Africa to open its electricity sector to private-sector participation, and in 2001, AES became majority shareholder of the utility (then called Sonel). A new reform phase began in 2011 with the unbundling of generation, transmission and distribution. Sonel was acquired by Actis in 2014, and rebranded as Eneo. A 2015 decree split the transmission and system operation components to create the state-owned Sonatrel, which decides dispatch and is a single buyer for grid-connected generation. Eneo dominates generation, but two IPPs operate the two main thermal plants. The legal framework for electricity needs significant review, which will likely begin after the October 2018 elections.

The large proportion of electricity generation comes from small-hydro systems which have been present on the system for a number of years. These systems are poorly maintained and break down often. There are supplementary diesel-powered generation units but these are small and account for only a few percent of the total installed capacity. There is an interconnection with the Democratic Republic of Congo, but this is inactive due to degradation. Current plans for the future of the electricity generation system include renovating existing generating assets as well as the distribution grids. There are plans to introduce a further 10MW of hydro capacity, but this has stagnated due to the political climate, despite financial support being provided. There is no electricity distribution market as such. Consumers connect to the grid and pay for their usage through the state-owned utility Enerca which dominates the generation, distribution and retail of electricity, despite all three segments being liberalized for competition. There are plans to introduce further laws to facilitate competition, but no plans have been made public.

Chad switched from importing fuel from Cameroon and Nigeria to supplying its own oil with the construction of a refinery 2010. Although the current generation fleet remains almost entirely fired by fossil fuels, solar projects amounting to 90MW are in the pipeline. Procurement, transmission and distribution are the state utilitys prerogatives, but independent producers can sell their output, with Socit Nationale dElectricit du Tchad (SNE) purchasing electricity from a 20MW thermal plant owned and operated by VPower. Given that the SNE is the sole procurer of all generation, corporate PPAs are off the cards. A law setting out more detailed regulations for IPPs, clarifying procedures and penalties, is currently being debated in the National Assembly.

Much of the countrys capacity runs on fossil fuels. Its largest generation asset is Enis 300MW OCGT gas plant, Centrale Electrique du Congo (CEC). Large hydro provides a sizeable slice of generation with such dams as Imboulou (120MW) and Moukoukoulou (74MW). No non-hydro renewables capacity has been installed to date. Although generation was first opened up to private producers in 2003, an application decree outlining the laws remit was not issued until July 2017. Even if the utility has agreed to buy electricity from Enis CEC plant, the state ensured it retained an 80% share of the projects equity. The markets lack of maturity is such that regulations concerning private generation remain unclear.

Hydropower generates the vast majority of the DRCs electricity needs and the Congo River has significant potential for further dam development. As yet, there are no utility-scale wind and solar projects, although there is some evidence that could change: Copperbelt Energy has announced plans for two PV plants to feed electricity to copper and cobalt mines in the country. Power generation still largely rests in the hands of state-controlled utility SNEL, which owns and operates 94% of installed capacity in the DRC. Independent power producers own just 6% of total generating capacity, at 135MW, which is mostly used for mining activities.

Cote d'Ivoire's electricity market is fully unbundled by law, but in practice only generation is open to competition and the utility one of the few non-state-owned in Africa- is the sole offtaker of electricity. Three IPPs  Ciprel, Azito and Aggreko  own 60% of the capacity through multiple gas units. The rest consists mainly of state-owned hydro plants. Several IPP-led renewable projects are in the works. Thermal capacity is also set to increase, with a 700MW coal project in planning. This suggests the share of renewables will not increase in the short term. In the medium term, there are a number of hydro and solar projects in the pipeline. If these were completed, the share of renewables capacity could reach 45%.

Urban electrification levels are fairly high, but fully reliant on diesel generation. In rural areas, access to electricity is much more variable. Eritrea has no interconnection with its neighbors, though now that relations are improving with Ethiopia there is talk of potential links. The power market itself is vertically integrated with no private participation nor any known plans for reform.

Ethiopia's power mix is dominated by hydro, which makes up more than 90% of the generation mix. While some hydro-reliant countries have struggled with drought, Ethiopia has mostly avoided the issue, with the most recent severe drought in 2008-09. However, it is a potential vulnerability for future security of supply. Wind makes up around 7% of generation, and the government aims to continue developing that sector. Ethiopia has not held large-scale competitive auctions yet, which tend to drive down prices. In terms of market structure, in 2013 the vertically integrated EEPCo was split into the EEP, which is responsible for generation and transmission; and the Ethiopian Electric Utility (EEU), which looks after distribution and sales.

The power market in Ghana has been through turbulent times in recent years. In 2016 it faced power shortages that led to the signing of high priced PPAs, which have now been delayed or cancelled. More recently, the main offtaker, the Electricity Company of Ghana (ECG), had to be rescued through a concession won by Meralco, the Philippine electricity company. The concession is aimed to turn around the poor finances of ECG and increase investment in the Ghanaian grid. Oil and gas provides the majority of Ghana's electricity supply, accounting for a combined 68% of generation in 2017. The remainder mostly comes from hydropower, so that low water levels pose a risk around the future availability of these plants. Renewable energy is largely confined to two utility-scale PV plants, with little prospect of new projects in the near future. There is an increasing number of (often solar) mini-grids being deployed in off-grid communities.

About two-thirds of generating capacity is derived from large-scale dams, with the completion of the aforementioned Kalta project in 2015 effectively tripling the countrys installed large hydro potential. The build-up of hydro capacity is set to continue with a series of dams in the pipeline, including the 450MW Souapiti project tabled for 2020. The rest of Guineas electricity fleet is oil and diesel-fired. There are plans to develop offshore gas fields, but reserves remain unproven. Efforts to liberalize the power market are driven by the prospect of trading competitively within the West African Power Pool: the first of four planned interconnection lines should be exporting electricity by 2020 (three are under construction).

The liberalization of the generation market has seen 13 IPPs cut into KenGens market share, and the government has mandated Ketraco to compete with Kenya Power on transmission. Kenya Power monopolizes distribution and retail today, but the monopoly will end if the proposed Energy Bill passes the parliament in its current form. Large hydro and geothermal are the two main sources of the Kenyas generation mix. The share of renewables stayed at 33% in 2017, but this is expected to increase in coming years as wind and solar projects (including Lake Turkana) come online and geothermal capacity is added. Retail electricity prices are fully regulated for all customer segments.

The country has a single government-owned utility that is wholly responsible for procurement of power, distribution and management of the transmission grid. Lesotho has only one power station, 72MW Muela Hydro, and electricity is imported from South Africa and Mozambique in order to meet demand. Lesotho has significant renewables sources that are mostly untapped; realizing even only a couple of projects would greatly reduce the country's reliance on imports from neighboring countries. Lesotho is unique in that it is very mountainous, it is difficult to reach remote villages with transmission and distribution infrastructure, and as a result has low electrification rates especially in rural areas.

The power system is served by the LEC, a state-owned monopoly responsible for generation, transmission, distribution, retail supply, and overall system operation. LEC owns and operates a small fleet of mostly hydroelectric generators, the most substantial of which, the 88MW Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant, was refurbished and returned to service in December 2016 after being offline for 26 years through civil turmoil and the Ebola outbreak. LEC also procures power from independent producers  mostly embedded diesel generators. The LEC grid is concentrated around the capital Monrovia, barely reaching the citys outer limits. The remainder of the country is not electrified, and it is not served by community-scale microgrid operators either. However, a multinational West Africa Power Pool that passes through Liberia is starting to provide power to some regions in the north of the country.

Libyas generation mix is dominated by fossil fuels, namely natural gas and fuel oil. Renewable energy has so far been limited to small-scale applications such as rural electrification, water pumping, communication networks, rooftop systems and solar heating in the residential sector. Renewable energy capacity additions have lagged behind due to the ongoing conflict in the country. The General Electricity Company of Libya (GECOL) is 100% state-owned and is responsible for all segments of the market. No independent generators participate in the market.

The sector has been opened up to IPPs for over a decade and there is a clear intention to attract more private and international investment into that segment. The retail of electricity can also be done by independent companies through direct sales or within rural electrification concessions; however experience in this segment remains limited. The typical PPA guarantees a volume and number of run hours to the generator for up to 20 years. Madagascar still lacks a modern dispatch center but a project led by the World Bank is looking to address this in the coming years.

Malawis electricity generation relies predominantly on large hydro, which accounts for 87% of the total installed capacity. Recently increased electricity demand has been met with supply from oil and diesel generators. In 2017, Escom held its first renewable energy tender, contracting 70MW of PV power. In 2018, IPPs issued tenders for 40MW of solar, but nothing has come to fruition yet. Malawian President Peter Mutharika has been in discussions with a Chinese consortium to construct a 300MW coal-fired power plant. In August 2016, the government completed the unbundling of the power sector. Escom became responsible for transmission, distribution and retail, while the new company; Electricity Supply Corporation of Malawi (Egenco) became in charge of generation.

Mali's electricity market has been unbundled legally since 2000, but in practice the utility has a regional concession on transmission and distribution which covers 98 municipalities. Generation is open to competition, although there is currently only one IPP, Sogem. Some 60% of the grid-connected capacity comes from state-owned heavy fuel oil plants. The rest is hydro capacity, composed mainly of two dams managed by Sogem that also provide electricity to Senegal and Mauritania. Mali also imports electricity from Cote d'Ivoire and Senegal, and soon will do so from Mauritania. Since 2003, authorizations can be obtained for the retail of electricity in rural areas not reached by the grid. In September 2015, 68 local private operators were operating in 215 municipalities, mostly using diesel technology but increasingly hybrid systems.

Solar is the countrys main clean energy source with 81.6MW installed to date. This is followed by wind with 30MW against nearly 300MW of thermal capacity.
