Procurement, transmission and distribution remain Somelecs prerogatives. The countrys first PPA, linked to the construction of the aforementioned Zouerate solar plant, was signed with Clemessy. A second such agreement has been signed with an IPP for the installation of a 100MW wind farm. A number of 1-3MW solar-diesel hybrid projects have been brought online, most recently at Kiffa, a plant whose PV component amounts to 1.3MW. Expanding renewables capacity and the discovery of offshore gas have made the government eager to begin selling energy to its neighbors.

Coal has the largest share of Moroccos power mix, accounting for 32% of capacity and more than 55% of generation in 2017. The coal sector has added more than 1GW of capacity since 2011 with a further 1.3GW expected online once the Safi plant is completed. In the context of total capacity growth of 20%, renewables share has remained constant at around a third for the last five years. Wind and solar capacity has doubled to 14% since 2011, and additions of a further 2.7GW of renewables capacity in the coming years will push this to the target of 42% by 2020. Recent years have been poor for hydropower and total renewable generation has been flat at around 16%. This has hidden growth in solar and wind generation from only 3% in 2010 to 11% in 2017. The Moroccan state utility, ONEE, still maintains a monopoly for the transmission network and is involved in all sales of electricity. It also accounts for around a third of total generation and more than half of the distribution and retail sectors of the power market.

The power sector consists predominantly of hydroelectric generation, representing 85% of the capacity mix in 2017. However, this mix is expected to change in the future following large discoveries of coal and offshore gas. No large-scale wind or PV plants have been commissioned to date. Mozambiques power market is currently structured around Electricidade de Moambique (EDM), a state-owned and vertically integrated utility responsible for the transmission, distribution and sale of electricity. EDM oversees 20% of the countrys generating capacity, but purchases power produced by IPPs and the 2.1GW Cahora Bassa Hydro (HCB). The latter is majority owned by the Mozambican state (92.5%). 90% of the plants generation is exported, mostly to South Africa.

Namibias electricity generation is dominated by its Ruacana hydropower plant, which accounts for 62% of installed capacity. It relies for almost 60% of its electricity consumption on imports from the Southern African Power Pool. With the desire of becoming more energy independent, Namibia commissioned 78MW of wind and solar capacity in 2015-17. At the moment, Nampower is the only offtaker with which IPPs can sign PPAs. However, the Electricity Control Board (regulator) wants to switch from a single buyer model to a modified single buyer model, where IPPs can sell directly to local distributors and large consumers, and potentially also export power.

Nigelec is vertically integrated except in power generation, which was opened up to IPPs in 2016. The only independent producer procured from is Sonichar, the aforementioned coal plant operator. Demand is currently met through energy imports from Nigeria. The total amount of power imported in 2017 is nearly double that generated domestically. Most of Nigers diesel generators spend much of the year idle, only being powered up when transmission from its southern neighbor is interrupted. While several solar projects are being carried out, investment in non-renewable generation is set to continue alongside work on the Kandadji dam, a 130MW project bedeviled by repeated delays, in addition to the ongoing construction of a 600MW coal plant.

At year-end 2017, Nigeria had installed electricity capacity of 13GW, of which 15.1% was large hydro, 0.5% small-hydro and 84.4% fossil fuels. Only 7.5GW of the installed capacity is actually available, and just 4GW are available on average during the year. Nigeria is currently trying to create an enabling environment that will lead to an increase of grid capacity. Nigerias target of 30% renewables by 2030 would require a change in its energy mix, though as yet it has no commissioned on-grid renewables capacity. Nigeria imports less than 2% of its power from other countries. Following an extensive power market reform a few years ago, generation is fully privatized, transmission is still government-owned, while distribution is privatized, but with only 11 players allocated by region.

Rwandas power mix is based heavily on hydro, at just under 50% as of June 2018, but other technologies, such as solar, natural gas and diesel are represented. State-owned Energy Development Corporation Ltd. has been the most prominent developer, but there are a multitude of private players involved in Rwandas generation sector. The country has an oversupply of on-grid generation, as well as a backlog of contracted projects. As a result, new developers will not be able to secure permitting until the roughly 200MW of generation projects with existing contracts are commissioned. The country is instead focusing near-term investment into transmission and distribution, both of which are fully controlled by REG.

Senegal still relies heavily on thermal power plants to provide the majority of its 800MW installed capacity, but the proportion generated by solar power is increasing rapidly, and the countrys first utility-scale wind project will provide around 15% of electricity demand when complete. Some 75MW of hydropower is imported into Senegal from nearby Mali, and there are also plans to import another 40MW from Mauritania once the relevant transmission line is complete. The power-market structure is partially liberalized in Senegal. Private companies can operate in power generation, but transmission and distribution is still controlled by state-owned utility Senelec until 2019. The exception to this is the rural concession areas where IPPs have been granted ownership across the power market structure.

Sierra Leones power system was partially unbundled in 2011. The National Electricity Act separated the Electricity Board into two state-owned entities: the self-descriptive Electricity Generation and Transmission Corp. (EGTC) and Electricity Distribution and Supply Authority (EDSA). The countrys power system is extremely dependent on hydro generation operated by EGTC and procured by EDSA through PPAs approved by regulators, such that the seasonality of water supplies leads to lingering supply constraints. The arrival of the Karpowership, a 126MW floating power plant, in Freetown Harbor in late 2017 has relieved some stress on system and power prices, but issues remain. EDSA also procures power through PPAs with renewable and non-renewable independent power producers.

As the electricity supply is very unreliable, Somalis rely on traditional biomass for basic energy needs. The electricity suppliers that do operate mostly run diesel generators, though PV systems are starting to penetrate the market, mainly in the more stable region of Somaliland. While the initial investment required for a diesel genset is still lower in some cases than a PV system, adding PV to an existing diesel system is proving popular among small IPPs. Many electricity service providers operating in Somaliland have specific plans to add renewables to their existing diesel infrastructure.

Eskom, the state-owned utility, dominates the power sector. Independent generators have started to capture generation market share, mostly renewables, and municipalities are responsible for retail of electricity in some areas. (The customer still has no choice of supplier.) The country regularly exports electricity to its neighbors through the Southern African Power Pool. South Africa saw some short-term load shedding (scheduled power cuts) in June 2018  its first episode since 1H 2016; but this is a far cry from the height of regular load shedding in 2014-15. Coal dominates South Africa's electricity mix, accounting for nearly 80% of capacity in 2017. This share is likely to be maintained once the Medupi and Kusile coal plants (at 4.8GW each) come online together with the government's IPP program.

On-grid energy generation is dominated by fossil fuels, with power plants consisting of a mix of oil/diesel facilities with one small hydro facility in the capital, Juba. The majority of the population, 99%, is off-grid and relies on diesel generators for power. However, there is an increasing proportion of the population that is moving to clean energy for their off-grid power, with 15MW of clean energy off-grid projects reported. This is equal to half of the grid generators.

The structure of the power sector has evolved in recent years. Following the unbundling of the sector at the turn of the millennium, 2016 saw the creation of the Sudanese Electricity Holding Co. With an effective monopoly on procurement, the holding company oversees two generation utilities  the Sudanese Thermal Power Generating company and its hydro-focused counterpart  as well as two companies whose respective remits cover distribution and transmission. Though the 2001 Electricity Law opened up private participation throughout the energy sector, the above actors are state-owned. The aforementioned IPP operates a 26.5MW thermal plant, yet the arrangement can only be loosely referred to as a PPA as the fuel used is provided by the thermal utility free of charge.

Tanzanias power sector is dominated by Tanesco, which owns most of the countrys transmission and distribution network and more than half of its generating capacity. In the 2016/17 financial year, Tanescos contribution reached 75% of generation, followed by Songas 20%. The government plans to reform the power sector by unbundling Tanesco by 2025, according to the 2014 Electricity Supply Industry Reform Strategy and Roadmap. However, achieving this will be hard within the prescribed timelines. The countrys two dominant generation sources are gas and hydro, which accounted for 59% and 35% of the total electricity generation of 7,100GWh in 2016/17. The contribution of renewable energy, meanwhile, was very limited.

Togos generation is mainly thermal, as it relies on a 100MW ContourGlobal fossil fuel generation plant in Lom, as well as imports (mostly gas from Ghana and Nigeria). The country aims to reach electricity independence by 2030. While there has been no large-scale renewables project in Togo to date, the national electrification and energy independence plan relies heavily on renewables over the coming decade. Some 50MW of solar have been commissioned, as well as 60MW of hydropower in Tetetou, 24MW in Titira, and another 24MW in Sarakawa. Under the new renewable energy sector law, renewables benefit from priority dispatch and purchase obligation from the offtaker. While the power sector is officially open to all players, the CEB (Communaut Electrique du Bnin) still owns most generation capacity in the country, as well as transmission assets. The CEET (Compagnie Energie Electrique du Togo) is in charge of retail.

Over 94% of Tunisias 5.5GW of installed capacity and more than 97% of the power produced in 2017 came from gas-fired plants. As of end-2017, only 240MW of wind plants and 62MW of small hydro were commissioned. However, the power mix is due to become more diversified over the next four years as auctions are due to increase the clean energy capacity. The state-owned utility Tunisia Company of Electricity and Gas (STEG) controls over 80% of power generation and has a monopoly over transmission and distribution of electricity and natural gas. IPPs are allowed in the market under the concession and authorization programs and can rely on a 20-year standardized PPA with STEG. According to law 2015-12 that regulates renewable energy generation, STEG is mandated to buy all power produced by clean energy plants.

Ugandas power market has been liberalized since 2001. State-owned Uganda Electricity Generation Company Ltd. competes with private players in the generation market, which is dominated by hydro (709MW), biomass (76MW) and solar (20MW). Hydro makes up the entire project pipeline, but an oversupply in generation has stalled additional project approvals, and the country is investigating opportunities to export electricity to neighboring countries. Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Ltd. has full ownership of transmission in the country, while Uganda Electricity Distribution Company Ltd. owns all distribution concessions, tendering them out to private players. Publicly-listed Umeme has won over 90% of these concessions. The Electricity Regulatory Authority looks over all of these segments, and is the most dynamic entity in Ugandas power market.

Zesco is a vertically integrated electricity utility owned by the Zambian government that generates, transmits, distributes and supplies the majority of the country's electricity. Its reliance on hydro generation is not forecasted to change as Zambias hydro generation potential is estimated at more than 6,000MW. Several existing large hydro facilities are currently being upgraded by Zesco, while a substantial pipeline of projects, including the 2,400MW Batoka Gorge Dam power project and the 8501,200 MW Luapula hydro scheme are in the planning phase. A large and untapped potential remains for small-scale hydropower, especially for rural electrification. Despite there being zero commissioned PV plants to date, the continual decline in technology costs have aided the potential for PV expansion as seen by projects such as the IFCs Scaling Solar program.  Wind energy potential in Zambia is relatively limited as is not particularly suitable for electricity generation.

The monopolized electricity sector is controlled by state-owned utility Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority (ZESA) and regulated by ZERA. Offtaker risk is high due to the utilitys struggling balance sheet. Due to insufficient supply, Zimbabwe heavily relies on imports from both Eskom (South Africa) and EDM (Mozambique) in order to meet the power demand in the country. Large hydro (Kariba Power Station) and coal (Hwange Power Station being the largest), owned by ZESA, make up the bulk of the countrys own generation with a small contribution from biomass and small hydro IPPs.

Afghanistan relies heavily on energy imports. About 80% of the countrys power needs are met by imports, hydro power being the dominant source of energy that is imported. The country has the potential to generate 318GW of electricity from renewable sources, with 23GW coming from hydro, 67GW from wind, 222GW from solar and 2GW from geothermal, as per the Renewable Energy Policy 2015. So far, only parts of some hydroelectric projects have been implemented. The power market currently is controlled by Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat and there is not much participation from the private sector. Term 1 of the Renewable Energy Policy focuses on creating an environment that encourages investments from private sector. This involves setting up transparent regulations, tariff guidelines, tax based incentives, freedom to sell power to third part, leasing, licensing incentives, etc

Armenias electricity capacity is roughly one-third hydro, one- third imported gas, and one-third nuclear. There are some small-scale hydropower plants due to come online, but the major resources are largely tapped. There is appetite for more nuclear power, but the scale of the projects makes them difficult to execute. Even one of the smallest plants that could be built would result in a large excess of power. Renewables are being installed mostly to displace gas and provide more power for the summer peak. The power market is in the process of being liberalized in order to align with EU rules. However, for the moment, Electricity Networks Armenia is the sole buyer and supplier of power for retail and industrial consumers. The generation market is fully liberalized, with a range of owners and smaller players. Liberalization, which has been legislated and is due to come into force this year, will mean that large energy consumers can choose to buy electricity directly from generators, although for the moment there is little demand for corporate PPAs.

Power tariffs are set by the so-called Tariff Council, which determines all public prices in the country from bus fares to electricity. At times there is a disconnect between those pushing for technology-specific tariffs and the Tariff Council, the main goal of which is controlling inflation through price control.Recently there has been some clarification for renewables in a studythat determined the wholesaletariff of $0.033/kWh would be profitable for renewable projects. Electricity prices in Azerbaijan are low compared to global levels but high for the region and as a percentage of income. Power prices are $0.052/kWh for commercial and $0.041-0.064/kWh for residential.

Bangladesh produces 70% of its electricity from gas power plants. However, as the countrys gas supplies dwindle, it plans to meet its rising electricity demand through imports from India, Nepal and Bhutan. Bangladesh is also investing in new coal and nuclear power projects with technical help from India and Russia. Private participation is allowed only in the power generation sector while transmission and distribution are owned by the government. The Bangladesh Power Development Board acts as a single wholesale-buyer of all electricity and thus restricts the options for sale of power. Currently there are no incentives for off-site captive generation and the selling of electricity by third-parties is restricted. Renewables, including hydro, produce only 2% of electricity and this may hold steady as rooftop solar projects increase in the coming years.

Cambodias power market is dominated by EDC, a utility that controls most of the grid and retails power to all grid-connected consumers. Nearly all of the generators are owned by independent power producers, which are able to sell to EDC only via a special license. In remote areas of the country, electricity is supplied by hundreds of private operators that generate, deliver and sell power; however, these operators lose their licenses to generate power as soon as the national grid arrives. Over 90% of grid-supplied power in Cambodia is generated by large hydro and coal-fired plants. Most of these units have been built since 2012, with the overall stack quadrupling as Cambodia sought to wean itself off imports as demand boomed.

Coal is still the dominant fuel in Chinas power system, accounting for 62% of capacity and 71% of generation in 2017. Wind and solar are growing rapidly, however, accounting for 17% of capacity and 7% of generation on aggregate. Renewable energy curtailment has been a chronic challenge, but regulators have implemented various measures to combat this, like mandating minimum dispatch and allowing renewables to participate in deregulated power sales. As a result, national average curtailment fell to 3.6% for solar and 8.7% for wind in 1H 2018, from 6% and 12% respectively in 2017. Regulators are piloting various market mechanisms including bilateral corporate PPAs, power exchanges, and spot markets to further liberalize the retail market.

The Indian power sector is unbundled and generation of power is handled by federal government-owned companies, state and private sector companies. Installed generating capacity was 346GW in June 2018, with renewables (excluding large hydro) accounting for 71GW. With coal taking a share of almost 60%, challenges with domestic coal supply are resulting in increased coal imports. Nevertheless, the government has reduced its coal capacity target for 2027 by 11GW to 238GW as the country seeks to replace coal with renewables through auctions. The UDAY (Ujjwal DISCOM Assurance Yojna) debt-restructuring program has been successful at overcoming some issues faced by financially distressed distribution companies. Now, more than 90% of the countrys electricity is covered by the program and companies in Gujarat, Chhattisgarh and Haryana have turned profitable according to the Indian Ministry of Power.

The power market in Indonesia is semi-unbundled: private players may only participate in generation, and accounted for 25% of the installed capacity in 2017. System operation, transmission and distribution is controlled by PLN, which is the sole offtaker. Private developers are not allowed to sign direct PPAs with consumers. Corporate users may only procure renewable power through on-site PV systems. Indonesias power mix is dominated by fossil fuels, which accounted for 87% of the installed capacity in 2017. The share of coal has increased from 36% to 49% of the installed capacity over 2010-17 to meet the rapid rise in electricity demand. Renewables share has declined due to lack of support from government.

Fossil fuels account for 86% of Kazakhstans installed generating capacity and approximately 90% of generation in 2017. This may change as the high-polluting Soviet-funded coal plants age, and more renewables are deployed, given the significant land and outstanding wind/solar resources. The country imports some electricity from Russia in its western part, but not significantly elsewhere. Fossil fuel new build is essentially on hold, except for an expansion of the Ekibastuz plant; renewable energy, despite slow growth in 2017, still has a number of wind/solar projects in the pipeline and will likely see a wave of new build by 2020. The existing renewables projects are prioritized in dispatch and little curtailment happens. The grid (KEGOC) is state-owned, while generation and retail sides allow the private sector; large power users can choose from which power supply companies to buy electricity although this does not apply to residential customers. The states Financial Settlement Center (FSC) is the only offtaker for renewables.

Kyrgyzstan does not have a competitive wholesale market. While the countrys vertically integrated state-owned utility, Kyrgyzenergo, was formally unbundled in 2001, state-controlled entities continue to dominate its power sector. Electric Power Plants JSC, for example, controls nearly 98% of power generation, the National Electric Energy Transmitting Co. has a monopoly in power transmission and four companies (that is, Vostokelectro, Jalalabatelectro, Oshelectro and Severelectro) handle nearly all power distribution. Kyrgyzstans installed power capacity has remained flat in recent years at around 3.8GW, but the country needs more capacity. Renewables besides large hydro play only a nominal role in the countrys power sector.

The domestic power market in Laos has a single-buyer structure, with Electricite du Laos (EDL) the sole buyer and retailer as well as the grid operator. Power generation was partially liberalized in 2010, when EDL spun off its large hydro assets under EDL-GEN, in which it owns a stake of about 75%. Independent power producers are also active in the market; they have been responsible for roughly 90% of the capacity additions since 2015. Capacity additions picked up rapidly from 2013-16, due to external demands: Thailands EGAT financed, contracted and now dispatches several new large hydro projects and a 2GW coal plant. As Thailand has become satiated, build has levelled off slightly.

Fossil fuels dominate Malaysia's energy mix at 87% of generation, with gas and coal leading the way. This trend is set the change as the newly elected government seeks to reduce the nation's dependence on coal and drive an ambitious green agenda. Malaysia's power sector is highly regulated and dominated by three state-owned utilities. A small number of IPPs operate, mostly focused on fossil fuels. Growth in renewables capacity was 4% over the last five years, led by solar after the introduction of the large-scale solar auctions. The new administration is on course to improve transparency in the power sector, stomping out the practice of direct awards/negotiations with large players and promoting competitive bidding.

Fossil fuels accounted for 95% of generation in 2017, although this may change as the high-polluting Soviet-funded coal plants age, and as renewables investment rises. In addition, grid-connected generating capacity is expanding, which should reduce Mongolias significant reliance on electricity imports from Russia in the western grid and to a lesser extent from China in its south. (Mongolia has four grids.) So far, almost 100% dispatch and offtake purchase is secured for wind and solar. In addition, Mongolia has approximately 1MW of off-grid solar and 0.87MW of solar-wind hybrids, which typically apply to soums and gers (Mongolian towns and living tents) distributed in remote villages. The power market is generally state-owned and the grid is regulated, without near-term plans for liberalization. The state is the biggest player in generation and distribution, and the National Dispatching Center is the only offtaker.

Myanmar only has 5GW of installed capacity as of 2017. Of this, 60% is hydro, 34% is gas and the remaining consists of biomass and coal. The government planned to transit to competitive bidding from traditionally bilateral negotiations in order to bring transparency and competition to the power market. In 2017, the Myingyan gas project was awarded via competitive bidding, the first in history. However, to expedite project development the government went back to bilateral negotiations with reputable developers via a special process called Notice to Proceed at the beginning of 2018, and issued approvals for four LNG-to-power projects amounting to more than 3GW. The government is said to be still considering competitive bidding for the future, although there are questions about its capacity to implement such a program.

The NEA enjoys monopoly control over the power market; however, increasing the role of private sector is one of the major goals of the government. Several PPAs have been signed between IPPs and Nepal Electricity Authority to privatize the sector. Solid biofuels used in the residential sector account for about 80% of total energy consumption in the country. Roughly about 23% of electricity is imported and the rest is generated by hydro plants.  Nepal has immense potential for hydropower and that continues to be the focus in all energy policy. Ambitious targets have been set for hydro, with small contributions expected from the wind and solar sectors as well. In 2017, Nepal increased its electricity imports, mainly from India. Power imports cost 15 billion Nepalese rupees in the last fiscal year.

Pakistan's renewable energy sector has been dominated by wind so far, but the solar sector has also picked up pace now. The power sector however has an albatross around its neck  a 'circular debt' burden of over a trillion rupees ($8 billion). Power distribution companies are stressed as the regulator allows them to claim only a part of their transmission and distribution losses from the consumer. The regulator also assumes 100% collection efficiency, which is not the case in actuality. This revenue gap of the distribution companies hits the generators and also the consumers. Tackling this burden would be one of the first tasks of the new government. While the power generation sector is open to competition, the transmission and distribution sector is largely controlled by government-owned entities. Some cities like Karachi have a private sector distribution company (K-Electric).

Before the 1980s, geothermal, oil/diesel and hydropower generation were the biggest share of installed capacity, but coal eclipsed those resources as demand burgeoned. Coal was the largest power source, at 47GWh (52%) in 2017, with the renewables share dwindling to 19% of generation. After the 2001 liberalization of the generation market under the EPIRA, Aboitiz Power, San Miguel Global Power and Trans Asia acquired the majority of assets. They currently own about 62% of all power generation assets in the Philippines. The Wholesale Electricity Spot Market (WESM) was also institutionalized at this time for Luzon and Visayas regions and will soon be open to Mindanao. The government has also opened more options for developers to sign power supply agreements (PSAs) directly with customers with a large enough demand. It also mandated utilities to facilitate retail opportunities for customers wanting renewable power through a Green Energy Option program. With a large increase in forecast demand there is potential for renewables to grab part of the pie. However, the Philippines is targeting coal to increase generation the most, up to five times the current level.

Six companies account for around 90% of power generation capacity in Singapore  Tuas Power, Senoko, YTL, Keppel Merlimau, Sembcorp, PacificLight and Tuaspring. Generators bid into the wholesale electricity market operated by the Energy Market Co., a subsidiary of Singapore Exchange. The retail power market is divided into contestable and non-contestable consumers. The contestable market serves industrial and commercial consumers that use over 2MWh of electricity per month. Licensed retailers, many of which are linked to generation companies, are permitted to sell power to contestable consumers at bespoke tariffs to meet the needs of customers. The contestable retail market is highly competitive, with around 30 licensed firms. Non-contestable consumers  small businesses and residences  must purchase their electricity from state-owned SP Group at a regulated tariff. The government launched a pilot program in April 2018 to liberalize the non-contested market in the district of Jurong, and plans to expand retail competition to the rest of the island. A market also exists for demand response where contestable consumers can bid to be paid to reduce their consumption during peak times.

The power market in the country is a long way away from liberalization. The CEB is yet to be unbundled, and seems to be on a constant collision path with the regulator PUCSL. Besides their differences on the ideal long-term generation mix for the country, the regulator is unhappy with the delays in new plant construction by the utility. Resorting to oil-fired emergency power is not only expensive, but also extremely polluting.

Coal accounted for nearly half of Taiwans power generation in 2017. This leading position is set to change with the governments energy transition to increase the share of gas power to 50% and renewables to 20% of total generation by 2025 while phasing out nuclear power, which accounted for 8% in 2017. To spur accelerated growth, policies have been introduced to give renewable energy priority dispatch and permission to be sold directly to end-users on the unregulated market. Fossil fuel generators can only sell power to Taipower  the vertically integrated utility that owned 80% of the islands total power capacity at the end of 2017  but liberalization for thermal generators is due to take effect in 6-9 years.

Barqi Tojik, a vertically integrated state-owned utility, dominates Tajikistans power sector. Despite its strong market position, the utility is in poor financial health due to low subsidized tariffs, losses on transmission and distribution services and mediocre collection rates. The government has granted Pamir Energy the authority to provide power generation, transmission, distribution and retails sales in one remote region, but Barqi Tojik acts as the utility for over 95% of the countrys population. Industrial players consume most of Tajikistans power.

Thailand's power market is partially liberalized, with the generation sector opened up to the participation from private players. State-owned utility EGAT is the sole offtaker of all generated electricity. The introduction of Small Power Producers (SPPs) and Very Small Power Producers (VSPPs) promoted the decentralization of power generation utilizing renewable energy. Although the share of renewables in the generation mix increased to approximately 11% by end-2017, Thailand still mainly relies on natural gas and coal, which account for 68.5% and 20.2% of power generation, to meet most of its power demand. The power development plan of Thailand aims to reduce the country's dependence on natural gas power generation to 40% by 2036.

Natural gas accounts for nearly 100% of the country's power mix, a significant portion of which is exported to neighboring countries. There are no clear regulations or tariffs to support other technologies and there is no competitive market for independent producers. Tukmenenergo, the state-owned utility, controls all aspects of the power market, including generation, transmission, distribution and exports. There are no formal plans to liberalize the market despite some movements to increase electricity tariffs. Some large industrials self-generate some power but are prohibited from selling excess back to the grid.

Uzbekistan's energy sector is a legacy of the Soviet era, complete with a centrally owned and operated utility. No part of the energy system is unbundled  generation, distribution and transmission fall under Uzbekenergo or its subsidiaries.Natural gas remains the main energy source in Uzbekistan, followed by coal and large hydro. There is no significant non-hydro renewable capacity. However, the recent announcement for 1GW of PV will increase the share of renewable capacity to nearly 10%. The PPA obligates Uzbekenergo to buy the entirety of the project's production. Outside of this bilaterallynegotiatedagreement, there is no government regulation that prioritizes renewable dispatch for other projects.

Large hydro and coal made up 75% of the installed capacity in 2017. Vietnam is one of the fastest growing electricity markets, with 11% CAGR of installed capacity in the past five years. Around two-thirds of the capacity installed in the last five years is coal-fired. Electricity imports from China and Laos were around 1.2% in 2017. Solar and wind are expected to play a major role to meet the renewables targets of 2020. The generation market is concentrated, with the government controlling about 60% of the installed capacity. No corporate PPAs were signed as of the end of 2017, but there is a lot of activity in the commercial and industrial rooftop PV sector.

Transmission and generation are separated into two distinct companies: KESH for generation, and OST for transmission. Acceptance into ENTSO-E, the European network of TSOs, is pegged to verification that OST is an unbundled TSO. However, retail and distribution are still combined under one distribution system operator, OSHEE. This entity missed the end of 2017 unbundling deadline, set in the 2015 Power Sector Law. In 2018, the government announced plans to break up OSHEE into three distinct companies: retail, distribution and service provider. There are some private players in generation and plans for more.

BiHs power fleet is roughly split between just over 2.1GW of capacity from five lignite power plants and an equal amount of hydro. As mentioned above, the aforementioned 50.6MW Mesihovina wind farm started operating in March 2018. Renewable energy capacity is minimal, but includes wind, solar, biomass and small hydro. Several further wind farms are planned, including two of 48MW each, in addition to six lignite power plants. While the electricity sector is open to private participation, the overwhelming share of generation and distribution is overseen by three vertically integrated, public utilities whose remit is geographically distributed. The transmission system is owned by a state-owned transco, Elektroprenos BiH and wholesale trading is policed by a comprehensive regulatory framework.

Most of Georgias power is supplied by a mix of small and large hydro plants. They are supplemented by gas, especially in the winter, when supply is low. The country has significant interconnection with Armenia, Turkey and Russia, which it uses to balance its supply. Still, the country has ambitions of becoming an energy exporter. Hydro capacity additions are slowing due to public opposition to new large-scale developments. Wind is popular, and could increase significantly if the government approves the project pipeline. The power market is being liberalized. The vast majority of power is currently bought through contracts, but a wholesale market has been growing slowly. The generation market is diverse, with Czech, U.S., and domestic players all owning capacity. There is little market for corporate PPAs, though rising commercial and industrial power prices could increase demand.

The Macedonian power sector has been unbundled and partially privatized. ELEMs monopoly on generation ended in 2008 insofar as big industrial consumers are concerned (and, since 2014, 230 companies with annual revenues of at least 10 million euros ($11.38 million) are allowed to choose their supplier). Thanks to the governments adoption of an energy law in April 2018, this choice will be extended to small firms and households from 2019. Yet ELEM maintains control of the countrys two major coal power stations, with a total capacity of 800MW, as well as most smaller generation assets. State-owned Mepso operates the electricity transmission system and EVN, an Austrian utility, has enjoyed a monopoly on electricity distribution for over a decade.

Russias electricity market is broken into competitive 'price zones' where there are wholesale power markets (including: European Russia, the Urals and Siberia); non-competitive areas where there are regulated power rates (for example: the Far East); and isolated areas where there are no wholesale power markets (for example: Sakhalin). Power transmission is entirely state-run (by the Federal Grid Company) and both power generation and distribution are mostly state-controlled. At the end of 2017, Russia had an installed power capacity of 239GW.

In 2017, some 70% of Serbia's generation came from coal, while most of the remaining 30% came from a combination of large and small hydro facilities.  Serbia has struggled to meet the unbundling requirement under the EU's so-called third energy package. As of late 2017, the state-owned TSO, Elektromrea Srbija (EMS), gained its license to operate and transmit electricity on the transmission system. To satisfy concerns over independent operation -- since the government also runs the state utility, Elektroprivreda Srbije (EPS)  EPS and EMS are operated by different ministries. But generation, retail and distribution fall under the control of the state-owned utility EPS. Serbia's import and export balances are sensitive to the country's hydrology  for its hydro generation, the condition of its aging fossil fuel plants, and demand dynamics from one of its seven interconnected, country neighbors.

Turkey has undertaken ambitious power market reform to privatize and liberalize the sector, and exploit domestic energy resources. This has primarily meant an emphasis on lignite and hydro, as well as renewables. The government plans to add as much as 12.5GW of nuclear capacity by 2030, though only one 4.8GW Russian-backed plant has broken ground, and still is unlikely to be commissioned before 2025. The historic dominance of coal and gas generation is likely to continue, at least in the short term. In the 2017 generation mix coal accounted for 33% and gas 37%. Renewables additions, mainly wind and solar but also geothermal and biomass, are all growing, but face an uncertain future due to lack of clarity on the feed-in tariff.

Nuclear plants supplied more than half the electricity generated in Ukraine in 2017  a proportion that has increased in recent years. Nuclear has stepped in as coal-fired power plants have struggled to secure fuel supplies after the war in the east of the country and the annexation of Crimea. Renewables account for something less than 2% of generation  a proportion that is increasing, albeit still at a quite slow pace. Reforms under the new Electricity Law, which is effective from July 2019, will clarify the offtakers role and standardize PPAs, for which there is no commercial market at present. This will facilitate renewables developers access to the power market. The new law will establish a wholesale power market, an important step for IPPs to operate in the country. Generation is partially privatized, and DTEK is by far the largest single player there. Regional gas distribution is unbundled, yet the unbundling of state-controlled oil and gas company Naftogaz faces severe delays.

Argentinas power matrix remains largely reliant on thermal and large hydro assets. Currently, 51% of installed capacity is gas power plants, with hydro representing 30%. The country has a considerable amount of oil & diesel assets at 11% of the mix. Renewables sum to only 2.5%. Argentina added approximately 4GW of gas assets in the last year alone, when it also retired 1.7GW of oil & diesel plants. The total capacity of clean plants added was less than 60MW in 2017, although it is expected the country will commission 3.8GW in the short term, as a result of the three rounds of renewable tenders. Despite considerable effort, it is unlikely the country will meet its 8% renewables goal by year-end 2018. In December 2017, only 2% of its generation came from small hydro, wind, solar and biomass. Most of the clean generation is due to small hydro power plants.

Bolivias subsidization of natural gas prices limits free competition among players in the electricity market. Nevertheless, renewables represent a significant portion of the generation base. Eighteen percent of its installed capacity comes from biomass, small hydro, solar, and wind. Bolivia is seeking to expand its total installed capacity with a strategic objective of exporting electricity to neighboring countries, a plan that entails construction of new, primarily hydro, facilities, making the grid predominantly hydro (74% by 2025, up from 23% in 2017), a dramatic change from the current composition of the matrix. ENDE, through its 11 subsidiaries, is responsible for most generation, transmission, and distribution in the system.

Brazil has the largest power market in Latin America, with total installed capacity of 157GW in 2017. The countrys size, plentiful resources and conducive policies have made Brazil the regions main renewable energy market and one of the top 10 in the world. Its matrix remains highly reliant on hydropower, which accounted for roughly 75-80% of the countrys generation in the past five years. The heavy reliance on one source came at a high cost in 2014: a prolonged drought put Brazils water supply and energy matrix into stress, exposing the market to costly generation from fossil-fueled plants. The hydro crisis emphasized the countrys need for generation diversification. Auctions and net metering will continue to be crucial policies to develop Brazils power sector. In terms of structure, the power market is fully unbundled and fairly evenly split between state-owned and private-sector players.

Chile has a National Electric System (Sistema Elctrico Nacional, or SEN) as well as two smaller isolated systems in the south of the country, the Sistema Elctrico de Aysn (SEA) and Sistema Elctrico de Magallanes (SEM). SEN was created with the connection of the countrys two primary power systems, the Sistema Interconectado del Norte Grande (SING) and the Sistema Interconectado Central (SIC), at the end of 2017. The process of interconnection is ongoing. The SIC and SING sub-systems together account for 99% of Chiles total installed capacity, with 18GW and 6GW installed, respectively. In November 2017, a SIC-SING interconnection was commissioned via a 600-kilometer transmission line. Ahead of that, the SING and SIC system operators merged.  
In 2017, Chile had 1.9GW of solar and 1.3GW of wind capacity, representing 13% of total installed capacity and renewable assets represented 24% of all energy generated. Wind generation in Chile surged from 1.4TWh in 2014 to 3.5TWh in 2017, while solar output spiked from 0.5TWh to 3.9TWh. Together, wind and solar represented 9.4% of the countrys total power generation in 2017, up from virtually nothing five years ago.

Of Colombias total installed capacity of 16.8GW at year-end 2017, large hydro represented 65% and provided 79% of the 67TWh generated that year, followed by natural gas at 9%. Other renewables accounted for 6% of generation, with most coming from small hydro. Capacity additions since 2010 have been dominated by hydro, as well as oil and diesel. Among renewables, Colombia had only 882MW of small hydro as well as a single 18MW wind plant and a single 10MW solar plant commissioned in 2017. Colombias power market has numerous private and state-owned players across segments, but is defined by substantial concentration. Empresas Publicas Medelin (EPM), Emgesa, and Isagen together accounted for 68% of generation in 2017. The fate of the landmark, 2.4GW Ituango hydro project is a key uncertainty in the countrys outlook. Previously expected to begin operations in late 2018, but now postponed indefinitely following a series of landslides and flooding at the site, whether Ituango can be recovered has major implications for Colombias firm supply outlook, its pace of non-renewables adoption, and power prices in the near and medium terms.

Costa Ricas electricity prices jumped 30% between 2010 and 2017. Between 2016 and 2017, prices spiked 15% as it was necessary use expensive diesel-fired power to satisfy a 6.6% increase in electricity demand. The increase in demand was driven by power price reductions applied in the previous months, as well as greater economic activity.

The Dominican Republic had 3.7GW of installed capacity in 2017. Oil and diesel are the main sources of electricity, accounting for 1.8GW, or approximately 50% of the total. Small hydro, wind, solar and biomass together account for 10% of the total. Although generation is open to private players, it remains dominated by state-owned assets. The distribution segment is divided into three public companies: Edeeste, Edenorte and Edesur. All state-owned companies are managed by the Corporacin Dominicana de Empresas Elctricas Estatales.

In Ecuador, the Ministry of Electricity and Renewable Energy (MEER) oversees renewable energy policy and planning. In 2015, the Act Establishing the Public Electric Power Service (LOSPEE) was published, overseeing the power sector in Ecuador. Under this law, the National Electricity Board (CONELEC) becomes the Agency for Regulation and Control of Electricity (ARCONEL). While generation is open to private players in Ecuador, transmission is under the responsibility of state-owned utility Corporacin Elctrica del Ecuador (CELEC EP Transelectric). Distribution is divided between 11 majority-public companies, in which MEER is the majority shareholder. In 2017, Ecuador had a total of 8.2GW of installed capacity, with hydro representing 49% and thermal power accounting for 42% of its mix. In 2016, the country doubled its hydro capacity, which totals 3.9GW today. Clean energy, encompassing small hydro, biomass, wind and solar plants, represents 10% of total capacity.

El Salvador had 1.9GW of installed capacity in 2017. Oil and diesel constitute the single largest source, with 41% of the total, followed by large hydro with 29%. Among renewables, biomass and geothermal dominate, with 14% and 11%, respectively, however PV capacity has increased four-fold since 2015, reaching 60MW in 2017. Both wind and solar are poised to grow over the next two years with 100MW of solar PV projects and 70MW of wind expected to come online. El Salvadors power market has been unbundled and generation is open to private operators. The country is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System and is connected to Guatemala and Honduras by 286km of transmission lines.

The power market in Guatemala is unbundled. The country has 50 companies (private and state-owned) acting in generation, distribution, and transmission. Guatemala is connected via the Central American Electrical Integration System (SIEPAC) to Honduras and El Salvador. Northern Guatemala is also connected to Mexicos transmission system. Energy generated by large hydro almost doubled between 2016-2017, from 2.6GWh to 4GWh. In 2012 and 2014 Guatemala held two auctions and contracted a total of 452MWh from wind, solar and hydro.

Haiti has around 284MW of installed generating capacity, with 80% comprising fossil fuel plants. The remaining 20% comes from the Pligre hydro plant, which is undergoing restoration, and a number of other small hydro plants. EDH owns 44% of Haitis generation capacity and is responsible for transmission along the 1,500km of power lines that run across the island. Due to infrastructure limitations, EDHs provision of power to Haitis capital Port-au-Prince and several nearby cities is intermittent. Meanwhile, the use of diesel generators, kerosene lamps and other forms of off-grid technologies is widespread. Despite EDHs monopoly on generation, thermal power PPAs have been awarded for 15 years. IPPs are responsible for generating most of the power sold by EDH.

Honduras has a total installed capacity of 2.6GW. In 2017, the largest share, or 37%, of total electricity produced came from oil and diesel plants. Large hydro represented 19% of generation, while other renewables (biomass, small hydro, solar and wind) accounted for a combined 40% of power production. Solar capacity has increased by 16% since 2015, rising to over 450MW in 2017, making it the second largest source after oil and diesel. Honduras is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System (SIEPAC) and is connected to El Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua by transmission lines. Honduras is a net importer in the regional market.

In 2017, almost 90% of Jamaicas total 4.7TWh of electricity production came from  fossil fuel plants. Renewable energy (small hydro, solar and wind) accounted for the remaining 10%. Clean energy capacity started increasing in 2016, when auction-winning projects came online. Among the winners, wind plants with combined capacity of 60MW and one 20MW PV plant were commissioned in 2016. A 37MW PV project located in Westmoreland Parish is expected to be online by early 2019. Private utility Jamaica Public Service (JPS) is in charge of 60% of generation and 100% of transmission and distribution services on the island.

Mexicos generation matrix is dominated by thermal sources, which represented approximately 81% of total generation in 2017, primarily natural gas and diesel. Hydro accounted for approximately 10% of generation, followed by nuclear and wind at 3% each. At year-end 2017, Mexico had 4.2GW of wind capacity commissioned, by far the largest renewable technology excluding large hydro, with total solar commissioned capacity standing at just 344MW. However, renewables dominate capacity additions. Through 2020, Mexico is expected to undergo a solar boom, with over 10GW added to the grid in addition to 7GW of wind. A fundamental change introduced by Mexico's energy reform is the separation of state-owned vertically integrated utility CFE, which holds the majority of generation assets and retains monopoly over transmission and distribution. Grid operation moved from within CFE to newly created, independent grid operator CENACE, which is to guarantee open and non-discriminatory access to transmission. Deregulation of generation in 2016 created Mexicos wholesale market, which has operated on a day-ahead basis since January 2016, with the real-time spot market beginning in January 2017.

Renewables account for the biggest share of power generation, reaching 56% of the 4.5TWh produced in 2017  up from 47% in 2016. Fossil fuel plants were still responsible for a substantial share, but decreased from 52% in 2016 to 44% in 2017. Nicaragua's power sector is unbundled and distinct actors (both state- and privately owned) participate in the generation and distribution sectors. A total of 18 companies with active generation contracts and IPPs hold a large share of installed capacity.

Panama had 3.3 GW of installed generating capacity in 2017. Oil and large hydro are Panamas main sources of electricity, with hydro responsible for almost half (1.2GW) of the countrys total installed capacity. The sum of solar and wind capacity jumped from zero in 2013 to 397MW in 2017. Panamas power market has been unbundled, and generation is open to private operators. Panama is also part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System and is connected to Costa Rica via 150 km of transmission lines.

Paraguays electricity market is overseen by the Department of Mines and Energy, which is under the Ministry of Public Works and Communications (Ministerio de Obras Pblicas y Comunicaciones) and controlled by state-owned vertically integrated utility Administracin Nacional de Electricidad (ANDE). ANDE allows the participation of independent power producers (IPPs), however, as of 2018, there were no independent power producers registered in the country. On October 1, 2015, the government of Paraguay submitted its Intended Nationally Determined Contribution to the United Nations, in which it committed unconditionally to cut greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by 10% by 2030, compared to 2000 levels. Paraguay also committed to an additional reduction of 10% below the unconditional target by 2030, subject to international support.

In 2017, Peru generated 8% of its total 49TWh from renewable sources. Large hydro accounted for 52% in 2017, up from 40% in 2016, despite no significant capacity additions in this technology. Natural gas registered 37% in 2017, down from 46%. Coal, oil and diesel altogether generated the complementary stake. Comparing with total installed capacity in 2010, the year the first renewable auction was held, Peru remains at the same share for clean installed capacity, 7%. Despite observing a considerable increase of 243MW in onshore wind capacities comparing with 2010, the country decommissioned 282 MW of small hydro assets in 2017. The technology that had the most additions since 2010 was large hydro, totaling 1.5 GW. Peru established a 5% renewable target of its total electricity consumption to be met by 2013. The country reached the level established, but it did not define a new one.

Uruguays electricity market is overseen by the Ministry of Industry, Energy and Mines and controlled by UTE. UTE allows the participation of independent power producers through project- or technology-specific tenders, usually based on 20-year power purchase agreements. Uruguay relies primarily on hydro resources to meet its power needs. Throughout renewables auctions, the country managed to diversify its power mix and reduce dependency on hydro. In 2017, 52% of the 14.3TWh generated in the country came from large hydro plants, while 26% came from wind, 18% from biomass and less than 2% from PV plants. Thermal plants had only a 2% contribution, compared to 35% in 2012.

Egypt's generating capacity mix remains decidedly fossil-fuel-focused, with more than a 90% share. This is principally because the government has sought to build out capacity quickly after the electricity shortages a few years ago. As part of this strategy, Siemens completed in 2H 2018 its 'Egypt megaproject' to build three combined-cycle gas turbine plants totaling 14.4GW. As a result, gas-fired generating capacity has expanded by 200% over 2010-17 and is expected to continue as the government seeks to exploit its recently discovered domestic reserves. With regard to structure, at present, the state dominates the power market, with the Egyptian Electricity Holding Company (EEHC) and its subsidiaries owning more than 90% of each segment. The 2015 electricity law envisaged a gradual market liberalization but progress has been limited.

The energy ministry acts as policy-maker, power producer, service provider, operator and regulator in Iraq. Gas turbines account for over half of the generation capacity, with steam comprising almost a third. Hydro has traditionally played a role but damage from recent wars has limited generation capacity. Electricity imports from Iran and Turkey help meet some demand. The ministry aims to have IPPs build 9GW of power capacity by 2025 in an attempt to meet domestic demand and reduce reliance on imports. By unbundling the market and introducing the private sector into the distribution and generation segments, the ministry hopes to improve its financial position.

Fossil fuels account for 84% of generation capacity in Jordan, followed by 12% from solar and 4% from wind. Capacity additions will accelerate in coming years with the commissioning of projects from the first rounds of direct proposals. Distinct bodies exist in the sector for production, transmission and distribution. There are separate companies for generation and distribution while transmission is the responsibility of Nepco. There is no wholesale generation market and Nepco purchases all generated electricity. Nepco has a template wind and solar PPA that currently exposes them to deemed energy compensation. Jordanian power prices are not market driven as generators cannot sell directly to the distributors and the government subsidizes tariffs.

Kuwaits electric power system is vertically integrated and the Ministry of Electricity and Water (MEW) is responsible for all activities in the power sector. Fossil fuels account for the bulk of the generation mix, with renewables representing less than 5%. Still, the country is committed to increasing this share to 15% by 2030 and a number of projects are under way to meet this goal. The Kuwait Authority for Partnership Projects oversees the development of PPAs according to law 116 of 2014. However, there is little experience in this area. The first phase of the Az-Zour North project was the first IPP in Kuwait, but the model is yet to be refined so it can provide a benchmark for future developments.

EDL has a monopoly on transmission and distribution and retail of electricity. Any reforms to EDL or the power market are unlikely in the current political stalemate. Diesel and heavy-fuel generation dominate Lebanons power mix, in the form of ageing plants, leased power ships, or illegal private generators. The country imports some electricity from the Syrian interconnector. The law authorizing IPPs is still pending implementation; however, an exceptional decree granting the executive temporary powers to license new projects introduced in 2014 has made possible the current auction pipeline.

Natural gas accounted for over 97% of all generation in 2017, and diesel-fired production made up much of the remainder. Installed solar capacity consists of a 300kW project and a handful of mostly rooftop PV systems. Several IPPs are involved in generation, but procurement, transmission and distribution are respectively controlled by the OPWP, the state-managed Oman Electricity Transmission Co., and joint-stock distribution companies under the publicly owned Nama group. A notable exception is the PDO  the Sultanates largest (largely state-owned) oil producer  which issued a 100MW PV tender in January 2018 under which it is to procure electricity through a 23-year PPA. Although 400MW of interconnection capacity allows for imports from the U.A.E., the transmission line is rarely used.

Oil accounts for the largest slice of generation capacity and this is a characteristic of the power generation sector that Saudi Arabia is intent on changing. It will do so by developing additional non-associated and unconventional gas fields and by adding more natural gas-fired capacity. Another big thrust for Saudi Arabia is solar and wind technology, development of which is just starting now. The power market is currently regulated and centralized, however, plans exist to privatize key institutions in the sector by 2020. Currently the Saudi Electric Co., through its wholly owned subsidiary National Grid, has a monopoly on electricity power transmission, operation, control, maintenance and rent of transmission network lines.

Installed renewables capacity  mostly solar  has grown swiftly over the past five years, rising from 14MW in 2012 to 351MW in 2017. Yet generation is still dominated by hydrocarbons: oil and natural gas account for well over 99% of the current output. A growing project pipeline is set to increase the share of renewables  the Ministry of Energy has set its sights on issuing tenders at a rate of 1GW a year until 2050. Ongoing projects include a 1.17GW PV plant in Abu Dhabi, the construction of which started in 2017. Four utilities have a monopoly on procurement, transmission and distribution. Generation is, however, open to private participation: over 90% of Abu Dhabis generation is provided by IPPs.

Installed generating capacity in Palestine is concentrated in one large-scale diesel-fired plant in the Gaza Strip, and some small-scale solar projects. The Gaza Power Plant is not operational due to fuel shortages, although there are plans to convert it to gas to make its operation more economical. The country relies heavily on electricity imports, mostly from Israel although also from Egypt and Jordan. There are plans to add more domestic generation capacity, including a 450MW CCGT plant, and renewables uptake is also meant to reduce reliance on imports.

Economic activity in Algeria is known to be stymied by excessive red tape and administrative process that can be costly in time. This holds also true in the energy sector, although the extensive set of regulation also provides developers a firm legal basis on which to build their projects. Sonelgaz is the offtaker for Algeria's grid. The company's financials have been extremely strained in recent years and it is suffering from losses, fraud and inefficiencies. However, it is a public company and the government or public banks have supported it financially.

Angola  like its fellow oil exporters  continues to face tough economic conditions, following the drop in commodity prices. But after GDP rose by an estimated 1.5% in 2017, Sub-Saharan Africas third-biggest economy is due to return to higher growth rates over the next few years. Angolas electrification rate in 2017 was 35%. In spite of the countrys history of hydropower, for 2025, the country expects to invest in renewable energy, connecting over 800MW to the grid.

The MCA II program sets Benin on a good track to develop the energy sector. The aim of the program is to reinforce the energy sector and hopefully see spillover effects into other sectors spurring economic activity.  The country has substantial off-grid electrification potential, as only 7% of the rural population has access to electricity. The OCEF, subsidiary of the MCA II, has set up a fund for off-grid electrification. The first call for proposals closed in May, and a shortlist of projects was published in September 2018.

Botswana boasts an impressive electrification rate of 59.05%. Botswana's power demand has plateaued in recently years, sitting at 610MW for the last three years. Demand has peaked as the mining sector has experienced a slowdown due to the commodities price slump  the largest state mine in the country filed for liquidation in 2016 and halted all operations. BPC has an aging power plant fleet. The oldest plant, commissioned in the late 1980s, is currently being refurbished and is expected to be operational in 2018.

Power demand has been rising rapidly, with peak demand growing on average by 13% a year since 2010. Electrification has barely kept up with growing demand: The electrification rate is 21% and in rural areas it is almost non-existent (2%). Burkina Faso has great solar and hydro resources, but as a landlocked country it has limited wind potential. The low rural electrification rate and high solar resources offer an opportunity for off- and mini-grid PV projects. Mini-grids can be owned and operated by private actors, while developers of installations over 25kW need a concession, which is controlled by ARSE.

Burundi is one of the poorest countries in the world and relies on foreign aid, which accounts for over half of the government budget. The country has only just emerged from two decades of civil war and is hampered by political tensions, corruption and inefficient bureaucracy that significantly adds to the cost of trade. In 2012, it ranked 131st out of 132 countries in the World Economic Forum (WEF) Enabling Trade Index, Several non-tariff barriers hamper private sector growth, including weak infrastructure, high corporate taxes and a lack of access to long-term credit. Nevertheless, Burundi has a relatively open trade regime, which aligns with the countrys Economic Growth and Poverty Reduction Strategy. As a part of regional integration strategy, Burundi joined the East African Community (EAC) in 2007 and began implementing the common external tariff (CET) in 2009. Burundi also made major reforms in 2011 to improve the procedure for creating a business, simplify construction permitting and ensure better investor protection.

Cameroon has seen average economic growth of 3.7% a year over the last decade but it has slowed recently owing to falling revenue from oil, rubber and coffee production. The country has a relatively weak electrification rate of 54%, with less than 30% in rural areas. The government aims to reach 3GW of power capacity by 2020, mainly through new hydropower plants, and off-grid solar in rural areas. The Rural Electrification Master Plan, in its second phase, aims to electrify 10,000 locations by 2035, securing 50,000 connections annually over 20 years. The government is also preparing a new framework to regulate private off-grid renewables projects, although the policys legal status is unclear.

Electricity demand has been relatively flat. Despite access to electricity rising, primarily in the urban areas, the limited time that there is access to electricity means that actual demand remains flat. Looking forward, as distribution grids and electrification rates improve, this is anticipated to rise. The rate of electrification is highly dependent on the upkeep of the distribution grid and the power plant fleet because outages determine when and where is supplied with electricity. There are programs to modernize the systems, funded primarily by international development banks, although these will not be sufficient to enable wider electrification of the population.

Despite having one of the worlds lowest electrification rates, and an official commitment toward providing electricity to 15% of the rural population by 2023, no coordinated electrification plan has been launched. Microgrid projects are few and far between for want of regulations covering off-grid generation. Meanwhile, the absence of a program aimed at rehabilitating the countrys ailing thermal fleet underlines the governments bet on renewables to meet future demand. Yet concerns remain regarding a lack of investment in transmission and distribution, with grid congestion a particular issue for projects in and around Ndjamena, the capital. The situation is exacerbated by the opacity surrounding grid extension plans, none of which have been published by the utility.

Mired in an economic crisis sparked by plummeting oil prices, the country has been teetering on the brink of insolvency since 2016. Congos business environment has taken a hit as a result, reducing the attractiveness of untested renewable energy investment. Moreover, the government appears more interested in spending what few resources it can muster on large hydro than in other renewables, despite the need to deploy off-grid solutions to electrify large swathes of the rural population. Even investment in the countrys dams, however, has been lacking. Although much of the current hydro fleet is decrepit, no concerted modernization plan is under way.

Mining activity will drive near-term growth in power demand in the DRC, in part due to the increase in global demand for specialty metals such as copper and cobalt that the country has in abundant supply. Copperbelt Energys plans to build two grid-connected solar PV projects for the mining sector are evidence of this. The government plan to triple the current national electrification rate to 32% by 2030 is likely to mean that favorable policies will be introduced for mini-grids or off-grid solar. However, continuing unrest, particularly in the lead-up to the elections in December 2018, may lead to power demand stagnation. Most DRC power plants are hydro-electric stations that do not require near-term upgrades.

Cote d'Ivoire's peak electricity demand has steadily increased by an average of 7% each year since 2011. Although the urban electrification rate is high (92%), the rural electrification rate is still relatively low (38%)  full electrification is expected by 2025. Demand is therefore expected to continue to grow in the coming years. The government has established electrification through the main grid as its priority solution for the development of the power sector, with little focus on isolated grids. Mini-grids are currently not allowed, and self-generation projects cannot sell electricity to their neighbors. The rules could change post 2020, when the concession contract of the utility expires, although what will happen then is unclear at present.

The absence of a reliable electricity supply in many areas of the country offers opportunities, especially for minigrid developers, but Eritrea is an extremely closed country and doing business is difficult. Power consumption per capita is among the lowest in Africa, which also offers opportunities, if capacity and infrastructure are improved.

Power demand is expected to grow as Ethiopia is Africa's fastest growing economy. The government is also prioritizing electrification, and aims for universal access by 2025, which would further increase power demand. Ethiopia has strong wind and solar resources, which it intends to exploit, while remaining fully committed to hydro. It is continuing work on the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam megaproject, which would add 6GW of power to the mix when commissioned, although it is already well behind schedule. Ethiopia intends to add more large hydro projects, as well as more capacity across nearly all renewables technologies. No regulations prohibit corporate PPAs, but so far all generation is purchased by EEP.

Power demand in Ghana has been growing, in part thanks to an increase in the percentage of the population with access to electricity. However, for the industrial sector, a significant challenge is the lack of access to a reliable electricity supply. The government believes that if the reliability of supply can be improved, industry will grow. This has become key to the restructuring of ECG, part of which requires the Meralco consortium to invest in improving the efficiency of the transmission network.

Electrification will continue to push up demand, with 70% of the population remaining unconnected despite a 10% increase in national electricity access rates since 2010. That less than a tenth of the rural population is hooked up to the grid renders distributed energy options all the more attractive. Crisscrossed by an estimated 1,165 watercourses, the country has considerable small hydro potential  over 300 sites have been mapped, many of which could support microgrids. Backed by the EU and World Bank, the government is poised to develop the first such location on the Tinkisso river. Existing thermal plants have been modernized; a program funded by the European Investment Bank aims to do the same for the countrys large hydro assets.

Kenyas power demand is the highest compared to East African Community (EAC) countries, and has seen moderate growth of 5.8% CAGR from 2012/13 to 2016/17, reaching 7,701GWh per year. It was partially driven by growing demand from residential customers that could benefit from a subsidized grid connection cost. Kenya Power introduced night-time discounted tariff for manufacturers in December 2017, which is likely increase the industrial power demand in 2017/18. Overall, Kenya has a relatively friendly environment for doing business compared to the other countries in Sub-Saharan Africa. Its robust value chain and international lending presence relative to its EAC neighbors makes it the least susceptible to currency risk for developers.

Lesotho is land-locked by South Africa. It imports all of its petroleum, some wood fuel and about a third of its electricity needs. This problem of energy security and access and declining biomass stocks is exacerbated by mountainous terrain, which limits network expansion. The government is committed to sustainable development and clean energy projects, especially those that help to increase electrification in rural areas. Peak power demand in 2016 was 153MW, but this is expected to grow to 304MW by 2020 and 432MW by 2030

The refurbishment of the Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant was a game-changer for the Liberian energy system. Power quality and reliability has since improved, and retail rates have dropped. However, demand for electricity far exceeds supply and significant grid issues persist. Customers complain of lengthy wait times for new connections, and power producers have struggled to enter into agreement to supply LEC. Outside of Monrovia, microgrid development has commenced despite the lack of a dedicated policy framework and regulatory oversight. Import duty exemptions on clean energy equipment brought into the country by aid organizations have been exploited by all developers cycling products through eligible agencies.

The Libyan economy has suffered from more than two decades of sanctions and a violent conflict that has stifled economic development. Still, power demand has been fueled by largely subsidized electricity prices and a lack of energy efficiency regulations in buildings. Solar and wind power have great potential in Libya but their contribution to power generation is still negligible. GECOL has plans for a large power capacity expansion program in the next 15 years, although its development depends entirely on the availability of funds and details remain scarce.

Jirama, which is the sole offtaker on the main grid, is under considerable financial stress and generators have started to be paid in treasury bonds, highlighting the high level of off-taker risk on the island. The budget gap covered by the government to support social retail tariffs and high fuel-import bills doubled from 2009 to 2014 to reach $150 million despite lower energy commodity prices at the time. The growth of renewables in the mix will improve the financial health of the utility and is government priority as a result. The 80% of the population that remains without access to electricity in Madagascar also presents an enormous opportunity for developers to get stuck in and deliver off-grid projects.

Malawi's electrification rate in 2017 is 10-11%, according to the Department of Energy Affairsand World. The country plans to more than double power supply by 2023 to end chronic blackouts. Currently, Malawi has 395MW of installed capacity, but President Peter Mutharika aims to raise it to 720MW in two years and to at least 1GW by 2023, as well as stating that the country needs not less than 2GW. The nation is going to expand its hydroelectric system with new dams and will diversify sources to include coal, wind, solar and gas. There are plans to complete the 300MW Kammwamba coal-fired facility by 2021, with a further two coal projects in the pipeline totalling 800MW.

Between 2005 and 2015, electricity sales in Mali grew by 8% annually on average. It is estimated sales will jump fourfold by 2025 compared with 2015, and annual growth of 15% is expected, mainly driven by low and high voltage clients. Electrification in rural areas is still very low, but grew from 1% in 1995 to 17% in 2017, mainly through the deployment of diesel-backed mini-grids operated by private local players. Solar/diesel hybrid plants are increasingly being deployed. The rural electrification agency is responsible for providing those operators with both grants and authorization, making the process of setting up a mini-grid efficient, although not always transparent.

Officials predict that coming years could see a tripling of demand with the completion of three large transmission projects linking up large urban centers. Investment in renewables is set to continue despite imported hydropower and the allure of offshore gas. Meanwhile, access to electricity in rural areas will be bolstered when the third branch of the national electrification program, RIMFIL, is brought to bear. Often coupled with thermal generation, off-grid solar will remain crucial to powering Mauritanias remote hinterlands. Although such hybrid plants as Kiffa are being built with future grid expansion in mind, distributed renewables will continue to play an important role in bringing electricity to rural communities.

Moroccos electricity demand has grown at an annual average rate of 5.1% since 2010, slightly outpacing average economic growth of 3.5%. Of particular importance to the energy sector, peak electrical demand has also risen at a similar rate to total demand. Morocco has had great success in the electrification of rural areas, with the ONEE connecting more than 99% of the rural population to the grid by 2014. The renewable energy agency, Masen, has been instrumental in reducing both barriers and risk in Moroccan renewables investment. It has borne currency risk, performed environmental studies and carried out land preparation, issued green bonds, acted as an offtaker, and blended concessional finance to consolidate loans with debt profiles suited to both developers and Masen. All of these functions have contributed to the success of the projects to date and have helped streamline renewables investment in the country.

Progress in extending electricity access to the wider population has been slow. As it stands, only 29% of the population is electrified. But power demand has been growing at pace, with peak consumption tripling since 2010. For on-grid projects, EDM has signed PPAs with IPPs. However, these are negotiated on a case-by-case basis but are usually long-term, with the duration of tenors starting at 20 years.

Namibia has one of the best solar resources in the world. Thanks to its geographic position and arid climate, a single-axis tracking PV project has a capacity factor as high as 30.2%.  The coastal areas have great wind resources as well. The electrification rate in the urban areas (77%) is much higher than in rural areas (30%). Providing access to the rural population is the biggest challenge in Namibia; being the least densely populated country in Africa, rural areas are very scarcely populated. In these areas, grid extensions are not feasible. Big investments in off-grid systems and mini-grids will be necessary to reach the 50% rural electrification target by 2020. So far, mini-grids have been developed top-down by the government, but the administration is keen to discuss public-private partnership arrangements with investors.

Future demand will be driven by the countrys continuing electrification. Alongside similar initiatives, the World Banks NESAP is expected to make considerable progress in raising what is among the worlds lowest access rate  Nigelec hopes to double its coverage over the next five years.
