Yet the historically slow rate of progress in this area leaves off-grid renewables well-suited to bringing electricity to rural areas. There is no national modernization program for the countrys power fleet, with ailing thermal plants and generators being repaired as they break down. The government is eager to push the development of renewables due to twin prospects of increasing Nigerian electricity costs and trading through the West African Power Pool, which is to be fully operational in 2020.

In 2016 alone, Nigerians spent $16 billion to power private diesel and gasoline generators, with more than 60% of companies having access to, or significantly relying on, generators, compared to less than 20% in South Africa. The potential for minigrids in Nigeria is substantial: a recent A.I. study has identified as many as 10,000 possible minigrid sites. That compares with GIZ's estimate of 4,000. In addition, the minigrid regulation Nigeria has in force since 2016, though not perfect yet, it arguably giving minigrid developers greater confidence. Nigerias strongest clean energy resource is solar (4-6.5 kWh/m2/day irradiation) followed by small-hydro (as much as 3.5GW).

Rwanda prides itself on being one of the best markets to do business in among Sub-Saharan African countries and has an appetite for domestic and foreign investment to serve its fast-growing economy. The Rwanda Development Board has been created to support private sector players entering the country, complementing the strong presence of commercial and donor-backed lenders on the ground. Most of the growth in the energy space has been off-grid, as Rwanda has reached critical mass in its on-grid sector with an oversupply of generation. The Government of Rwanda has developed transparent grid extension plans, designating specific areas for off-grid development, which has led to dozens of off-grid and mini-grid companies operating in the country.

Senegal has a national electrification rate of 68%, which has steadily increased over recent years in line with the target for 100% electrification by 2025. Access to electricity in rural areas is much lower, at just 40%, but the division of the country into concession areas to be electrified by private companies should speed up the process through the installation of mini-grids. The discovery of gas reserves off Senegals coast could also improve the outlook for domestic resource exploitation. Economic growth is projected to remain at 6.8% this year, according to the World Bank. Its stable government and adoption of the Plan Senegal Emergent in 2014 have helped to make it an economic hub in West Africa.

Sierra Leone is increasingly attractive for renewables development. Newly minted president Julius Maada Bio has launched a crackdown on corruption within government and state-run organizations, while promising to push ahead with electricity sector reform. Import and sales tax exemptions have fostered the development of a pico solar industry, with micro-grid and small utility-scale projects set to follow. While the local supply chain is incomplete and policy instruments to support projects are currently lacking, there is growing interest in the West African market. Foreign players, including Lebanese, Chinese, and Ghanaian firms, are seeing Sierra Leone as an up and coming opportunity.

The absence of reliable electricity supply is in general a major concern for Somalia and a significant barrier to doing business. Even those consumers that do have a grid connection are not satisfied with the quality of the power they receive. If generation capacity and transmission and distribution infrastructure improve, power demand could grow significantly. As the grid in Somalia is already very decentralized, off-grid and mini-grid development offer potential for electrification even in the most remote areas. Somalia's rich solar resources make PV mini-grid systems an attractive option, and one of the longest coastlines in Africa also offers good resource potential for wind.

The main opportunity for off- or mini-grid projects in South Africa is in rural areas where electrification was at 66% in 2017, compared with 93% in urban areas. The Integrated National Electrification Plan includes initiatives to boost electricity access in rural areas; aims to fund an estimated 723,000 grid and 49,650 non-grid connections to households by 2019/20. Electricity consumption in South Africa has stagnated in recent years, declining 0.5% a year on average since 2006. The reduction has been most felt by heavy power users due to factors including economic slowdown, volatility in commodity markets and rising electricity costs. This trend has been reflected in peak demand, which decreased by a compound annual growth rate of 0.44%.

Power demand in the country is growing, but the rate of growth is limited by a lack of transmission infrastructure. The power grid is currently confined to the three largest cities, Juba, Wau and Malakal. Those living in rural areas therefore have to make do with no electricity or must rely on diesel generators. A Chinese company has recently built an electricity pole manufacturing plant in Juba. The government hopes that this will enable electricity to reach 20% of the capitals population by 2020, up from 5% today.

While optimism abounded following the removal of U.S. sanctions in October 2017, inflation has since surged, widening the chasm between production costs and already rock-bottom power prices. Economic hardship will persist in the wake of a sharp currency devaluation on October 7, 2018. Yet Sudans geography is well suited to renewables. The countrys assets include high solar irradiation and strong winds. Future energy demand will be met by ongoing electrification initiatives  population growth outstrips the 100,000-odd new customers connected to the grid each year by a considerable margin. Moreover, the states balance sheets are ravaged by its reliance on diesel, the scarcity of which has boosted both the cost of thermal power production and the attractiveness of renewables.

Tanzanias power demand has grown relatively slowly over the past several years. Peak power demand increased by only 1% in 2016/17, reaching 1,051MW. This is well below 1,450MW, the base-case power demand scenario, in the governments Power Systems Master Plan 2016. The country has a binding target of electrifying all the public facilities such as schools, hospitals and churches by 2021 (100% village electrification), which may bring opportunities for on-site solar or mini-grids in off-grid areas. As of February 2018, some 36% of Tanzanias 12,248 villages had access to electricity, according to the Rural Energy Agency.

Togo has an electrification rate of just 11% in rural areas. The country has developed a roadmap for electrification to reach 100% of the population by 2030. The program combines the distribution of 550,000 solar kits, notably with partners such as BBOXX, developing 315 micro-grids, and extending the distribution grid to remote areas. Togos power demand has grown from 130MW to 193MW from 2010 to 2017. The country has not accompanied this growth with increased capacity yet, relying on imports from regional neighbors. The development of renewables will allow the country to match demand.

The country is slowly recovering from an economic crisis and reached 2% GDP growth in 2017, against 1.1% in 2016. The economy is forecasted to further expand with 2.5% GDP growth in 2018. After a 6% drop from 2015 to 2016, Tunisias peak power demand is recovering and recorded a spike of 18% year-on-year to 4,025MW in 2017. This represented the greatest increase since at least 2011. It is one of few countries in Africa with nearly 100% electrification rates.

Due to an excess of power plants connected to the grid, the generation market in Uganda is in a holding pattern. On-grid, most investment opportunity lies in strengthening and expanding the transmission and distribution network. A number of development banks, including the World Bank and KfW, have already contributed to ongoing projects in these areas, but more support is required if the country is to meet a universal electricity access target by 2035. Rural electricity is just as essential, and Uganda has a thriving off-grid solar market, with dozens of companies using pay-as-you-go and mobile money models to great success. The maturity of this segment of the market is demonstrated by the flow of investment from financial institutions.

Zambias electrification rate is 67% in urban areas and 4% in rural areas, giving the country an overall national electrification of approximately 31%. The governments plan of universal access by 2030 is likely to mean favourable policies will be introduced for mini-grids or off-grid solar, evident from the successful launch of the small-scale solar tender program currently under way. Demand for electricity has been rising due to robust GDP growth of more than 6% per year for the past decade, particularly in the mining, manufacturing and agriculture sectors. According to the Zambia Development Agency (ZDA), the demand for electricity in the country has been growing at an average of about 3%, or between 150 and 200 MW, each year. Despite the drop in copper prices in 2016, international agencies have given Zambia's mining sector a positive outlook as copper production nearly doubled in light of the introduction of Zambias first coal-fired power plant, Maamba power plant, in July 2016. This will further add to the increasing demand for power. Most Zambian power plants are hydro stations that do not require short-term upgrades.

The country imports expensive power from Mozambique and South Africa in order to meet demand. Despite the supply deficit, Zimbabwe also has contractual obligation to export 150MW to Namibia. Both the generation (besides Kariba) and transmission infrastructure is outdated and requires significant investment in order to restore potential capacity. Zimbabwe has extensive coal resources but also great renewables potential, both hydro and solar. The country experiences frequent load shedding. Electrification rate in rural areas is 16% with the bulk of communities relying on wood fuel for cooking and kerosene for lighting.

Power demand for Afghanistan is largely met by imports  neighboring countries account for some 80% of the countrys power needs. Power demand is expected to rise in the future, but imports are not considered a reliable source to meet these needs, mainly because of political instability in the region. Policies have been set in place to harness the countrys potential to exploit its own hydroelectric, solar and wind resources. There has been progress in increasing the electrification rate within the country  rural electrification now stands at 78%, and urban electrification is at 98%.

Armenias peak demand has been falling slightly from a high of 1.5GWp in 2013. The countrys economy has been relatively stable throughout the period, but there has been an increase in energy efficiency efforts and regulation. In a country whose main industry is construction, these regulations could have a marked effect on power demand. The country is 100% electrified, with little need for off-grid capacity. Resources for solar and wind are good, though transmission constraints have prevented much investment in wind. There are plans to modernize the hydropower fleet in order to extend the lifetimes of the plants.

One barrier to meeting demand is the inefficiency of the countrys grid and a dependence on regional cooperation regarding the Central Asian power grid.Electrification in the country is near 100% and it has already undergone a power fleet modernization.There is no framework for off-grid or rooftop solar, however, the Ministry of Energy has identified off-grid as a strategic sector.

Bangladesh is an electricity deficit country where several large customers experience regular load shedding. The country will consume more electricity as the population increases and GDP rises. Several industries that had been receiving subsidized gas to generate their own power may start buying electricity from the grid in future as domestic gas supplies decrease and the country relies on often expensive imported gas. Most of the rural population in Bangladesh has access to electricity through the use of solar home systems. Further increases in power requirements will be met through a combination of grid extensions and minigrid projects

The governments aggressive electrification program has raised the share of households with access to electricity from only 22% in 2010 to a reported 70% in 2017, boosting demand for power threefold. Electricity quality remains an issue in remote areas, but opportunities for off-grid companies are thin: the government is not transparent about grid extension plans, and off-grid systems are unable to feed into the grid once it arrives, effectively stranding these assets. Many companies formerly specializing in solar home systems have shifted focus to work on commercial and industrial sites, where there is more opportunity.

In 1H 2018, Chinas gross power demand grew by 9.4%, reaching 3,229TWh. This is the fastest growth since 2011, on the back of strong recovery in heavy industry demand and a record surge in power consumption by households and public institutions. Switching from fossil fuels to renewables, and electrification of transport, cooking, heating, industrial processes, etc. are long-term policy goals that will continue to present opportunities for investment. BNEF forecasts a slowing of Chinas power demand growth in 2H 2018, with full-year rise of 8%. We expect a further slowdown in 2019 and 2020, due to downward pressure from the U.S.-China trade war on manufacturing, iron and steel, aluminum, etc. Even with the slowdown, national power demand in 2020 will reach 7,715TWh, 7% higher than the upper target set by Chinas 13th Five-Year Plan.

Indias total electricity demand is expected to increase by 76% between 2017 and 2027 as per the Central Electricity Authority. Peak demand is forecast to grow 85% in the same period. India's economy achieved 7.1% real annual growth in 2017. High inflation has caused a rise in benchmark lending rates. Furthermore, recent currency depreciation has increased pressure on domestic solar developers that import equipment from China. The government achieved 100% village electrification in April 2018, though around 25 million households remain un-electrified. BNEF expects this village electrification scheme to increase Indias annual electricity demand by approximately 2% from the current level in the short term.

Power demand in Indonesia is not increasing as expected by the countrys policy planners. Economic growth rates were high during 2010-12, and electricity demand increased at an annual rate of 8-9%. Demand growth has slowed since 2014 to only 4-5% per year due to lower-than-expected GDP growth. This has forced the government to cut its power capacity expansion plans. The electrification rate has increased to 92% in 2017 from only 64% in 2010 There is a huge potential to develop clean energy microgrids in Indonesia as the country has more than a gigawatt of diesel power generators providing electricity in the remote regions. Replacing diesel power with a combination of solar, battery storage and diesel could decrease generation costs as well as emissions.

Kazakhstan could supply wind power of 1.8TWh and solar of 3.76TWh annually. Power demand has increased in recent years, at an approximate annual rate of 3.4%. It was slightly faster, growing at around 4% and reaching over 16,500MW in 2017, because the country placed more resources on the development of its new capital city for the EXPO2017. Kazakhstan is also the largest power market in Central Asia. There is potential for off-grid development (such as solar) in remote areas of the country, although access to power is no longer a significant challenge to Kazakhstanis. More importantly, as the Soviet-era coal-fired power fleet is getting older (mostly aged over 40 years) and in desperate need of refurbishment, Kazakh renewables could be in a position to replace some of the existing capacity.

Its electrification rate is near 100%, but Kyrgyzstan suffers from power supply reliability issues due to its dependence on large hydropower plants, most of which are operating beyond their intended lifespan. While peak power demand has remained flat in recent years, the country needs to install additional power capacity and invest in existing plants in order to address these reliability concerns and enable economic growth. Kyrgyzstan has seen GDP of around 4% for the past five years. It is likely this figure would be higher if power outages were less frequent.

Power demand has surged as Laos has extended its electric grid into the reaches of its countryside, with peak load nearly doubling since 2010 and overall generation (much of which is exported) tripling over the same time frame. Laos aims to reach 98% of household electrification by 2020; it is well on its way, according to official statistics, with 94% electrification in 2017, compared to only 15% in 1995. Concerns remain, however, on the quality of the power supply to rural areas, and many speculate that the true electrification rate remains around 70-80%. Off-grid systems are an option for the remaining households that the grid hasnt yet reached, but the remoteness of these homes means that income-generating opportunities  and therefore, the ability to pay for solar home systems  remain limited. Most solar home systems to date have effectively been given as grants.

Malaysia's power demand has grown around 19% over the past five years, with an electrification rate of nearly 100%. There is room for enhancing rural electrification though, especially in the Bornean states of Sabah and Sarawak  one of the main goals of the Sarawak Corridor of Renewable Energy (SCORE) initiative. Being the third-largest PV cell producer in the world, Malaysia has homegrown expertise across the entire value chain, making it an environment conducive for solar players to operate. The largest potential lies with rooftop solar, but until a new mechanism to replace the existing net-metering program can be introduced, this is unlikely to take off. The government fully supports increasing investments in renewable energy as it helps to spur economic growth and employment.

Power demand has slowly increased in recent years but remains low  a trend expected to continue in the coming decade. This is because GDP growth in Mongolia peaked at 17% in 2011 and kept rising at a slower rate since then  it was as low as 1.2% in 2016, then rebounded to 5.9% in 2017. In addition, national electrification is 98%, though access to power is an issue in some rural areas. The country has good land supply and weather conditions to develop wind and solar, while mini- and off-grid systems operate well in remote areas. Last but not least, it needs to modernize its coal-power fleet as it was built at least 30 years ago.

The Myanmar Companies Law, which came into effect in August 2018, is expected to attract an influx of foreign investment as it not only loosens foreign investment restrictions, but also sets up a one-stop online company registration platform to simplify the business registration process. Now the share of foreign holding is lifted to 65% maximum, so foreign capital can gain majority rights in a local company and own land for power project development. The Union Tax Law has exempted solar panels, charge controllers and inverters from commercial tax since 2016. The Myanmar Investment Law offers an import duty exemption to project developers that need to import their equipment, including solar modules and wind and gas turbines. In addition, corporate income tax breaks are set in different economic zones. There are three categories, developed, less developed and least developed in terms of their economy, that offer three, five and seven years of zero corporate income tax.

Power demand is growing at about 8% per year, and is expected to exceed 17,400GWh by 2027. The increased demand is largely to be met by additional hydropower resources. Only 1.7% of the total estimated 42GW of hydro resources is tapped. The current growth in hydropower implies the countrys targets will probably not be met. The electrification rate currently stands at 85%, after huge jumps made both for rural and urban areas from 2010. The target is to achieve 100% electrification by 2030.

A spate of new power plants commissioned in the last few years means that the gap between demand and supply has narrowed, and planners are getting ready for an era of surplus electricity. This is despite the fact that about a fourth of the population does not have access to electricity. A surplus of about 900MW at peak time was expected in the year ended June 30, 2018, according to the regulator (Nepra).  This would increase to almost 14GW by 2025. This puts brakes on the expansion of renewables, even though they present the most cost-competitive option to generate power.

Over the past two decades, the Philippines went through significant energy reform, including opening the power industry to the private sector. However, the relationship between developer and regulators has been strained, with developers complaining about red tape and bureaucracy. While the government has created policies that allow more private participation, the failure to meet installation targets suggests a lack of follow-through. Unpermitted rooftop solar is widespread. One of the largest solar vendors widely advertises a solar/diesel/storage microgrid that is often deployed without the required permits. While policy implementation lags, both population and economic growth are expected to increase demand greatly and open more opportunity for power development.

Singapore is a developed economy with strong legal and institutional frameworks in place to support business transactions and financing arrangements. The country has world class infrastructure and office space, and a highly educated English speaking workforce. The government is also keen to attract foreign investment and developers into the market and is likely to attract more foreign players for subsequent tender rounds for SolarNova and floating PV projects.

Rooftop solar is a bright spark in renewable energy in Sri Lanka. The availability of a net metering scheme coupled with high tariffs means that more and more rooftops are aiming for solar installations. The latest government budget (unveiled in November 2017) also offers subsidized loans (at 8%) for the installation of solar panels by households and entrepreneurs. The import of equipment for renewable energy is exempt from the national building tax and as well as the ports and airport levy.

Taiwans power demand is only expected to grow modestly at 1.6% in the next two decades, according to Taiwan Research Institute. Yet the governments intention to take all of the 5.1GW nuclear power capacity offline by 2025 creates opportunities for renewable energy. The island has been receptive to foreign players, granting three-quarters of the 3.8GW offshore wind capacity announced in April 2018 to overseas developers. The government is also working with global supply chain companies to establish a local offshore wind manufacturing hub. Overseas banks have also actively participated in project financing.

Despite its near 100% electrification rate, Tajikistan suffers from power reliability issues due to its dependence on large hydropower plants (most of which are operating beyond their intended operating life). Still, these same large hydro plants also provide the country with an oversupply of power in summer months, so Tajikistan is an active participant in the CASA 1000 project, a new transmission line that aims to better connect the country with Kyrgyzstan, Pakistan and Afghanistan. Tajikistan has experienced high GDP growth for the past five years, and peak power demand has increased moderately.

Thailand has achieved 100% electrification. In the 2015 PDP, total electricity demand is forecasted to increase at an average growth rate of 2.68% in the period 2014-36. Year-on-year percentage growth is expected to decrease. Average growth is estimated to be 3.43% over the period 2017-21 but drops to 2.66% for 2022-26. This is partly due to an expected increase in energy efficiency. To boost the development of the renewable energy industry, Thailand's Board of Investment has exempted such projects from import tariffs. The investment climate in Thailand is stable. There are no known defaults by the single offtaker, EGAT. The grid in Thailand is also relatively robust, with a few instances of supply interruptions and no known curtailment. There are no barriers to entry in the form of foreign ownership restrictions or local content requirements.

Power demand is expected to increase along with exports of electricity to neighboring countries. Domestic demand is also expected to increase slightly as the industrial sector grows. Despite nearly 100% electrification, this will put a strain on the grid, which is plagued by blackouts and instability.The existing power fleet is a legacy of Soviet times but there are plans to modernize it. Investment in the sector could significantly increase the efficiency of the system.

Uzbekistan's power demand is increasing due to a stronger economy and a move toward diversification away from a single resource-based economy. The country is planning to increase capacity for both domestic demand and boost exports to neighboringcountries. Uzbekistan hopes to benefit from a more robust unified Central Asian grid, but in the meantime it has moved forward with bilateral agreements with countries such as Afghanistan and Tajikistan.

Peak power demand has been growing at an average of 11% annually since the start of the decade. This rapid growth has resulted in a threefold increase in electricity generation from coal in the same period. Vietnam plans to increase coal capacity threefold again from 17GW in 2017 to 55GW by 2030. The country has an electrification rate of 99.2% with the urban population fully electrified. Most of the solar and wind potential areas lie in the low power demand regions in the country.

Albania has already reached 100% electrification but the power system can be unreliable. In periods of low water reserves, the system relies on the distribution system operator, OSHEE, to tender for energy imports to cover the shortfall and meet its customers' demands (OSHEE supplies the regulated tariff customers). In 2017, the system was tight because levels were so low that in order to afford the energy imports, state-owned utility KESH had to make an emergency draw-down on a loan provided by the World Bank for reforming the electricity sector. As a result, the government is looking to diversify its electricity mix through adding solar and wind. It has also outlined a plan to incentivize net-metering for systems up to 500kW, covering households and small- to medium-sized commercial enterprises.

The World Bank estimates that BiHs energy sector is in need of an additional $6 billion for the modernization of its power sector and construction of new generation facilities. Over half of the countrys thermal capacity was commissioned in the 1960s and 1970s  the list of thermal power plants to be closed encompasses 30% of the countrys total thermal capacity. Demand has grown strongly since the turn of the millennium, and power generation increased by 50% between 2001 and 2013. As exports more than quadrupled between 2001 and 2010, distribution losses halved in the 2007-10 period. Although BiH is currently a net electricity exporter, this could change if no significant generation facilities are brought into service over the next decade.

Power demand in Georgia has been rising for the past eight years, but is now levelling out. The majority of the growth comes from the rural population in the disputed northern region. There are plans to upgrade the grid and add new high-voltage lines in order to accommodate new renewable energy. Ageing hydropower plants are being refurbished to extend their lifetimes. The country is completely electrified, with little interest in off-grid developments.

Macedonia fully electrified its population in 2016. The modernization of the domestic power fleet is under way, with 2015 seeing ELEM launch the third phase of a program looking into restoring one of the countrys main thermal power plants. The government is also exploring converting the mothballed heavy oil-fired TEC Negotino power plant to natural gas. Demand is, however, decreasing  peak usage has dropped by approximately 12% since 2010. This trend has been matched by a reduction in domestic electricity production by a quarter over the last decade. Meanwhile imports, mostly in the form of Russian gas funneled in through Bulgaria, have risen to 34% of consumption.

Russia has long had a 100% electrification rate. Due to some improvements in energy efficiency and stagnant economic growth, the countrys peak power demand has remained relatively flat for the past seven years, fluctuating between 150GW and 155GW. State-controlled companies dominate most of the power sector. EU and U.S. sanctions have prevented most Western companies from operating in the country, though some have recently set up joint ventures with state-run players to enter Russias nascent renewables market. Issues such as currency volatility and government corruption remain serious barriers to doing business in Russia.

Serbia has a consumption target of 36.6% renewable energy in the electricity sector by 2020. As of 2017, it reached roughly 27% thanks to hydro commanding a 37% share of installed capacity (plus some small generation from demonstration wind and solar projects). But with 500MW of wind capacity due online by 2020, it is expected to close the gap. To meet the EU's accession requirements, specifically, adhering to the 'Large Combustion Plants Directive', at least eight coal power plants need to be shut down by 2024. The generation gap is to be replaced by two new coal power plants, a combined heat and power plant, and at least 500MW of wind capacity. Since 2010, peak power demand has been flat.

Turkey continues adding capacity across all technologies, assuming long-term economic growth and increasing power demand, though these assumptions are likely much more optimistic than realistic. The government's prioritization of lignite and emphasis on domestic resources means it is focusing on adding capacity based on energy independence and security of supply rather than just the economics of different technologies. To take advantage of domestic resources, Turkey plans to refit existing coal assets to run off lower-quality domestic lignite rather than imported hard coal  this will help keep costs down and reduce reliance on imported fuel.

Power demand in Ukraine, as for many of the former Soviet states, plunged after the collapse of the Soviet Union  and has not returned to prior levels. Industrial demand has not recovered, which has allowed for the current generation assets to serve the national market. The governments drive to improve efficiency in housing and public buildings is expected to help limit increases in demand while renewables are developed. The aim is to lower Ukraines dependency on Russian gas for its power and heating needs. Electrification is 100%, as in most neighboring countries. The south of Ukraine has good solar resources, which has drawn investors to regions such as Odessa. Wind resources are also good  foreign equipment manufacturers have reportedly been mapping the wind resources to strengthen their case for selling to developers. Many of the coal and nuclear fleet need investment to modernize or extend their lifespan  as does the distribution and transmission system.

Argentinas clean energy investment is likely to be affected by the recent macroeconomic crisis, especially the financing of projects from RenovAr 2.0, which awarded contracts to 1.8GW of wind and solar assets. Additionally, the Ministry of Energy decreased the amount of capacity to be tendered considerably in 2018. RenovAr MiniRen 3.0 will tender around 400MW, contrasting with the 1GW initially expected and will focus on small projects limited to 10MW of capacity.

Business opportunities for renewable energy in Bolivia may be improving, underpinned by an outlook of sharply rising electricity demand growth, which has averaged over 5% since 2010. The countrys plans for aggressive expansion of hydroelectric and other renewables sources with the overall goal of increasing energy exports could create new opportunities for investment. Early steps in introducing wind and solar onto the grid in recent years may pave the way for a greater role for these sources in official planning and targets. At 93%, Bolivia has a low electrification rate by regional standards and the government has a target of universal access by 2025, to be achieved via the its Electricidad para Vivir con Dignidad (Electricity for Life with Dignity) program, which focuses on extending the grid and installing PV, wind, and hybrid systems in low-income municipalities.

After three years of economic crisis, Brazils GDP grew 1% in 2017, with the annual inflation rate declining from 8.77% in 2016 to 3.46% in 2017. The country continues to struggle to recover from its worst recession on record, navigating a tumultuous first half of 2018 marked by rising unemployment, a 10-day truckers strike that paralyzed the economy, and a polarized presidential election. As a result of the economic crisis, peak demand remained almost flat between 2014 and 2017, at 85.7GW.

Chile is the worlds largest copper exporter, and the energy-intensive nature of that industry creates substantial power demand. In 2016, the copper industry alone accounted for 8% of Chiles total GDP and 51% of exports. In a given year, the mining industry consumes an average of 30% of the total power generated in the country. Mining operations are located in the northern part of the country and mostly served by the SING system. The majority of coal assets are also located in this region, in addition to the greatest potential for solar generation in the country. However, the lack of interconnection between SIC and SING has historically driven the majority of solar developments to the SIC system, where over 90% of the population lives and most of the retail demand is located. This reality might change, however, as the government increasingly focuses on integration of the two sub-systems and on building connections with neighboring countries.

The business environment for renewable energy in Colombia is mixed. While the country has seen average electricity demand growth of 2.5% annually since 2010 and has a well-established regulatory framework governing its electricity sector, policies introduced to date have done little to accelerate development of non-hydro renewables. The government introduced tax incentives for investments in renewables in Law 1715, effective in 2014, which provides for accelerated depreciation of up to 20% per year for renewable energy investments, income tax deduction of 50% of investment value for up to 50% of taxable income for up to 5 years, VAT exemption for renewable energy equipment and services, and import duty exemption for renewable energy equipment not produced locally. However, as it took almost two years from enactment for the law to come into force, benefits to the market have been limited. The off-grid space, or zonas no interconectadas (ZNI), is characterized by a large amount of players, but faces implementation challenges in rural areas.

Costa Ricas government shows strong commitment to energy and climate-related incentives. However, high hydro penetration and slow demand growth limits new entrants in the market. Around 77% of the countrys power generation is supplied by hydro, reducing the need for other clean energy sources for the country to meet its goals. Generation only grew 11% between 2010 and 2017 while peak demand rose by less than 1% over the period.

In 2017, Dominican Republics electrification rate was 96%. Peak power demand jumped 87% over the past eight years, from 1,810MW in 2010 to 3,397MW in 2017, while generation grew 23% over the same period. The Dominican Republics official planning document estimates demand growth of 3-4% per year through 2030. With 18% of total electricity provided by renewable energy plants (including large hydro) in 2017, the country remains under its target of 25% of clean energy generation by 2020, though momentum appears to be in the right direction. A 58MW PV plant was commissioned in 2018 and another 183MW of wind and PV plants were financed over the course of the year.

On October 13, 2015, the Government of Ecuador submitted its unconditional Intended Nationally Determined Contribution (INDC) to the United Nations, committing to cut greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in the energy sector by 20.4%-25% below the business as usual (BAU) scenario by 2025. Ecuador also committed to a further reduction of GHG emissions in the energy sector to a level between 37.5% and 45.8% below the BAU scenario by 2025. This additional reduction is conditioned upon availability of resources and international support.

The business environment for renewable energy is positive in El Salvador. Total generation and peak demand have increased significantly every year between 2012 and 2017, growing by 11% and 26% respectively, over the period. The National Energy Council (CNE) estimates annual demand growth of 2.2% per year through 2035. In the first half of 2018, the country commissioned 30MW of PV capacity as part of the Bosforo Project, a joint-venture between AES and Central American conglomerate Corporacin Multi Inversiones (CMI) that is expected to commission a total of 100MW of solar capacity over the next two years.

Guatemalas national energy plan established a target that 64% of its energy should come from renewable sources by 2032. According to the National Electricity Commission (CNEE), as of August 2018, 38% of the country's energy comes from renewables, suggesting that additional investment should be made in the coming years. Guatemala's level of electrification was 92% in 2016.

The deficit between available capacity and demand has created opportunities for distributed clean energy. Financed by a USAID grant, Haitis first micro-grid started operation in the south of the country in 2015, providing solar power to around 450 households in the city of Les Anglais. The system relies on batteries and smart meters for system stability and to facilitate pre-pay capability for customers. Yet Haiti is prone to natural disasters, rendering generation assets vulnerable. The aforementioned micro-grid was partially destroyed after hurricane Matthew in late 2016. 20% of PV panels and all the cabling and polls were destroyed. EarthSpark plans to develop 80 other micro-grid projects.

The business environment for renewable energy in Honduras is high risk. Empresa Nacional de Energia Elctrica (ENEE) has failed to pay the feed-in premium promised to solar plants commissioned by July 31, 2015. According to the ENEE, energy demand is growing and is expected to increase around 4% per year through 2030. Total solar and wind capacity grew by 16% between 2016 and 2017. The national electrification rate in 2018 stood at 95%.

According to the Ministry of Science, Energy and Technology (MSET), the national electrification rate in 2015 was 97%. Jamaicas peak demand has remained somewhat stable over the past eight years. It has inched up only 4% over the period, from 638MW in 2010 to 667MW in 2017, which represents an average growth rate of just 0.5% per year.

Business opportunities for renewable energy in Mexico have improved significantly, underpinned by an outlook of rising electricity demand, which has averaged annual growth of over 3% since 2010. Mexicos three auctions held over 2016-17 have spurred investor interest in the countrys excellent wind and solar resources. Mexico has led Latin America in new clean energy investment since 2017, attracting nearly $2 billion in the first half of 2018, of which 70% of was directed towards solar. Large projects that secured contracts in the countrys first auction, held in March 2016, began to come online in 2018. In June 2018, Mexico announced the end of the 15% customs duty on solar PV module imports, introduced in 2015, removing a significant barrier to renewables development. Mexico is a potential market for distributed generation, with residential PV installation accelerating rapidly in recent years, reaching 434MW cumulatively at year-end 2017, the largest in Latin America. Retail electricity consumers in Mexico who have renewable energy or co-generation facilities can connect to the national grid, deliver surplus generation to it, and obtain billing credit for excess electricity provided.

Nicaraguas peak power demand jumped 26% over 2010-17 to 680MW, rising 6% on average over the first two years of the period. However, growth then decelerated mainly due to an economy slowdown, reaching just 1% per year in 2015-17. Still, the governments National Expansion Plan 2017-2030 expects demand to grow 4.5% per year between 2017 and 2030.

The business environment for renewable energy is positive in Panama. Although hydro still represents a larger source, solar and wind energy began increasing in 2014. Regulations mandate a 5% premium on the price paid for electricity generated from renewable sources, which includes biomass, geothermal, small hydro (up to 3MW), solar and wind.
Paraguays electrification rate in 2017 was 99%. The countrys peak demand jumped 66% over the past eight years, from 1,892MW in 2010 to 3,135MW in 2017.

Ministerio de Energa y Minas (MINEM) is the responsible for evaluating the need for auctions, and Organismo Supervisor de la Inversin en Energa y Minera (OSINERGMIN), the power sector regulator, conducts the tenders. A fifth renewable auction, expected to be held in 2018, was canceled in April 2017 and no new tender has been announced since then. MINEMs explanation for the cancellation is that not all projects selected in the previous auction are being developed. In 10 years, Peru saw its electrification rate spike from 74% to 96%, the biggest increase in Latin American countries. The progress is due to a governmental rural electrification program, which included an off-grid auction aiming to contract PV systems for isolated regions in the country.

Renewable markets in Uruguay have slowed down significantly since 2015, mostly because consumption has stabilized. Peak demand varies between 1,800 to 1,900 MW since 2013, while total capacity installed is at 4,500 MW.

Economic growth helped Egypt increase power demand by a compound annual growth rate of 4% over 2010-16. However, 2017 saw a more modest rise of less than 1%, as economic activity slowed down, in particular in industry, and inflation more than doubled. In the longer term, Egypt is expected to see a significant increase in power demand over the next few decades fueled by economic growth. The government is intending to meet the expansion in electricity demand through a mix of fuels, with plans for further coal power tenders and an agreement with Russia's Rosatom to build four 1.2GW nuclear reactors.

International industrials such as General Electric, Siemans and ABB are working with the Iraqi government to repair and upgrade power plants in an attempt to sustain current plant production and rehabilitate capacity damaged during years of conflict. The government also aims to strengthen the grid and reconnect areas in the north and west with the rest of the country. Despite these attempts, Iraqs demand exceeds peak load by almost 50% in hot periods, when air conditioning units consume the most power. With demand growing in excess of 7% each year, further capacity will be necessary to avoid continued shortages.

Despite demand for power slowing in 2016 and 2017 due to a slowdown in the economy, the outlook for power demand in Jordan remains strong. The government expect high population growth combined with an expanding commercial and industrial sector to boost power demand to over 5.8GW by 2025, from 3.3GW in 2017. The majority of Jordanians live in the north of the country surrounding the capital Amman, and 99.9% of the population have access to power.

Electricity consumption is growing at approximately 8% a year, which means capacity needs to double every decade to meet demand. This is the result of several factors, namely wasteful resource consumption on the back of heavily subsidized energy prices, population growth, and a nascent petrochemical industry. By 2017, renewables accounted for a negligible 1% of capacity, but Kuwaits abundant solar and wind resources offer the potential for a quick ramp-up. Kuwaits solar global horizontal irradiance is at 1,900kWh/m2/year, according to Irena, while the potential for wind stands at as much as 1,605 hours/year. Although no explicit fleet modernization program has been announced, Kuwait is building capacity in response to the forecast growth in electricity demand.

Lebanons power demand is difficult to estimate as much as much of it is unmet or provided by the fleet of black-market diesel generators. In recent years, an estimated 490MW of additional demand has come from the 1.5 million Syrian refugees present in the country. Forecast demand growth is modest, however, significant investment is required before current demand can be met. Lebanon enjoys high electrification rates and has few off-grid developments, although this sector represents opportunities to reduce dependence on the chronically unreliable grid. In terms of natural resource, Lebanon has abundant solar potential and previous studies have suggested wind potential between 1.5GW to 6GW of capacity.

The countrys power fleet is well maintained and its rural regions electrified. Peak demand is expected to increase at around 9% per year in line with the economys robust growth, with consumption increasing for both residential and industrial users. Moreover, net metering is being explored through a pilot scheme, which could encourage further growth in rooftop solar installations alongside a better management of residential electricity use, which currently makes up 46% of demand. The Authority for Electricity Regulation (AER) has identified solar as an area of particular potential, and renewables have been given the green light by Sultan Qaboos with the creation of the regions only dedicated Ministry for Environment and Climate Affairs.

Electricity demand has grown at a very rapid clip in Saudi Arabia over the past few decades. Capacity totaled just over 87GW in 2016 and has risen 7.6-9% annually since 2000. This skyrocketing demand, driven by an expanding economy, a growing population and the need for greater volumes of desalinated water, has driven the countrys interest in power generation diversity and transitioning away from using oil in power generation. All of this has prompted efforts to promote the construction of new solar-powered plants and nuclear generation. Saudi Aramco has apparently spent the last three years mapping out solar and wind energy resources, which are reportedly robust.

Peak demand has gone up significantly over the last few years, with an increase of nearly 5,000MW over the last half-decade. This trend is set to continue with the U.A.E.s continuing economic and population growth. With high irradiation rates, the country has considerable solar potential. Frequent power cuts in the poorer emirates are a thing of the past, and the population is geographically concentrated and connected to the grid  85% of Emiratis live in the emirates of Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Sharjah. Existing thermal plants are well-maintained and the countrys business environment is generally favorable, with a high degree of clarity regarding the rules and procedures underpinning energy projects.

Power demand is growing in Palestine and this trend will likely continue, although economic growth is limited, especially in the Gaza Strip. The population is expanding more quickly than in Israel, making the Palestinian market an important destination for Israeli power generation. The unreliability of power supply in the Gaza Strip, where most consumers rely on diesel generators, offers opportunities  still, doing business is difficult as imports and entry are controlled by Israel. In the West Bank, the potential for PV uptake is significant but in practice limited as the most promising area for development is under the control of the Israeli military.

The main challenges for developers are local content requirements and restrictions on the use of foreign financing sources which are not compensated by domestic alternatives. The government has also refused to offer developers a sovereign guarantee which creates concern for financiers as there are expectations that the offtaker, Sonelgaz, will be restructured in the near future. Some project developers for commercial and industrial users have, however, started to secure funding for their activities domestic commercial banks.

The 2015 Electricity Law established the legal framework for independent power producers (IPPs), and the government is working with the African Development Bank to implement the legislation including PPAs and feed-in tariffs. In the meantime, IPPs are still rare in Angola and PPAs are negotiated on a case-by-case basis. The sector has also been suffering from a number of inefficiencies: non-payment from customers is a challenge, with over 80% not metered. In addition, the cost of electricity production and distribution is high; the average consumer tariff is low; and technical and commercial losses are sizeable (around 50%).

The small size of the Benin energy sector is a limit in itself. Since there have been no large-scale projects to date, the energy value chain is limited. The lack of regulation or previous projects means that the process for project development and bureaucracy are unclear.  Though slow policy development is a hurdle to project development, Benin has no particular political risks, currency volatility or offtaker risk.

Botswana, much like other Sub-Saharan countries, has an import duty exemption on all equipment and machinery, a category that includes solar panels, inverters and other parts. The countrys so-called manufacturing investment incentive is a broad policy that was brought in to bolster the manufacturing sector. The incentives makes no special provision for the renewables industry, however, they present an opportunity to develop a manufacturing industry, if the local market becomes more stable. There is offtaker risk as BPC has historically run at considerable loss and only made a profit once in the last 10 financial years.  In recent years, under the guidance of the newly appointed CEO, Stefan Schwarzfischer, BPC has managed to reduce its losses. Unlike its neighbors, Botswana has little currency risk  the pula has strengthened to the dollar by 33% over the last seven years.

With Burkina Faso being one of the poorest countries in the world, the state of the infrastructure is bad. The main grid is unreliable and congested, and blackouts are common. The country is politically relatively unstable, and in 2015 a military coup caused unrest across the country. Potential IPPs in the urban-based segment are obliged to sign a PPA with Sonabel, although the utility is heavily in debt and cannot pay for grid maintenance and fleet modernization. Alternatively, project developers that wish to set up a mini-grid have to deal with a fair amount of bureaucracy: a project larger than 10kW requires administrative approval and requires an authorization from the Ministry of Energy, if it services more than 10 clients.

The main barrier to private sector participation is that any large capital program will face a heightened risk of unforeseen events due to the deteriorating internal security in Burundi or unrest in neighboring countries. Until recently, no consistent and coordinated government energy efficiency programs had been launched since the end of Burundi's long-term conflict. As a result, energy efficiency is facing barriers at all levels due to low awareness for energy efficient products and appliances, and a lack of quality technical and service standards for energy efficient equipment. More generally in the electricity sector, there is insufficient management experience and a lack of access to investment finance to deliver new projects. There is also growing concern over the severe constraints in the electricity supply, involving frequent power outages. The supply deficit currently varies between about 15MW during the wet season and 25MW during the dry season, when the countrys main hydropower plants run at reduced capacity.

The main barrier to private-sector participation is the extent of Eneo's concession for generation, which limits those who can produce electricity in a given area. Another barrier is the inconsistent implementation of import duties for renewables, as Cameroon does not have an import tariff waiver. Equally, the governments prioritization of the development of hydro resources has impeded solar deployment, which has been seen as too expensive. Of the 792MW of solar in Cameroons project pipeline, just one megawatt-scale plant (Huaweis 20MW solar microgrid) has secured financing. Concerns over the impact of dry seasons on hydropower availability have, however, resulted in the government considering alternatives including some demand response in the capital, Douala.

CAR has no manufacturing capacity for clean energy, nor are there any local content requirements. There are no import duties, tariffs or exemptions for clean energy components or equipment. While the government is considering whether to implement such measures, this is not expected to happen in the near future. The risks are high for developers and asset owners in CAR due to the political unrest. The key barriers are the lack of stability in the market, the absence of major policies to incentivize clean energy growth and a lack of sufficient infrastructure to facilitate such growth.

Developers must account for haulage fees over the 2,000km separating Chad from Douala on the Cameroonian coast, where much of the countrys imports are unloaded. Equipment costs could, however, be worse: although the practice has yet to be codified into law, import and VAT have recently been waived for components used in renewables projects. Legislation is being drafted to streamline licensing regulations, but the issuing of permits remains a drawn-out process. Payment delays notwithstanding, the utility has consistently managed to meet its contractual obligations in purchasing power from VPower, the aforementioned IPP. Renewable energy deployment can be slowed in other ways  the frequent hiring and firing of ministers has held up the implementation of a national clean energy strategy.

Equipment required for renewable energy projects is taxable through both import tariffs and VAT, increasing capital costs. Offtaker risk is another issue. Socit Nationale dElectricit, the national utility, was dissolved in July 2018 before being replaced by Energie Electrique du Congo (EDC). Alongside uncertainty regarding the reasons behind the utilitys dismantling, the transition has been plagued by confusion concerning the newly created companys legal status and the transfer of assets from its defunct predecessor. Although talks with several candidates were under way, no bidder was found to take the reins through a management contract, leaving EDC to embark upon the long process of recapitalization and reform alone.

Offtaker risk for power projects in the DRC is very high as SNEL, the state-owned utility, is not solvent. SNEL owns 94% of total installed capacity so the prospects for wind and solar developers to build new projects in the country are not very good, as a result of the high offtaker risk, currency volatility and political uncertainty. The DRC does not yet have any meaningful renewable energy incentives in place. Given the lack of utility-scale energy projects built in recent years, there would also be a substantial amount of red tape faced by developers. The DRC has no manufacturing capacity of any scale for its hydro or other renewable energy projects, so local content requirements do not exist. Smaller-scale companies also face import duties on off-grid solar products, unless they are granted an exemption.

Cote dIvoire has little experience in renewables other than hydro, and policies that incentivize their development are minimal. The generation market  the only segment open to competition  is dominated by a few major players. General standards and procedures are lacking and transactions with the state are done on a project-by-project basis. Due to the utility's monopoly in electricity retail, the off-grid market is limited to self-consumption solar projects. Importing renewable components remains difficult despite some tax exemptions on solar products. Not all solar equipment is covered by exemptions, limiting the attractiveness of larger projects, and it can be cumbersome to secure the discount rates at customs, notably because of laborious administrative processes.

The lack of frameworks for private investment in Eritrea is a major barrier to renewables development. Importing not only renewables components but equipment in general is cumbersome, and there is very little transparency in general around the existing regulatory framework. Political risk is significant in the single-party country, where media freedom is severely restricted. Eritrea and Ethiopia reached a rapprochement, which could signal a move toward more open government, but the country has a long way to go before it might tempt investors.

One major barrier to renewables development in Ethiopia is financing difficulties. The country has a serious shortage of foreign currency reserves, which make raising financing difficult. There are also no sovereign guarantees on offtake payments. Offtaker risk has not yet been a problem in Ethiopia, but EEP is struggling financially and IPPs may be hesitant to enter into long-term contracts. Renewables components are exempt from import duties and VAT, in theory, but in practice getting items through customs can be cumbersome and slow.

Offtaker risk remains the biggest barrier to renewables deployment in Ghana. ECG the main offtaker had to be rescued early in 2018 due to its poor finances, which meant that PPAs it had signed were not sufficient to secure financing for projects, without a put-call option agreement (PCOA), or government consent and support agreement (GCSA) also being put in place. The government then undertook a further PPA review process in 2018, which will delay any new build until 2020 at the earliest. Further to this, in August 2018 the President sacked the minister for energy (Boakye Agyarko) due to proposals for a renegotiation of a $510 million private power deal. In addition to impeding power policy development and the electricity market reform process, this is likely to exacerbate uncertainty around the Ghanaian governments stance on renewables, at least in the short term.

Access to finance is consistently identified as the biggest issue holding back the implementation of renewable energy projects. Moreover, the absence of microgrid regulations or clean energy incentives also has much to do with the countrys reliance on large hydro, the abundance of which has long restrained the allure of renewable sources. A lack of experienced personnel throughout the project development supply chain further increases the upfront costs facing would-be developers. Prospective investors must also take import duties and VAT into account, which they could be saddled with despite the possibility of ad hoc exemptions.

Land access has been a challenge for both site selection and transmission connection. The Lake Turkana wind farm is expected to come online in 2018 after facing severe delays in the construction and transmission phases. Generally, administrative processes take a long time and developers often face reluctance by Kenya Power and ERC for the development of a new project. For small-scale renewable energy projects, the regulatory framework only requires a mini-grid permit for those with a generation capacity of 1-3MW and requires no permit or licence for those below 1MW projects. Regulations for on-site generation are light-handed.

There are a number of overlapping energy sector entities including Department of Energy, Lesotho Electricity Co., Lesotho Energy and Water Authority and Rural Electrification Unit. This set-up has resulted in confusion, an underdeveloped regulatory framework, a lack of equipment technical standards and ultimately slow implementation of projects. There is limited availability of suitable land for renewables development  the terrain is mountainous and access is difficult, and where land is accessible it is often already being used for agriculture or settlement. There is a lack of awareness across the board about renewable energy technology and its potential social and economic benefits.

The lack of clear policy enablers in combination with inaction from the state-owned utility present the most significant barriers to the prosperity of Liberias nascent clean energy industry. Perceived corruption within government is accentuated by long-term vacancies among senior positions in the Ministry of Energy and the utility regulatory commission. Meanwhile, the LEC has earned a reputation of being difficult to negotiate with and tediously slow to interconnect customers and generators. Moving past bureaucratic impediments, the nations distinct wet and dry seasons present challenges for planning and operating a system dependent on hydroelectric generation.

New tax legislation in Libya states that all renewable equipment and components are fully exempt from customs import duty, but within the country no tax privileges or priority are provided to clean energy projects. Given the negligible contribution of renewables to the generation mix, there is no risk of curtailment nor offtaker risk, since the market remains closed to private generators. Libya is engulfed in a complex conflict, so political risk, among others, is high.  Foreign sources of investment, whether from international organizations or the private sector, seem unlikely to tap into potential opportunities in the current setting.

Administrative process and land acquisition can be difficult and lengthy. Access to finance is generally complicated. The state of the grid will also causes stability issues for larger projects. This is why international technical assistance in the country has recommended that most PV developers include a battery in their project (as in the 2018 Scaling Solar tender) and finance their connection to the grid.

In Malawi there is an absence of stable and convincing renewables incentives, besides tax deductions and import duty exemptions on generation equipment. The country lacks experience with renewables project development and most recent talks seem to show the governments interest in coal power. There are no obvious PPA duration limitations on the PPA market. Clause 2.2 of the standard PPA does not specify the duration of the agreement, but instead leaves it to the seller and the off-taker to decide on an agreement. When it comes to interconnection, a ""grid code"" has been approved with rules on the process and standards for connecting to the grid. Malawi has signed a PPA with Zambia for 20MW, however it is yet to become active. There are currently no interconnections, but talks are ongoing with Zambia and Mozambique.

Mali has little experience in renewables other than hydro, and policies for incentives are lacking. The generation market is dominated by two players, including the utility, and there are few general standards and procedures for grid-scale projects. The country has a dynamic mini-grid market, although private players must be established locally before participating. There are also significant challenges over tariffs in rural areas, which are around three times higher than the tariff of the utility, which sells power at below cost. Local consumers struggle to understand this difference and developers sometimes face violent reactions. Furthermore, the rural electrification agency plays a central role in the off-grid market, distributing both grants and authorizations. This has eased administrative procedures and contributed to the success of the market, although the lack of transparency is sometimes criticized.

International agencies have observed that licensing and approval procedures are encumbered by rigid bureaucracy. Regulations can prove difficult to navigate, a situation compounded by a puzzling overlap between the remits of the various relevant public bodies. Similarly, international donors have highlighted a lack of transparency regarding forthcoming legislation, increasing uncertainty about reforms. Other issues include the lack of an effective electrification agency, slowing the implementation of a coherent regulatory framework that would encompass private and off-grid generation. Lastly, while import duties are waived for solar panels, upfront costs are driven up by their application to inverters and batteries.

Moroccos political stability and business-friendly legal frameworks have combined with its excellent solar and wind resources to fuel consistent speculation on its renewables ambitions. The local content requirement of the 850MW wind tender awarded in 2016 was met whilst also setting a world record low tariff. Completed in 2017, the Siemens-Gamesa blade factory in Morocco is the only facility of its kind in Africa. Located in the free-export zone of the port-city of Tangier, it is envisioned that this factory will enable further cost reductions for local projects in Morocco, whilst opening up export markets in Africa. Currently the law that provides the framework for renewables projects, law 13-09, only permits the sale of electricity over the medium- and high-voltage networks. In 2015, the publication of act 58-15 opened up the possibility of access to the low-voltage networks, seen as key to the growth of the small-scale PV sector. However, as of 2018, this act is not yet implemented and therefore any sale of electricity back to the grid by small enterprises or private individuals is not yet possible. This obstacle is intended to be removed in the short to medium term. Estimates of total wind resource potential for Morocco are as high as 25GW.

In addition to the lack of renewables incentives, developers face a difficult investment environment: the country came in 135th place on the World Banks ease of doing business index. There is currently no standardized PPA duration outlined for either utility-scale or off-grid projects. Moreover, offshore gas discoveries have rendered renewables less attractive. The lack of PPA standardization has meant that negotiations with EDM can be drawn out. The national utility is also in flux, with major structural and operational changes under way, in addition to being laden with debts. Private investors have complained that project development is often hindered by the state electricity companys internal politics.

While local ownership rules in Namibia are restrictive, there is no local content requirement for renewable energy developers, as Namibia does not have a manufacturing industry. Grid problems form a major barrier for renewable energy project development and are related to Nampowers monopoly in electricity transmission. Nampower has easy access to imports of baseload electricity from the Southern African Power Pool. It has been slow to adapt its operations to intermittent renewables, as no smart grid management is in place yet. If Nampower does not change its ways of working, it will hinder high renewables penetration. Moreover, the transmission grid is congested, which is a barrier for the development of larger-scale (30-80MW) renewable energy projects.

Security concerns present a considerable challenge and weaken the markets attractiveness to investors. Project costs increase dramatically outside of Niameys immediate vicinity. A lack of domestically based companies involved in the renewables sector must also be surmounted. The dearth of human resources extends to the public sector, with administrative capacity nearing breaking point as the relevant government bodies struggle to cope with a growing pipeline of projects. Moreover, the general business climate is far from clement, with Niger ranking 144th on the World Banks Ease of Doing Business survey. That said, donors report that such hurdles as licensing progress swiftly once a project is given the go-ahead by the authorities.

The import duty rate varies between 0% and 30% of the purchase value. PV modules without a bypass diode do not pay any 0% duty whilst those that have one pay a 5% charge plus 5% VAT. As the vast majority of modules come shipped with a bypass diodes that allows for a more stable generations, developers have complained that the duty exemption is redundant. Lithium-ion batteries, even if used for energy storage, are slapped with a 20% duty on import plus 5% VAT. The other major barrier is currency convertibility risks. Due to the restrictions on foreign currency by the CBN, international developers and lenders are worried about investing in the Nigerian power sector. Whether denominated in U.S. dollars or not, energy tariffs in Nigeria are paid in naira, raising currency convertibility issues  while awaiting supply of hard currency, the naira can weaken, eating into potential profits. As a result, the market is dominated mostly by local players more comfortable with holding naira.

Being a landlocked country, importing components into Rwanda is an expensive endeavor, even if most pieces are exempt from value added taxes. At the same time, a strong government presence in the growth of the countrys energy sector can sometimes prove overbearing: in an effort to expedite electrification rates, the government ran a tender for exclusive solar home system distribution rights to the countrys poorest households. Threat of similar tenders in the future is of concern to the countrys off-grid players, and would interfere with what is otherwise an attractive market to do business in.

There is no manufacturing capacity in Senegal for wind turbines or solar panels, so developers must import components when building projects. Utility-scale renewable energy projects are exempt from paying VAT on power production and import duties on substituent components under the latest investment code, but small-scale projects remain subject to VAT of 18% and import duties of 25%. Solar panels are the only exception, subject to a lower tariff of 5%. Obtaining these exemptions and tariff reductions can nevertheless be a lengthy and costly process for developers and companies providing small-scale power. For the last two years, power offtaker Senelec has been in profit, so offtaker risk is now lower. Bureaucratic hurdles are still present but are decreasing as more IPPS enter the market and the launch of Scaling Solar auctions makes it simpler for international companies to enter the space.

The lack of clear policy enablers and a uniform offtake arrangement is the most significant barrier to the Sierra Leone clean energy industry. While energy remains a key social issue, the governments immediate priorities lie in addressing corruption within its own ranks and improving health and wellbeing following the Ebola crisis. The nations weak and limited grid presents challenges for independent power producers to bring capacity to markets, even when the project economics are viable. Additionally, Sierra Leones distinct wet and dry seasons present challenges in planning and operating a system dependent on hydroelectric generation.

Somalia's electricity sector remains almost entirely unregulated, which offers IPPs opportunities to enter the market without needing to compete with a national monopoly. On the other hand, the lack of a national transmission or distribution infrastructure is a major barrier to development of grid-connected projects. The local workforce is also lacking in technical expertise and even construction equipment is in many cases difficult to secure. Although Somaliland is quite stable, the security situation in other areas is also a deterrent to investors and makes it even more difficult to achieve financing.

Investors remain wary of future policy stalemates as well as the offtaker  Eskom  which is now even more financially beleaguered and has yet to demonstrate its support for renewables. Its financial woes continue amid weak power demand, non-payment by municipalities and governance issues. Even though the change of administration bodes well for renewables, there remain vocal opponents to what they label as "expensive" technologies. Tariffs in forthcoming renewables auction rounds may increase as the government imposes tougher local content requirements and there is dwindling space on the grid with good resource potential. One barrier to roofotp PV is the lack of approved mandatory process to govern small-scale embedded generation connecting to the grid.

The lack of a transmission grid poses a serious barrier to both clean energy adoption and wider electrification. Outside of the three largest cities, people largely have to rely on diesel generators if they want access to electricity. The ongoing civil war and disputes within the government means that there is little policy in place to encourage further electrification or the adoption of clean energy. The civil war will also act as a deterrent to foreign investment.

Developers entering the Sudanese market are faced with a number of obstacles, such as the domestic security situation: the countrys western and southern regions remain unstable. In addition to high capex costs due to country risk, import duties on solar equipment are high, reaching rates of as much as 60%. As with other countries in the region, matters are not helped by low customer confidence in PV systems stemming from a lack of reputable solar companies in the market. The devolution of grid extensions to regional authorities impedes long-term planning and affords little visibility on future transmission projects, which ultimately leads to them being completed in a haphazard manner.

An issue holding back investment in power plant projects is the high offtaker risk caused by Tanescos huge debt. Fundamentally, retail electricity rates are set too low to unlock generation opportunities upstream. Although Tanzania has an import-duty exemption for PV equipment under the East African Community, the off-grid solar sector in particular is facing challenges of inconsistent policy implementation on the ground. Some tax officers have limited understanding of energy equipment, including solar home systems, leading to unnecessary tax payments.

The country has limited energy-value-chain infrastructure, as no projects of scale have been developed so far. The new energy law has reduced import duties and tariffs, and encourages foreign capital to invest in Togo. Other than a steep learning curve ahead, there are no major political or economic risks in the country. Furthermore, the offtaker has a solid record of delivering payments accordingly. The national effort and emphasis on the energy sector development, carried by renewables, suggests bureaucracy should be transparent and in favor of project developers.

Uncertainties around political instability and relatively recent law (2015) that allowed IPPs in the market are the main barriers for international investors. This indicates that support from development organizations in form of concessional finance might be required to change the market risk perception. Tunisia has a 0% import tax for wind and solar products from the EU and 30% for products from outside of the EU. The country also imposes a 19% VAT on wind turbines, towers, blades and PV panels, and 7% for inverters.

Being a landlocked country, Uganda must import components via overland shipping from the port of Mombasa, Kenya  an expensive and time-consuming endeavor. While many of these components are VAT-exempt, there remains a lack of clarity of what constitutes exemption and what doesnt. Uganda is also rife with corruption: many donor agencies have tightened the reins on investment or established more stringent targets that the Ministry of Energy & Mines and other state-owned players need to hit to activate further funding. Umeme remains both a credible and well-run company, but uncertainty around its ability to renew its distribution concessions in 2025 will fuel investor apprehension in the coming years.

Zambia, along with most other Sub-Saharan countries, has an import duty exemption on all renewable energy type equipment and machinery for agriculture, aquaculture and mining. Zesco currently controls all generation, transmission and distribution of electricity in Zambia, but its financial position is not considered stable and it receives a sizeable amount of funding from government. The joint IDA and IFC Scaling Solar project aims to address Zambias current power shortages by increasing the reliability and security of electricity supplies.  Their presence has a significant leveraging impact and de-risks projects through off-taker risk cover, helping the country attract investors and lenders, and lower project tariffs. Power Africa has been working with African governments and private sector partners to remove barriers that impede sustainable energy development.

The government is taking steps to improve the ease of doing business in the country and trying to open up it up to more foreign investment. With relatively outdated infrastructure, the country struggles with poor roads and, at times, disrupted electricity supply. Solar equipment (including solar lanterns) can be imported duty free but are still subject to 15% VAT. Countrywide, a lack of awareness and understanding of clean energy products may hinder short-term uptake.

The energy sector in Afghanistan faces issues such as funding gaps, a lack of expertise, a lack of reliable historical data, weak public awareness about environmental issues, high interest rates (almost 15% as compared to less than 5% in European countries), and security concerns that result in high premiums for installing and commissioning projects. Moreover, DABS charges almost four times more for electricity produced through off-grid plants because of higher generation costs. Also, there is no offtaker that is obliged to purchase the electricity from renewables projects, which discourages the use of off-grid electricity and increases the offtaker risk.

Armenia has taken steps to build a domestic supply chain for PV equipment and services. The government has granted licenses for small systems (0.51MW) to encourage local providers to develop expertise. Licenses will be increased to 5MW in the next few years, to prepare them to participate in future auction rounds. There are currently no special duties on renewable equipment, and no local content requirements.
