The process for building and connecting renewable energy has been fairly straightforward, and the ministry has been offering supply agreements of 15-20 years. However, there is significant political risk in the country, as the government was very suddenly replaced in May 2018. There is currently little clarity on which energy policies the new administration will elect to keep, though most had broad support when they were introduced.

As is the case for many countries in the region, Azerbaijan's economy, budget and credit rating rely greatly on the price of oil and gas. In periods of lower oil prices, the country has slashed investment in other industries and subsidizedhydrocarbon use to promote the sector. This adds another level of complexity to project finance as the government is a guarantor to many projects.Over the last decade, the government has shuffled agencies and changed their mandates, leaving no clear authority to enact policies for renewables. Nonetheless, Azerbaijan has a positive reputation for supporting foreign investment in the energy sector.

The slow pace of land acquisitions and delays in getting the necessary approvals are major barriers to investment in renewables in the country. A 200MW PV project being developed by SunEdison is on the verge of being cancelled due to permitting delays. Another 60MW wind project being evaluated by U.S.-DK Green Energy is also running behind schedule. The country does not have a history of operating large renewable projects but if any curtailments do happen then private IPPs will be the first ones to face it. Bangladesh does not have a well-developed domestic supply chain for renewable energy projects. Most equipment and technical expertise is imported, which increases the project costs compared to neighboring India.

The absence of regulatory clarity is a significant obstacle to renewable energy development in Cambodia. Recently, EDC proposed a new rate structure to allow for grid-connected, small-scale solar at commercial and industrial sites, but the rates capacity charge is essentially workable only for very large facilities that run round-the-clock. Many expect the tariff to be adjusted, but there is little urgency on EDCs side. For utility-scale renewables, it can be difficult to obtain a generation license, which is required to export power to the grid; at the same time, EDC has little experience with PPAs for intermittent resources and is not eager to incorporate them into the system.

Chinas strong local manufacturing capacity for wind and solar leaves little space for overseas players to compete. Even though the escalating trade war with the U.S. looms large on growth, its impact on Chinas wind and solar developments, batteries and electric vehicles has been limited. The government is opening up more of the energy sector  such as the distribution grid and electric vehicles  for domestic private and foreign investment. But these and other policy changes have given rise to short-term uncertainties around the speed of government-allowed growth in wind and solar, and questions about where in the liberalized retail power market the incumbent grid companies will allow for competition.

Land acquisition and transmission connectivity are two recurring challenges faced by developers in India. Due to this, IPPs have been requesting the government to extend deadlines for projects won in auctions. Aside from the cost of debt increasing and a depreciating rupee, cost pressures have further increased with the government's decision to impose safeguard duties on solar PV cells and modules. This is expected to trigger a series of renegotiations to revise realized tariffs in recent auctions and slow down solar rooftop projects.

Indonesia has a history of implementing strict rules on local content in the power sector. In 2017, solar companies were required to use at least 43% local content in goods and services used in the plant. Project development costs are also higher than in neighboring markets due to inconsistent tax incentives and high property prices that reduce the chances of renewable developers undercutting the costs of existing generation. In addition, the Indonesian rupiah has seen high volatility against the U.S. dollar, which is a concern for foreign players if the project revenue or costs are in local currency. The need to engage with multiple government agencies at local and national level is another hurdle for project developers. Dependence of PLN, which offtakes power from all the grid-connected power plants, on government subsidies to stay afloat has resulted in higher off-taker credit risk.

The greatest challenge for renewables investors is how to finance a project, given the lack of liquidity in local banks and limited loan maturity. Local banks that are not experienced in renewables will likely require a 12-15% interest rate on loans denominated in the local currency, with a 4-5-year tenor  much too short for a typical renewable energy project. There is also currency risk, considering that tengi (KZT) depreciated from $0.0083 in 2008 to $0.0031 in 2017. Shipping of wind turbines and solar PV requires land transport, pricier than marine shipping. Apart from issues related to financing and costing, some developers in the country have also encountered small barriers in terms of land preparation and technical adaptation. Some delays of permitting and engineering should be expected.

There are numerous barriers to renewable energy development in Kyrgyzstan, and organic market growth remains unlikely. While the government has introduced some support mechanisms for small hydro, policy support for wind and solar is nonexistent. The industry is too nascent for foreign developers to enter the market and there are a number of barriers to doing business in Kyrgyzstan, such as unclear land allocation regulations, inconsistent legal frameworks, insufficient local expertise and weak enforceability of commercial contracts. International development banks are working to tackle some of these market challenges.

At present, project development in Laos is effectively on hold as the government assesses the risk of its existing and under-construction hydroelectric fleet, in response to the dam collapse at the Xe-pian Xe-namnoy project in July 2018. The government is unlikely to prioritize solar projects during this time. Meanwhile, offtaker risk remains a significant obstacle to new projects of all types: projects with an EDL offtake are considered unbankable due to the utilitys financial difficulties. Projects for the Thai market have been more successful because EGAT, Thailands utility, is considered a credit-worthy offtaker; however, as EGATs supply has slowly caught up with electricity demand, its interest in Lao projects has levelled off. This means many new projects will likely face an EDL or EVN (Vietnams utility) offtake, which will make financing more difficult.

Renewable assets in the country must be majority-owned by a local company, and feed-in tariff projects do receive bonus tariffs if components are sourced locally. There are no import levies on components, but a new service and sales tax was introduced for manufacturers in September. Though Malaysia experienced a major upheaval in government in the May 2018 general election, political instability is unlikely to impede the nation's push toward clean energy. Land for large-scale projects is a growing constraint as much of the available acreage is high-value agricultural land. Multiple authorities oversee different aspects of the renewable energy industry, occasionally creating blurred lines of accountability on renewable energy targets and goals.

Challenges lie ahead as the country works to clean its power supply. Existing coal-fired plants have low marginal costs to operate, and demand for additional capacity appears stagnant and easily satisfied by a few of the potential projects in the pipeline. Mongolia has no manufacturing capacity for solar or wind components. Imports of such equipment can be exempted from duties and VAT, based on their application and pre-clearance at customs. Foreign and private investment is welcome in the energy sector; but currency instability poses a risk given the tugriks history of depreciation. Policy instability, such as the upcoming revision of the renewable energy law and local administrative inefficiency, is also a potential investment barrier. Last but not least, Mongolia has four relatively independent grid regions, which adversely affect the wide dispatch/transmission of renewable energy.

A lack of institutional frameworks and governing capacity to implement policies and rules are the key barriers to scaling up project development. Currently, there is no legal framework or institutional system for granting PPAs. This does not encourage competition that is critical for driving down project cost. Another challenge is finance. Domestic banks are not able to provide finance for projects. The lending market is only just moving from an over-drafted loan market to a term loan market. In the past, all projects were financed by the government and/or multilateral concessional financing. The countrys power sector development is hampered by severe budgetary constraints and the non-existence of conventional commercial or project financing for power projects.

Nepal aims to increase foreign investments in the energy sector. Currently, the country has not been able to attract much of such investments mainly because of the high risks related to the offtaker, curtailment and foreign exchange, as well as inadequate infrastructure and cumbersome government procedures within the energy sector. Projects under construction are often put on hold because of natural disasters in the country. Products must be approved by the AEPC's Renewable Energy Test Station to qualify for subsidies and a VAT exemption  but market participants view this as helpful for upholding quality standards. All these factors create an unfavorable environment for attracting capital for energy projects.

The new government campaigned on an anti-corruption agenda. Initial statements from Prime Minister Khan underline the need to break from the past, within limits, which indicates that a pragmatic approach will be followed. Nevertheless, the country is in a volatile region (with Iran and Afghanistan as neighbors) with a currency that has lost significant value since the beginning of the year.  There have been at least three devaluations in the last nine months. There is uncertainty about another IMF bailout. Taking on more debt from China would come with its own share of risks.

The current FiT program for solar and wind has reached capacity and wont be expanded. The project permitting process may involve dozens of agencies, causing some developers to wait over five years for approval. Utilities have limited the technologies they will contract for. Legal obstacles have made it difficult to provide renewable power for behind the meter projects and areas with limited power. All of this hinders setting up renewable microgrids and net metering and entering into PSAs. Limitations on foreign ownership, a lack of transmission capacity and the Philippines archipelago geography create additional challenges to developing a project. Other initiatives offer the hope that some of these barriers will be addressed. The Green Energy Option program will require utilities to facilitate renewable PPAs to give deliver renewable power to end-users. The RPS will also push utilities to increase their sourced share of clean power and set up a market to trade renewable energy credits.

The market is limited in terms of scale and the slow pace of market liberalization. Development led by the government and public bodies present challenges in terms of timing and requires patience for investor looking to deploy capital to opportunities in the country. Furthermore, the lack of transparency around the PV tenders and the reasons for successful bidders being awarded contracts is a barrier to new entrants hoping to understand the market.

With its limited area and population, Sri Lanka could be an ideal market for electric vehicles. The budget offered some tax exemptions for setting up EV charging stations, even as a plan for electrifying mobility is being worked on. Also in the pipeline are a host of pilot projects in what are being described as "exotic technologies": large-scale battery storage, ocean energy, small wind power vertical-type systems and hybrid power systems combining solar, wind and batteries. Though the aspirational target of 100% clean energy is often heard, the fact is that new coal plants are part of the new long-term energy plan, despite opposition from the regulator.

Regulators do not allow Taiwan companies to import solar cells and wind turbines from mainland China, slowing down the decrease in project capex and levelized costs brought by the mainland markets massive scale. Local so-called Nimby movements, taking the forms of environmental protectionism and land transfer challenges, are significant barriers for project implementation. Taipower has modified the feed-in tariff rules at least twice before: in 2010 to shorten the commissioning deadline for solar auction winners, and then in 2012-13 to renegotiate tariffs with thermal IPPs. These changes provide concerns over whether Taipower will retrospectively lower the feed-in tariff rates for offshore wind and other technologies.

There are numerous barriers to renewable energy development in Tajikistan, and market growth beyond the governments goals remains unlikely. While the government has introduced some polices to support the renewables industry, it has not introduced a feed-in tariff or auctions program. In addition to the countrys isolation and lack of domestic renewables manufacturing capacity, there are other issues such as the high cost of credit (which is approximately 24-26% APR) and the lack of interest from foreign developers in entering the market. The countrys regulatory environment is also complex, and Tajikistan ranks near the bottom of the World Banks ease of doing business ranking.

Thailand's power generation market is open to foreign investment. There is currently a halt on utility-scale project applications in 2016 causing a lack of large-scale opportunities in the country. Developers in Thailand are currently waiting for a revised PDP, expected to be released within 2018. Development activities are generally on hold until the new directive is announced by the government. Wind projects previously suffered a setback through the revocation of a land lease for Thep Sathit Wind Farm, which was developed by Energy Absolute. However, this has been resolved and wind projects have seen steady progress since.

Turkmenistan is largely a closed economy, not far removed from its Soviet predecessor. Foreign investors are subject to strict limitations, including local content rules, setting up joint ventures with domestic companies and negotiating ad hoc agreements per project in the absence of set regulations. Not surprisingly, bureaucracyis notoriouslyconvoluted and very transactional.Investing in the country is high risk. The Central Bank typically guarantees contracts but it is not independent of the treasury, and the health of both these organizations is tied to the price of gas.

There are no explicit policies limiting foreign investment or ownership. Conversely, there are no set rules regulating renewables, interconnection and tariffs. This creates an environment of uncertainty as well as increasingtransaction costs as each deal and PPA must be negotiatedindividually. To date, the single known PPA has provisions for curtailment and offtaker risk as the government is the guarantor for Uzbekenergo. Naturally this mitigates risk but that should be considered along with the fact that Uzbekistan is only now planning to get its first ever credit rating.

Vietnam has a manufacturing base for PV modules to meet foreign demand. Most of the manufacturers import solar PV cells and pay 0% import duties, assemble them in Vietnam and export them due to lack of domestic demand. There is high dispatch risk as EVN has no obligation to purchase electricity while there is grid availability. The result of heavily subsidized retail tariffs can be seen in EVNs financials. The offtaker risk is high as there is no government guarantee against EVN.

The biggest barrier to new renewable capacity is offtaker risk. As part of the power sector reform the distribution system operator and supplier of electricity for regulated tariff customers, OSHEE, will act as the offtaker for new renewable projects. It is currently undergoing a reform, using a loan from the World Bank, to reduce its debt burden. At fault are low tariffs, electricity theft, and technical losses in the distribution system. OSHEE's perilous financial position means there is high offtaker risk and any PPA will most likely be signed in conjunction with one or several government or World Bank guarantees. Proposed PPAs are for 15 years and, in 2018, grid codes for connecting to the transmission and distribution grids were adopted. The Renewable Energy Law details that generators are responsible for the cost of connecting to the grid, while the grid operator is responsible for any costs needed to strengthen the grid as a result of the new capacity.

The countrys highly decentralized institutions and fragmented governance structure have long hampered the liberalization of the national electricity sector. Within southeastern Europe, BiH is consistently ranked as the worst performer in reforming its power market. A lack of communication among different government departments and tortuous licensing procedures complicate project development. Matters are worsened by the lack of awareness regarding renewable energy throughout the general population, reducing the political pressure to promote its deployment. In addition, the three public utilities are self-sustaining, but recent years have seen the deterioration of their financial results due to poor hydraulic conditions and ageing thermal assets. Curtailment is not an issue given the low level of variable renewables deployment to date.

Georgia has few barriers to foreign investment and development. There is little domestic expertise in wind and solar, so most developers partner with a foreign business for equipment supply and construction. The political risk to new projects is low, as each one is considered individually as a proposal from the developer. New projects are virtually guaranteed a grid connection, though the operator can negotiate with developers on the location, to avoid grid constraints. Generators receive 10-year PPAs for all of their generation in the winter months. During the summer they can export their power to other countries through Georgias significant interconnection. The new wholesale market offers PPAs with a 15-year term.

A key obstacle in Macedonia is the large number of institutions involved in handling procedures and licensing, in addition to the lack of coordination among the bodies involved. There is no one-stop shop overseeing all aspects of project development, but recent years have seen progress being made in streamlining application processes. Having been defined by legislation, the timetable for handling applications is clear  the average time for getting decision on applications is between one and two months. Offtaker risk is minimal, and curtailment is a non-issue given the low levels of variable renewables capacity connected to the grid.

Climbing local content requirements, unpredictable currency fluctuations and forecasts for flat electricity demand remain significant barriers to organic renewable energy market growth in Russia. While about 5GW of renewables is already in the pipeline and domestic renewables manufacturing capacity is ramping up, large-scale deployment of renewables outside the auction program is unlikely. Fossil fuels dominate Russia's electricity sector, accounting for over 60% of the countrys power generation, and the government is in no hurry to displace its national energy giants or ratify the Paris Agreement.

There are no obvious barriers to entry for clean energy development in Serbia. Technology capacity caps, as part of the feed-in tariff design, are the biggest challenge facing developers. Since they can secure a preliminary approval (termed 'temporary privileged power producer' status) into the capacity budget it leaves few opportunities for new developers. However, opportunities may arise once the feed-in tariff closes at the end of 2018 and the government looks towards feed-in premiums and auctions. Offtaker risk is low thanks to a robust PPA design that was included in the PPA package as part of the secondary legislation following Serbia's 2014 Energy Act.

Local content requirements for renewables in Turkey are high, but the country benefits from a well-developed value chain in most sectors. Policy risk is currently a major barrier to new project development, as pre-licenses for development are only allocated via auction. Energy policy overall has remained stable as President Erdogan consolidates his hold on power, but associated currency volatility raises offtaker risks. Turkish utilities already have considerable dollar-denominated debt, while distribution companies are required to pay the generous feed-in tariff in dollars as well. While the lira has fallen against the dollar, offtaker risk has grown accordingly. There is a risk of cuts to the feed-in tariff as the cost of the subsidy grows in relative terms.

Ukraine now offers a premium on top of the feed-in tariff for the use of locally produced parts in renewables projects. There is, however, little in the way of local manufacturing. Imported equipment and goods for renewables projects is exempt from duties. There are restrictions on the use of agricultural land for renewables projects and on the production of bioethanol by foreign companies.  There are some untested rules around the ownership of strategically important energy assets by foreign companies. Probably of greater concern is the level of political risk  although this has been declining, investors still face financing issues because of perceptions of instability in the country, even though the trend in Ukraine is toward more transparency. Currency risk has also been a barrier to renewables deployment. The administrative burden on foreign companies is still more onerous than for local companies. There is no curtailment risk in Ukraine, but grid connections are still obtained through variable procedures.

Despite Macri government initiatives to boost clean energy and cut emissions, Argentina has a long road ahead to achieve all its targets. Efforts to rebuild international investor confidence are a work in progress, as the country continues to navigate macroeconomic crises. The current crisis will likely hurt the ability of projects to obtain financing, especially for the most recent auction, RenovAr Round 2, and upcoming mini auction, RenovAr MiniRen 3.0. Constrained transmission and distribution networks stand to inhibit wind and solar build. While Argentina has taken important steps to foster its clean energy industry, important barriers remain.

A lack of clear incentives for renewable energy constrain opportunities in the electricity market in Bolivia. Nationalization of the energy sector beginning in 2010, which reversed privatization undertaken more than a decade earlier, has concentrated generation, transmission, and distribution within state entities, effectively eliminating competition. The countrys heavy reliance on natural gas-fired generation and subsidized power prices also limits competition and suppresses market signals for investment.

In October 2018, Brazil elected former military officer and far-right politician Jair Messias Bolsonaro of the Social Liberal Party (PSL) as its 42nd president. After an extremely polarizing campaign, the results represent a repudiation of traditional politics in the country and of entrenched corruption, as well as a reaction to high levels of violent crime and ongoing economic woes. Bolsonaros focus on the energy sector as a key driver of growth and development, as well as his emphasis on partially privatizing state-owned companies and regaining investor confidence could mean a bright future for renewables in the country. However, the former military mans security ties may present barriers to new investment and limit privatization plans.

The main barrier for renewables development remains insufficient interconnection between the two sub-systems. Interconnection is critical for enabling solar energy, in particular, produced in the northern SING sub-system and home to the best solar resources, to flow to the center of the country, where population and demand are concentrated. Curtailment of renewables began in Chile in August 2015. Since then, wind and solar power have been curtailed at increasing rates, though progress is being made on development of new transmission infrastructure aimed at easing this. In addition to the SIC-SING interconnection commissioned in 2017, Chile is building the 550kV Cardones-Polpaico transmission line that will also connect the two systems, expected to be commissioned by December 2018.

Investors are uncertain of the overall potential of Colombias clean energy market, given ambiguity around long-term planning scenarios, the slow pace and limited effect of policies adopted to date, and modest official targets. Colombia has no state-owned utility with which to sign long term PPAs; non-regulated industrial consumers are allowed to participate in the competitive market and to sign negotiated, long-term PPAs at unregulated prices. These PPAs can be entered into between the generator and non-regulated user directly. Colombia has an electrification rate of 99 percent, but areas that lack access overlap with former conflict zones.  Provision of basic services, such as access to electricity, was agreed to as part of the peace accords. Reaching the Ministry of Mines and Energys goal of 100 percent electrification is therefore tied to the broader process of reconciliation and will involve navigating relations with local communities.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Costa Rica are low. In 2010, Costa Rica established import tax exemption for imported and local equipment and materials used in the renewable energy industry. Law 51, which came in force in 2016, authorized power purchase agreements (PPA) for up to 20 years.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Dominican Republic are low. An incentive regime for the development of clean energy has been in place since May 2007, consistent with the national energy plan (the Plan Energtico Nacional, or PEN). It includes an investment tax credit, external financing, tax reductions, and exemptions from taxes on the transfer of industrialized goods and services, as well as from import duties. Renewable energy generators have dispatch priority and open access to transmission and distribution.

Ecuador faces difficulties to deploy more renewable projects due to key characteristics of its power market. A combination of very low electricity tariffs and a low power demand produces a challenging environment for project developers. Currently, the country is able to meet peak power demand via its hydro capacity alone.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in El Salvador are low. Under decree 462 of 2007, El Salvador grants tax incentives for development of renewable energy sources, including 10 years of import tax exemption to machines and equipment, and income tax breaks for renewable energy projects. The incentive is valid for the first 5 years of the operation of projects between 10 and 20 MW, and 10 years for projects of less than 10MW capacity. Furthermore, state-owned Empresa Transmisora de El Salvador (ETESAL) is required to guarantee priority dispatch to electricity generated from renewable sources.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Guatemala are low. Tax incentives, implemented in 2003, promote the development of renewable energy generation capacity. These include import tax breaks for machines, equipment, materials and inputs for investment and construction; value-added tax break for machines, equipment, materials and inputs for investment and construction; income tax breaks; and industrial tax breaks valid for a period of 10 years from the date the plant starts operating.

EDHs continued mismanagement has long plagued the development of Haitis power sector. The state utility is on its last legs financially, with shortfalls such that it relies on government subsidies to maintain its operations. Losses are estimated at $200 million per year, 4% of the national budget. Connection costs charged by the electricity company are prohibitively high at $65. Moreover, EDH has proven itself unable to manage the generation it currently sources for its grid operations, with its dispatching system crude and inefficient.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Honduras are low. PPAs with renewable energy generators last for up to 20 years, but cannot be renewed following expiration. Honduras grants import, income, and sales tax exemption to renewable energy generators.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Jamaica are low. Consumers with their own generation facilities may participate in Jamaica Public Services net metering pilot program. They receive JPSs avoided-cost rate plus 15% for electricity delivered to the national grid. As of May 2015, a total of 118 consumers with renewable energy self-generation facilities were connected to the grid. Jamaica has a zero rated value added tax (VAT) for components needed to build a solar or wind project.

While Mexico's nearly-completed energy reform is increasing private participation in generation, the market remains highly concentrated in the hands of CFE, the state-owned, formerly vertically integrated utility. Diversification of certain areas of the competitive landscape, such as in qualified supply, is likely to take time. Investors are also wary of environmental and other regulatory risks in some areas of Mexico due to land disputes with indigenous communities, which remain an important barrier for project development in the country and a primary reason for project construction delays in specific regions, such as Yucatan. Additionally, there is some uncertainty around the CELS market ahead of its entry into force in 2018 and in particular, whether there will be sufficient clean energy capacity to generate quantities of CELs needed to comply with future requirements.

The lack of active substantial policy support programs is likely to stymie renewables deployment in Nicaragua. The exception is the series of tax incentives to ease the clean energy project development process. Import tax and VAT exemptions for machines, equipment, materials and inputs for investment and construction, including the sub-transmission lines required to transport electricity to the national grid, the Sistema Interconectado Nacional (SIN). The incentives, introduced in 2005, were initially to be in force for a period of 10 years and expire in May 2015. In December 2017, the national assembly approved the law reform in which extends the fiscal benefits until 2023.

Formal barriers to development of renewables in Panama are low. Since 2004, Panama has had tax incentives for the construction, operation and maintenance of clean energy projects. The policy grants clean energy projects with an installed capacity less than or equal to 10MW the ability to enter direct power purchase agreements (PPA) with the distribution utility as long as power sold does not exceed 15% of the distribution companys maximum demand.

From Paraguays total 59.6GWh generated in 2017, only 27% was directed to national consumption; the rest is exported to Brazil and Argentina. The Paraguayan power market does not have private players. The average level of import duties for components to build a solar or wind project is 14%. The average level of value added tax (VAT) for components needed to build a solar or wind project is 10%.

Perus energy consumption has been stable for the last three years, with an average of 1% increase in demand over the past two years. There are indications the country is oversupplied with power assets, which would be the main explanation for the hiatus in renewable auctions for the past three years. In terms of incentives, Peru does not charge import taxes for common renewable equipment such as wind turbines and PV panels, and charges an average of 18% of value added taxation.

The main barrier for Uruguayan clean development is the lack of demand growth. The country has deployed a significant amount of capacity relatively to its small market, and now, there is little room for more additions. Despite no sign of new tenders in the near future, the country still holds renewable energy incentives, which includes a value added tax exemption for wind generation and income tax reduction for clean energy and energy efficiency projects. Retail consumers may apply to UTEs net metering program and receive credits for clean energy generation delivered to the grid.

The Ministry of Finance guarantees all financial obligations of the offtaker (the Egyptian Electric Transmission Company, EETC) under the PPA for projects over 20MW. The offtaker does not have a history of non-payment but it does have a history of delayed payments. In the longer term, there is a question mark over what happens when EETC is no longer a subsidiary of the Egyptian Electricity Holding Company  as is envisaged as part of the power market reform  and therefore may not be covered by the sovereign guarantee. The local currency has hovered around 17.6-17.9 pounds per dollar since 2Q 2017  a far cry from its level before it was floated (at some 8-9 pounds). Overall, some administrative processes could be streamlined, the government needs to implement international standards and there is a lack of awareness about renewables among consumers.

Political risk and the absence of incentives deter investment in the renewable sector. The Ministry of Energy has tried to incentivize foreign developers to enter the renewables market with tax incentives. Projects in areas defined by the National Investment Council (NIC) are exempt from taxes and fees for 10 years from the date of completion. When the developer adds capacity to the plant, the period restarts for an additional 10 years. The NIC can also extend the period of exemption up to 15 years if the Iraqi investor share of the project exceeds 50%. Equipment imported for the construction of the project is exempt from customs duties, as are raw materials imported for the commercial operation of the plant. Following failed tender processes in 2011, the ministry in 2014 entered into PPAs with three Iraqi IPPs. Difficulties transferring land to the projects, applying the grid code and complying with environmental laws have delayed the process.

Jordan introduced a 35% local content requirement for solar and wind projects in 2018. The requirement applies to the total value of each project. The solar sector in Jordan is well established, with multiple local firms capable of producing panels, cables and steel structures for solar projects. However, wind projects are likely to struggle to meet the 35% threshold, as there are no major component manufacturers in Jordan. All equipment used in renewable energy projects are exempt from import and sales tax. The National Energy Strategy also provides a 100% exemption from income tax over 10 years for independent power producers generating renewable energy. The tax break incentivizes private sector investment in renewables and receives backing from project developers.

Kuwait has a very stable government; law is transparent and often available in English; and the country maintains a strong credit rating, with high liquidity in the domestic banking sector. The government is striving to attract foreign investment as a way to grow the local economy, create jobs, and promote technology transfer. However, the effort to grow the share of renewables in generation lacks a consolidated approach. Effort fragmentation is common, with the work split between research institutes, the government and the private sector, which undermines the development of a national strategy to meet the countrys energy target.

In some regards, barriers to renewable investment in Lebanon remain low; so far no tenders have stipulated local content requirements, there are no restrictions on foreign investment, and renewable energy equipment does not attract import duties or tariffs (but it is subject to Lebanese sales tax). The country has some manufacturing capacity, but most renewables equipment will likely remain imported. In contrast to this, considerable red tape surrounds the current IPP tendering procedures and political considerations can increase the time taken to reach decisions. Finally, offtaker risk could be considerable, given the poor financial situation of EDL, in addition to curtailment risks in the form of transmission and distribution constraints in the underfunded grid

Quotas set through labor nationalization measures designed to reduce the economys reliance on immigrant workers may slow down project implementation. Yet such omanization rates are not significant enough to prove a major hurdle to future renewables deployment. Although import duties are not waived for renewable energy equipment, these are relatively low, at less than 10%. The country has few barriers to overcome, with a well-developed regulatory body in the AER overseeing the sectors development. The launch of a spot market in 2019-2020 may change things, but there is little in the way of offtaker risk at present  the well-capitalized OPWP procures all electricity generated by IPPs.

Several Saudi institutions question whether Saudi Arabia's projected electricity demand growth will materialize. Energy efficiency improvements, possible slowing population growth and recent price increases for petrol and electricity may ease electricity demand growth, and it is unclear what may then happen to demand for renewables. There are ambitious plans to develop solar, including a proposed $200 billion, 200GW venture with Softbank. Still, local content rules of up to 30% may hinder these plans. There appears to be a concerted effort to support renewable energy development in Saudi Arabia, but the process of actually developing and building projects is a prolonged process.

Renewable energy projects face few hurdles in the U.A.E. The sector benefits from strong political support, with the state positioning itself as the regional champion of renewable energy by hosting the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) and underwriting domestic heavyweights such as Masdar. Offtaker risk is low and there is little chance of curtailment presenting an issue. Efforts are being made to interconnect transmission networks run by the four power authorities with a view to improving the grids ability to cope with increased intermittency once solar generation begins ramping up.

Resource potential, especially for PV, is high in the West Bank and Gaza, but in practice Israel's role in the Palestinian territories is a barrier to renewables development. Import of components to the Gaza Strip requires military authorization, and critical shortages of land make rooftop PV the only practical solution. In the West Bank, PV installations have been subject to demolition or confiscation by the Israeli military in cases where building permits are disputed. Offtaker risk is also an issue as retailers operate at a loss and PETL, the TSO which purchases electricity from Israel, remains in debt to the Israel Electric Company.
